<HEADLINE>Please mind the gaps</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SUE TRANTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geologists are digging in at Glasgow sites for, as SUE TRANTER explains, moves
are being made to map the city's mine workings
ENGINEERS are busy drilling at a number of residential sites around Glasgow . .
. to fill in a few holes on the city's geological map.
The British Geological Survey, which has been charting Britain's foundations
since 1835, states that of all the major cities in Scotland, Glasgow has the
biggest potential for underground problems.
So far, recording Glasgow's roots has been an incomplete even haphazard
exercise, according to Alan Redfern at the City Council. Pollokshields, the
West End and Ruchill are locations for drilling and Redfern is anxious to
reassure residents who live nearby that there is no cause for alarm.
``The work is just to give us more precise knowledge. It will help us protect
against any potential risk. We cannot apply for future funding to put right any
problems if we don't know what's there.''
Uncharted mine workings are a particular concern and work is currently in hand
to fill in a previously unknown shaft in Bellahouston Park that recently opened
up. A total of #6,000,000 has been spent consolidating ground at 40 tenements
near Queen's Park by pouring in hundreds of gallons of cement.
``Our records are scanty,'' says Redfern, ``though from the turn of the century
pretty good records have been kept. But 150 to 200 years ago, people just mined
where they liked and it was often quite close to the surface.''
But it's not just coal workings that have caused problems. Recent subsidence in
a front garden in Craigton, led to the discovery of an iron ore mine.
Iron ore already figures on the geological map. Its presence is marked along
with a grid of lines denoting serious coal mining in the Possil area.
Kelvinside has its fair share of seams, but most of them have shifted due to
the movement of ancient fault lines that crisscross the city.
To consult the geological map of Glasgow, head straight for the Science and
Technology section of the Mitchell Library where you might also find a kindly
assistant who just happens to have a degree in geology to help you make head
and tail of it all.
Dr Stewart Monro of the British Geoglogical Survey in Edinburgh says the map is
constantly being revised and that bore holes are an important source of
knowledge.
``Glasgow expanded on the basis of its coal, lime and iron stone from the
medieval period onwards. It expanded on its own dereliction and a lot shafts
and workings were abandoned. The mid land valley was very productive from
Alloa, Hamilton and down to Ayr and we are now wrestling with a legacy of the
mining past,'' he explains.
``It is only relatively recently that companies had to officially declare their
mining intentions, there are probably still many papers lying around in
lawyers' offices that could help us chart old workings.
``Our predictions can never be foolproof, they are based on the best statement
we can make at the time but we are constantly revising our information.''
That revision has been made easier by the advance of computer technology and
the BGS are holding maps as images on screen allowing for more frequent
changes. The public map is only updated every 40 to 50 years so it could take
some time before information from the new drilling is published. However the
BGS in Edinburgh will advise anyone direct with updated information.
</TEXT>
