<HEADLINE>A system stands accused</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sarah Nelson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
After Cornton Vale prison's latest suicide Sarah Nelson asks three vital
questions
AS HMP Cornton Vale reels from its third consecutive recent suicide of a remand
prisoner (Joanne O'Reilly, who was addicted to heroin), public debate has
concentrated remarkably on the system's failure at the very end of these
women's lives. Yet this may be unimportant - a red herring which damagingly
diverts courts, prisons, social work, media and public from the real issues
these suicides raise.
To home in on last-ditch gatekeeping is the easy option. Such gatekeeping is
the way prison authorities or police understandably watch their backs: through
its mistakes, individual staff are found to blame for personal and social
tragedies.
Did someone fail to watch these unhappy teenagers every 15 minutes precisely,
to ensure they didn't hang themselves? Did someone fail to spot from the notes
that this prisoner was a suicide risk? Such questions are also the stuff of
fatal accident inquiries, though well-conducted FAIs will draw wider lessons,
too.
Physically stopping people committing suicide is important for prison
reputations, avoiding major public embarrassment. It is hopelessly, laughably
inadequate for the distressed prisoner, and often just a temporary frustration,
later resolved with minimal publicity in an alleyway or squalid flat. It
seriously diverts attention from the questions that matter.
Should these people have been remanded in jail at all, and were they a danger
to the public? If they already had serious problems in their lives had they
received any of the help they actually needed, either outside or inside prison?
And, crucially, do features of the prison regime itself, especially the remand
regime and the very restrictions and isolation of the strip-cell and suicide
watch, actually encourage many prisoners to despair or ``crack up''? After all,
they might do in the rest of us.
Given the recent rise in jail suicides these three questions are important for
all prisons, but particularly for Cornton Vale if, as some reports have
claimed, an astonishing 80%-plus of the inmates pose a potential suicide risk.
The penal and courts system have to ask urgently why this should be, and how
far court disposals and the prison regime - criticised in detail in last year's
Inspectorate report - might be relevant to it.
It is extraordinary how few hard questions have been asked about the first, not
the last, stage of the process for these three young people. Why were they
remanded in custody in the first place when their offences were relatively
trivial, especially since Kelly Holland and Arlene Elliot were only 17?
Why is there such an absence in Scotland of female bail accommodation, and a
dearth of research figures or debate on comparative rates of remand in custody
for young men and young women? Are female remands forced into the penal system
earlier and more often, through lack of alternatives and various assumptions or
prejudices about female offenders?
As Tayside social work director Peter Bates told a Sacro conference on women
offenders this year: ``We suffer from a sad deficiency in research. The Central
Research Unit has decided that all its projects must now address the gender
issue, but as yet in Scotland we have no in-depth study to compare with the
thematic report by HM Inspectorate of Probation into women offenders . . .
there is still room in Scotland for much more work reflecting women's
experience.''
It is also unclear how much has changed since Sue Gutteridge carried out her
research in Cornton Vale more than 15 years ago. Then, she was particularly
struck at the very high rates of remand in custody for under-21s. This directs
critical questions on to court decisions, but she also noted in the book, The
Imprisonment of Women, Cornton Vale's own failure, even by its social workers,
to recognise prisoners' basic needs for proper legal advice.
Observing five prisoners admitted one morning on remand, she wrote: ``If they
had no lawyer, there appeared to be no provision for getting them one . . . the
question of appealing against remand in custody was never raised, even though
it was difficult to see why any of the five women in question had been so
remanded. All were on trivial charges, except one who hadn't been charged at
all . . .
``The rigidly hierarchical structure of Cornton Vale discouraged any
challenging of the decisions of authority, and the prison's conception of a
`therapeutic' establishment encouraged the view that women had been put there
for their own good. The crime itself, and the justice of the sentence, were
less relevant.''
Back in 1987, the World Group on Bail and Custodial Remand set up by Sacro
urged the general principle that bail should be granted unless the prosecution
proved there was sufficient reason for not doing so.
They also called for research into the problems and stresses of remand
prisoners; and the involvement of psychologists in the design of remand
regimes, in their evaluation, in assessment of prisoners and training of staff.
Nor should psychologists and other staff working with remand prisoners have to
play any part in the judicial process.
THE working group also took evidence on distressed behaviour resulting from
remand, such as self-mutilation, often made worse by withdrawal from drugs or
alcohol and by remand regimes' own restraints - such as inability to mix freely
with, and get support from, other prisoners. The report's sweeping
recommendations for change ran into 40 measures for courts, social workers and
the penal system.
But prisons can easily become everyone else's scapegoats. A more fundamental
question for legal, penal and welfare systems is why so many women, especially
young women, enter prisons with major problems already in place - like
self-harm, drink and drug abuse, serious depression or a psychiatric history.
The whole weight of traditional theories on female offenders still encourages
them to be seen as simply mad, bad, inadequate or ``attention-seeking'' (Sue
Gutteridge even noted prisoners being charged the cost of saucers they broke to
slash themselves). These attitudes heavily affect the kind of support services
female offenders do, or do not, receive.
The idea that many might be normal young people deeply affected by life
experiences of upheaval, trauma or serious abuse, with offending just one
manifestation of that, has yet to be acted upon beyond lip service, with
support programmes geared to address those experiences directly - diverting
them from the penal system, or plugging them into effective services when they
do end up in jail.
As Peter Bates said, one of the most important challenges female offenders pose
is ``the need to hear what women say about their own offending, and to treat
them as responsible people''.
It is, perhaps, worryingly symptomatic of the prison service's ``gatekeeping''
priorities for both female and male prisoners that it is prepared to build 13
special ``at risk'' cells in Scottish jails, complete with non-tear clothes and
resuscitation equipment on hand at a cost of #30,000 each. And yet Cornton
Vale's deputy governor, Mr William Low, told the FAI on Holland and Elliot last
week that cell modernisation and provision of full-time counsellors would drain
``a huge proportion'' of the prison's budget.
</TEXT>
