<HEADLINE>Asylum-seeker curbs `tougher than feared'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of asylum-seekers will face a stark choice of deportation or
destitution in the new year, MPs were told yesterday.
A benefits crackdown means help will be withdrawn from up to 13,000 would-be
refugees, Department of Social Security officials disclosed. They ruled out any
possibility of people being given cash for a flight back home.
The disclosures - to the Commons Social Security Select Committee - are even
worse than refugee organisations had feared. Mr Nick Hardwick, chief executive
of the Refugee Council has warned that up to 8000 asylum-seekers could be left
homeless and destitute. Labour MP Jeremy Corbyn (Islington) described the
action as ``abominable''.
Meanwhile, Home Secretary Michael Howard stepped into a row over the release of
confidential details about a Nigerian asylum-seeker which were given to
journalists by Conservative Party headquarters.
In a letter to Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw, he repeated a statement given
earlier by the Prime Minister that the Home Office decided to give out
information to set the record straight after Abiodun Igbindu's team had
publicised details of the case and allegations about its handling.
WESTERN Isles MP Calum Macdonald has called on the Scottish Secretary to use
his voice in Cabinet to support a European bid to save Scottish salmon farmers
from Norwegian over-production and dumping. Mr Macdonald, a Labour spokesman on
the Highlands and Islands, last night attacked what he saw as Mr Forsyth's
inaction: ``Salmon-farming is an important Scottish industry, and vital to the
fragile economies of the Highlands and Islands. It has been twice devastated by
Norwegian over-production and dumping. Now is the time to act. It is Mr
Forsyth's job to ensure that Scotland's interests are backed by the whole power
of the UK in Europe. He has failed to do this.''
A NEW bid to crack down on the sex tourism industry was launched last night
amid indications that the Government is considering action on the issue.
Crossbencher Lord Hylton, introducing his Sexual Offences (Amendment) Bill,
told the Lords it would ``extend the jurisdiction of the UK courts to try
sexual offences against children committed overseas''.
BABY deaths are at their lowest level, Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell told
the Commons yesterday. The perinatal rate - stillbirths and deaths of babies
less than a week old - fell by nearly 40% between 1979 and 1994 and the infant
death rate - for those under one year - dropped by half during the same period.
Mr Dorrell said the figures demonstrated the ``good value, efficient'' service
being delivered by the National Health Service.
</TEXT>
