<HEADLINE>Judges' ruling on jury's #165,000 damages pay-out creates a pattern for claims in Scotland Awards for injuries set to rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAMAGES awards in personal injuries cases in Scotland look set to increase
after three appeal court judges refused to interfere with a jury's decision to
give #165,000 to a Kilmarnock binman.
The court decided to leave the amount intact, despite the fact that #91,000 of
the total - awarded for the pain suffered by Mr Wallace Currie - was around
twice what a judge would have given.
Lord Hope, the Lord President, acknowledged the risk that judges might become
increasingly out of touch with awards made legitimately by juries.
The appeal court decision to leave the jury's award standing was welcomed by Mr
Currie's solicitor, Mr Ian Newton. He said: ``The modest acknowledgement by the
appeal court, that judges may be out of touch with the ordinary person,
provides an opportunity for judges to bring damages awards more into line with
what the Scottish public considers to be reasonable compensation in personal
injury cases.''
The immediate result of the decision is likely to be an increased demand for
juries in personal injuries cases.
They give higher damages than judges and Mr Currie's case indicates that the
appeal court will be slow to interfere, even when it thinks the award is much
too high.
If Mr Newton is right, the decision might also be seen as a hint to judges that
their awards are too low.
Mr Currie, of Methven Avenue, Kilmarnock, suffered serious injuries when a bin
lorry drove over his feet in August 1992. The first four toes of his left foot
had to be amputated and the jury at the Court of Session was told that a
further below-the-knee amputation was imminent.
He had been an enthusiastic cross-country runner and had enjoyed some success
in veteran events.
He alleged that his employers, Kilmarnock and Loudon District Council, had been
negligent, and sued for #200,000. The jury gave him #165,000, including #91,000
for solatium (pain and suffering).
The council appealed on the grounds that the award for pain and suffering was
excessive, and suggested #35,000.
Lord Hope, who heard the appeal with Lords Prosser and Osborne, said the
solatium award was substantially in excess of what a judge would have given, in
light of recent awards in similar cases.
If the #91,000 had been awarded by a judge sitting alone, the appeal court
would have been entitled to reduce it, but a jury award could be set aside only
if the jury had committed a gross injustice.
There was a wealth of information about the level of awards made by judges for
pain and suffering. Inflation tables had been devised and were recognised in
practice as an appropriate method of updating past awards.
Lord Hope added, however: ``It is open to question whether an award, arrived at
by comparison with past awards, (and) updated by an inflation table based upon
the retail price index, is a true reflection of a reasonable jury's conception
of the value of money.
``There is a risk that, by adhering to the relatively narrow band within which
judges operate, judges will become increasingly out of touch with awards made
by juries in the proper exercise of their discretion. The court must adopt a
fairly broad approach in its examination of awards of solatium made by juries,
and that any previous awards, whether by a judge or by a jury, can be no more
than a rough guide as to what is or what is not excessive.
``As for the award of solatium made by the jury in the present case, I do not
think that they can be described as so extravagant as to have resulted in a
gross injustice to the defenders.''
There is a right to a jury trial in the Court of Session unless the person
defending the action can show special cause why the case is unsuitable for a
jury.
</TEXT>
