<HEADLINE>Nice and restrained - just the questions are bizarre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR TONY BLAIR was accused yesterday of ``disgraceful intimidation and
browbeating,'' not so much ``tough on crime and tough on the causes of crime''
as just tough.
The accusation, surprisingly, did not come from his own side but from Tory Tim
Devlin (Stockton South). This alleged thuggery was being perpetrated, the MP
claimed, on parents at a North of England school, who were thinking of opting
their children's school out of local authority control.
The Prime Minister, perhaps mindful of the Speaker's view the day before, that
MPs should not be nasty to each other, was tough on ``disgraceful intimidation
and browbeating'' but brought in a verdict of not proven on Mr Blair by not
mentioning him.
The Labour leader reciprocated by asking a low-key question about education
and, even when provoked by having the sorry records of some Labour-controlled
education authorities read out to him, declined to ask a second, never mind a
third question.
Not only were Members being nice and restrained, there was no burning issue
that anyone could think of how Mr Major found himself in trouble of a different
kind than usual as he tried to frame rational answers to some bizarre questions.
Mrs Elizabeth Peacock (Batley and Spen - Con.) asked for his view on the use of
textiles from three Yorkshire companies to clothe the latest James Bond. Mr
Michael Brown (Brigg and Cleethorpes - Con.) asked if Mr Major agreed that his
constituency was becoming ``the chemical capital of the world.''
Sir Michael Shersby (Uxbridge - Con.) asked him to praise the outstanding
success of Operation Christmas Cracker.
Mr George Foulkes (Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley - Lab.) asked him to reveal
all about the issue that has gripped the attention of the nation - the alleged
doctoring of the video of the Conservative Party conference to make one
Minister (Dr Brian Mawhinney) look better and another (Mr Michael Portillo)
less good.
Besides these, the efforts of Mr Michael Fabricant (Mid Staffordshire - Con.)
and Mr Bill Walker (Tayside North - Con.), urging him to commend ``the
Conservative Party's crusade for choice'' in the first case and condemn
Labour's plans for a Scottish parliament in the second, seemed positively
statesmanlike.
However, even the blandest Question Time rarely passes without suggesting that
the Government is up to another fishy operation.
Mr Matthew Taylor, the youthful Liberal Democrat from Truro, complained about
Government figures claiming to show that Devon and Cornwall get a better deal
from public spending than the rest of the country.
Ministers, of course, are always telling the Scots and Welsh that they do
better than the rest of the country. The Sketch is weak on economics, but
surely every region can't be doing better than the rest of the country.
It was in character with the spirit of this session that Mr Rhodri Morgan
(Cardiff West - Lab.), after indicating the latest buffers on which rail
privatisation has crashed, ended by urging the Prime Minister and the House to
join him in a chorus of the old song, Let's Call the Whole Thing Off.
For yesterday's question session, it might not have been a bad idea.
</TEXT>
