<HEADLINE>Christmas cynicism that runs in the blood</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TIS the season to be ..... well and truly freaked that it's that season again.
Why, seems like only yesterday that we were being informed by some thoughtful
advertiser that t'was a mere 276 shopping days to Christmas but, dash it, yet
again and, despite the best of intentions, I've missed my chance to be up to
scratch on the old Blue Peter Advent crown front.
I'm sure that one day that plastic bag of wire coat hangers, gold tinsel and
candles that I've been hoarding in the wardrobe will be put to good use but
somehow I suspect that the end result would not be suitable for broadcast on
children's television. Or a family newspaper for that matter - so don't bother
writing in for DIY diagrams.
The female best friend arrived at the door the other day radiating the sort of
glow that only podgy infants bundled into duffle coats in those ancient Ready
Brek ads ever had. I was instantly suspicious. I knew she wasn't the type but I
wondered if she had taken drugs. I couldn't think of anything else which would
inspire the state of serendipity she was clearly in.
If I hadn't already buzzed her through by intercom I would have kept her
standing on the doorstep but she was in the kitchen making herself a coffee
before I could begin my interrogation. ``You look, um, very snug,'' I said.
``Mmm,'' she said dreamily with an air of beneficent grace which, alarmingly,
reminded me of Sydney Penny, the spooky star of the film Bernadette. This was
scary stuff. I considered dialling the emergency services. Perhaps she had been
brainwashed by some weird cult?
But her beatific state was not down to organised religion but something even
worse: organised shopping. When she revealed her heinous secret it was all I
could do to stop myself from shrieking in terror and rushing off to shake
copies of various slacker's Bibles at her like some latter-day,
garlic-clutching vampire catcher. She imparted her revelation with a reluctance
which I deemed false judging by the slight smirk lurking round her lips.
``Spill the beans - no, not those ones,'' I shrieked, as she got at the jar of
Nescafe (three types of the world's finest) out of the cupboard. She shrugged
and gave an eerie smile. ``It's no big deal,'' she said, brandishing the kettle
with a witchy glee. ``I've just bought the last present on my Christmas
shopping list.''
``Aargh! I told you not to go into teaching; I knew you would pick up bad
habits,'' I wailed. If it is at all possible to sip coffee airily then I swear
that is what she did next, before pausing and declaring: ``I've also posted my
Christmas cards, bought the Christmas food in, and painted all the skirting
boards.''
I promptly collapsed in a moaning heap, uttering profanities, curses, and cries
of betrayal. I recovered to her wafting one of her surplus Christmas cards over
my face. ``I haven't really painted all the skirting boards,'' she was
comforting me. ``Only three walls' worth in one room.''
What happened to traditional Christmas cynicism? It seems to be drowned out by
waves of festive cheer. I suppose the one bright spot is that if everyone else
is going to be so organised it means my normal ``Christmas Eve dash'', which
involves the kind of shopping frenzy which would put even the hyped-up
contestants on Dale Winton's Supermarket Sweep to shame, will be that much
easier. Everyone else will be sitting at home in smug stupification, munching
on mince pies and putting the final touches to beribboned parcels, giving me
some space frantically to gather all before my path.
Christmas is so intimidating. Only ickie-bickie kiddies and proper grown ups
can really enjoy it. Us in-betweenies are bewildered. Christmas looks like too
much fuss. We simply don't have the know-how to know how to deal with it. The
products of the functional and diffracted families we can do some strange and
wonderful and even vaguely illegal things but no-one ever showed us how to
stuff a turkey.
Consequently, those of us who can afford to are leaving the country in droves
to avoid the festive season, signing up for trips to sunny, tinsel-free,
angst-free climes like Goa and Thailand. Those of us who can't afford to do so
will, ironically, end up spending more. We'll sign up for prolonged debt by
putting our signature to credit card slips for presents all the more expensive
for being bought in the grip of last-minute panic.
Because for all our expressed cynicism we succumb to guilt in the end, falling
for that consumer mantra which is slyly wrapped inside a supposedly charitable
message: it is better to give than to receive.
It's a message which has been cleverly deployed by the Blood Donor Centre this
year. A personal plea has dropped through the letter box. I'm a regular,
card-carrying donor. Well, as a lapsed Catholic I had to find something to
replace the cleansing sensation of walking out of confession. Strolling out of
the Blood Donor Centre, having had my blood sucked and feeling the kind of
euphoric self-righteousness which normally only comes from chucking bags of
empties into the bottle bank, seems to hit the spot.
SO, the blood bank people have solved my annual dilemma of what to give with
their ``Better to give than to receive'' plea. After all, goodwill gestures are
so hep, and adopting a dolphin for someone's Crimbo prezzie is so passe. Don't
get me wrong. I hope my highly efficient, super-organised mates will never need
it but my gift to them will be a donation of blood to the nation's supplies.
Well, it's the thought that counts. I've enough of the old red stuff to give
some away. The health bods don't seem to object to it being boiling.
</TEXT>
