<HEADLINE>Atherton is now better than Boycott</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIKE Atherton has been rewarded for his recent Test-saving innings with
possibly the biggest compliment English cricket can pay an opening batsman.
``I think Mike is a better player than Geoff Boycott was at the same age,''
said manager Ray Illingworth.
``They are comparable in terms of concentration and technique, but Mike is only
27 whereas Geoff reached his best around 30.''
Boycott was among those who watched with admiration at the Wanderers as
Atherton saved the second Test against South Africa by batting for nearly 11
hours while scoring an undefeated 185. Boycott, who totalled 8114 runs from 108
Tests, found few things in life more enjoyable than occupying the crease for
long periods. But, as captain of a side facing what most people thought was
certain defeat, Atherton's main satisfaction came from saving England.
Even when the job was as good as done and he could have aimed for an extra
chunk of glory, thoughts of scoring a first double century at senior level did
not enter his head.
``Mike never mentioned trying to get 200,'' said Illingworth. ``I don't think
records and milestones mean the same to him as they did to Boycks. ``He is one
of those people whose game is suited to captaincy. It has made him a better
player.''
The statistics tend to support Illingworth's case. For Atherton has now scored
nine centuries in 53 Tests - six of them since taking over as captain from
Graham Gooch 26 matches ago.
``I can think of only one other current English player who could play the kind
of innings Mike produced at the Wanderers,'' said Illingworth. ``Tim Robinson
has the necessary concentration, but he probably could not do it against quick
bowlers like Allan Donald.
``A lot of people don't have the ability to concentrate like that.''
Illingworth also was full of admiration for Jack Russell's long contribution to
an undefeated stand of 119 that spanned 75 overs.
``Jack is twice the pro he was four years ago,'' said the manager. ``Since
becoming captain of Gloucestershire he has had to think about other people
rather than just his own game.
``He still works hard at his wicketkeeping and batting but he has a wider
vision of things. He gees up other people and is a very good senior pro.''
Illingworth kept his advice to a minimum when Atherton and Russell returned to
the pavilion at the breaks. ``I just said `well done' and reminded them they
had to start all over again at the beginning of each new session,'' explained
the manager.
Yesterday, the England squad relaxed in their hotel, having flown to Cape Town
and then travelled the short distance to Paarl by coach. Today, however, it is
back to work - preparing for tomorrow's match against provincial side Boland.
Phillip DeFreitas, who is spending the winter in South Africa, should be among
England's opponents on a delightful ground that nestles at the foot of an
impressive mountain range.
``I hope Daffy plays,'' said Illingworth. ``He is not out of our World Cup
reckoning by any means.''
DeFreitas' name was missing from a provisional list of 20 supplied by England
to organisers of the New Year tournament in India and Pakistan.
However, Illingworth insists changes can be made before a final squad of 14 is
submitted, even though cricket officials on the sub-continent are currently
contesting that view.
</TEXT>
