<HEADLINE>Firm hand needed to turn BTR around</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in the BTR industrial conglomerate took a hammering yesterday sliding
14p to 320p after a profits warning that took analysts by surprise.
That helped remove the gloss from a new opening high for the FTSE-100 of 3683
which ended the day at 3664.2 despite Wall Street having risen by nearly 100
points over two days.
In what is now a routine quarterly trading update for shareholders, BTR said
1995 profits and sales would not be in line with earlier expectations although
they would be above those achieved last year. These are being re-stated at
#1308m compared with the earlier published #1341m following disposals including
the #330m sale of construction materials firm Tilcon to Minorco last month.
Pinpointed were the slowdown in parts of the US activities such as automotive
and commercial interiors, and in Australian construction, as well as mixed
trading in Britain and continental Europe. However, many other parts of the
group remain perky.
A particular concern was the downturn in profitability at the Taiwanese polymer
operation which has suffered from a dearth of exports to China. That is thought
be lined up for disposal.
The net effect has been to send profit projections tumbling about #100m to
#1420m, which is obviously no help to a company which has under-performed the
FTSE by 10% since the beginning of the year. That may be partly a problem of
perception as communication is not a major preoccupation at BTR, even if there
has been a fair bit of portfolio reorganisation in the last year.
The City is expecting a great deal from Ian Strachan who takes over as chief
executive at the turn of the year. He was a major player in the vast
improvement in the fortunes of RTZ, and his first executive action at BTR
should not be too long coming to help reverse the stock's under-performance.
Plainly urgent
RECENT legislation on consumer contracts requires that they be written in plain
English, and this includes mortgage contracts.
The Banking Ombudsman Laurence Shurman agrees it is high time the impenetrable
legalese in these documents was made more understandable. At present people
cannot comprehend what they are agreeing to.
Unfortunately, even in plain English mortgage paperwork can never be simple,
but lenders might at least take more trouble to explain to customers what it is
all about.
Another bee in Mr Shurman's bonnet is the mortgage indemnity guarantee. This is
an (expensive) insurance policy paid for by the borrower for the benefit of the
lender should the property realise less than the mortgage in a forced sale.
There is still confusion over whether the insurer, having paid out to the
lender, could then pursue the borrower for this money. This would be a nonsense
and the uncertainty must be cleared up.
Because the insurers have lost a packet on MIGs as a result of falling house
prices they appear to be penalising borrowers. It is time the whole subject was
brought more into the open.
Astute operator
RACAL Electronic's reputation as an astute operator gained by its participation
in the Camelot consortium, which runs the National Lottery, will not suffer as
a result of its #133m purchase of BR Telecommunications (BRT) from British
Rail.
It provides Racal with a dependable revenue flow arising from long-term
contracts with Railtrack, while giving it a ready-made telecommunications
network within which to sell capacity.
Racal has already approached the American giants AT&amp;T and NYNEX which are eager
to make inroads here. UK cable companies are others which would no doubt be
interested. Racal itself will use some of the capacity for its developing voice
and data transmission services.
BRT is a profitable business, earning #17.6m in the year to last March on
turnover of #174m.
The deal will push up Racal's gearing to 82% but it still expects the purchase
to be earnings enhancing this financial year. Gearing will soon be on the way
down and to finance the acquisition with debt rather than a rights issue looks
better for shareholders. The rising proportion of revenue coming from
telecommunications gives good support to the shares at 276p, up 6p, selling at
about 15 times prospective earnings.
</TEXT>
