<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n AS land prices around the edge of Glasgow rise, locations which would have
once been thought too far out are now becoming more popular.
Tay Homes says its development off Inchmurrin Drive in Kilmarnock, known as The
Craigs, is attracting the kind
of family purchasers who might previously have opted for a location on the
outskirts of Glasgow.
The three-bedroom Beauly and the four-bedroom detached Lewis are priced from
#74,950 and #89,950 respectively, and sales and marketing director Iain Stewart
says such prices are proving to be a key selling point.
Christmas is coming, but builders are keeping the pressure to achieve sales
before the market packs up for the festive season. Tay Homes is offering
part-exchange deals on apartments at its Hyndland Gate scheme in Glasgow's West
End.
Incentives are still playing a key role. Wimpey Homes claims to have been
particularly busy in October and November, mainly due to its special deals
which allow buyers to postpone their first payments for six months - backed up
by 100% market value part-exchange deals.
Ian Brown, sales and marketing director for Wimpey Homes (Scotland West), says:
``There is no doubt that our incentives are attractive and have helped to
increase the level of sales at this time of year. 1995 has been a difficult
year, but 1996 is just around the corner and I am confident the activity we
have been seeing over the past couple of months will continue into 1996.''
A show home has just opened at Glenavon Gate in the Ferguslie Park area of
Paisley where 94 homes have been built.
Four house types are available on the development - The Cary and The Spey, both
two-bedroom semi-detached; The Tweed, a three-bedroom semi-detached; and The
Derwent, a three-bedroom semi-detached. The Spey is on show for visitors to
view. Prices start at #36,995.
Meanwhile, Barratt West Scotland has made it easier to buy one of its
``Oakleaf' properties, taken in part-exchange from buyers who have moved into
new Barratt homes, with a special bonus package.
All Oakleaf homes have been independently inspected and valued, with many
available at prices well below the current market valuations and with extras
such as carpets, curtains and light fittings. Oakleafs are currently available
all over Scotland at #21,000 to #92,000.
That bonus package? On selected Oakleaf homes, Barratt will pay your 5%
deposit; pay your mortgage for six months; provide you with free redundancy
protection for two years, and let you move in for just #99. This package is
over and above the many extras included with Oakleaf Homes.
In the West, a number of Oakleaf homes are available with this bonus package.
In Coatbridge, a one-bedroom starter flat is available in Dundyvan Road for
#32,995. This has a spacious lounge with feature fireplace; built-in mirrored
wardrobes and fitted kitchen with oven, hob and hood.
In Drumry, Clydebank, a two-bedroom upper cottage flat is priced at #29,950. It
has a double oven hob and hood as well as double-glazing and a bathroom with
shower.
A three-bedroom, first-floor flat is available in Dumbarton Road, Scotstoun,
Glasgow. Priced at #41,995 with double glazing, it comprises spacious lounge,
fitted kitchen, three bedrooms and bathroom.
A bonus package property is also available in Balloch. In Shearer Quadrant, a
two-bedroom, first-floor flat - professionally decorated and with new carpets -
is priced at #25,500.
</TEXT>
