<HEADLINE>Hope burns bright</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN unusual musical premiere will take place in London tonight: the performance
of a new composition in memory of the late John Smith, former leader of the
Labour Party, set to texts chosen with the advice of his widow, Baroness Smith.
The composition, entitled A Live Flame, is a 20-minute work for solo tenor and
orchestra, and will be performed at St John's Smith Square this evening by the
London Musici with tenor Richard Coxon.
The composition is by Keith Burstein, a controversial young composer who has
tended to annoy the Establishment by his confrontation of social issues in his
music. (He has written a Requiem for the victims of the 1989 Marchioness river
boat disaster.)
Moved by the ``moment of loss'' he felt on hearing of the death of John
Smith, Burstein contacted Labour MPs and Baroness Smith and expressed his
intention to write a work which would ``create images of permanence and hope''.
Texts were chose from the poems of Keats, Graves and Burns, among others, with
a particular reference to Gerard Manley Hopkins's Inversnaid, recommended by
Baroness Smith as one of her late husband's favourite poems.
Burstein then approached the London Musici's founder and music director, Mark
Stephenson, who agreed to take on the new work for his orchestra.
Richard Coxon, who will sing the solo tenor part, is a familiar face in
Scottish music circles. Currently a contract principal with Scottish Opera,
Coxon has recently sung in a range of Scottish Opera productions, including
Beethoven's Fidelio    at the Edinburgh Festival and Dvorak's The Jacobin.
MICHAEL TUMELTY
</TEXT>
