<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The carousel starts to turn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart McIntosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish home prices
are set for a gentle
recovery, according to
a new report analysed
by Stewart McIntosh
A leading economic forecaster is predicting that Scottish house prices will
rise every year for the next five years. But don't fasten your seat belt yet.
The upswing will be a rather genteel one, carrying the market on a steady, if
undramatic, upward curve.
In a report for the merchant bankers Charterhouse, forecaster James Morrell
says UK house prices will edge higher next year then accelerate in 1997/98 to
produce an average rate of growth of 3% per annum in the years to 2000. The
peak will come in two years, when the South-east will see rises of 5% or 6%.
Scotland's success in outperforming the rest of the UK housing market over the
last four years means that rises north of the Border will be more muted.
Scotland's price increases will peak at 4% in 1998 - and the five-year average
north of the Border will pan out at around 2.25% per annum, compared with the
UK's 3% average, predicts Morrell.
When inflation is taken into account, there will be no real growth in values
anywhere in the UK over the next five years. But although prices will be moving
sideways in real terms, a gradual increase in the price tag pinned to the front
doors will bring smiles of relief to house builders, estate agents and sellers.
The best news in the report is that housing should become even more affordable
over the next five years. The ratio of house prices to earnings is now at a
record low level, which makes housing very affordable. ``The market is poised
for a gentle recovery,'' says Morrell.
He calculates that the current average cost of a second-hand house in Scotland
is #57,200, a figure which will rise to #64,100 by the year 2000. But the
increase will be more than met by the forecast rises in earnings. The average
combined earnings of Scottish households is #31,500 - which Morrell says will
rise to #38,300 by 2000. Put average earnings and average house prices together
and the price-to-earnings ratio shows that Scotland's homes will become
steadily more affordable.
The average house in Scotland currently costs 1.83 times the average combined
earnings - and will reduce to 1.67 by 2000. The price-to-earnings ratios for
new-build housing is slightly higher but follows the same pattern of reduction
over the next five years.
Morrell's figures offer vivid evidence of the canny Scots' reluctance to get
carried away by the bonfire of insanities which swept through the southern
market at the end of the 1980s. At the height of the boom in 1989 Scottish
house prices rose to 2.13 times average combined earnings - but in the south of
England people were having to pay more than four times their combined earnings
to buy a house. Then the bubble burst.
Since then, the market has never really dragged back to its feet. But Morrell
believes we have learned to live with insecurity and debt. As a result, the
Charterhouse report predicts that spending power will increase next spring.
More importantly, he also forsees an increase in first-time buying then.
If he is right, the first-time buyer will be the engine that drives the
house-market recovery. Around 50% of all purchases are accounted for by
first-time buyers and any increase in activity will generate chains of deals
throughout the market.
In 1988 the Government warned that it was going to withdraw the double mortgage
relief which was available for unmarried couples. The resulting orgy of
frenzied transactions saw 545,000 ``virgin' purchases that year, pushing up
prices and creating greed, envy and lust in a market which had been rather
straightlaced for the previous 20 years. But it could not last, the
first-timers ran out of steam, and transactions slumped to 327,000 by 1992.
When the tide turned, many of those younger people who plunged headlong into
the market in 1988 found themselves high and dry with negative equity.
Having seen what happened to their older brothers and sisters, many other
potential buyers have deferred their first house purchase. But the costs of
buying and renting have converged and an increase in activity among first-time
buyers is now predicted by the Charterhouse report. Around 400,000 first-timers
will come into the market each year for the next five years, the report
predicts.
All in all, Morrell reveals a telling comparison between Scottish and UK price
swings over the last ten years, projected forward to 2000. The graphs show a
much smoother pattern north of the Border compared with the jagged peaks and
troughs which afflict the English market.
</TEXT>
