<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Your own place in history</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CASTLE is the stuff of fantasy in these embattled times. The nuisances of
daily life seem further away when you can slam the gate shut, climb the stairs
to your turret and defy tax inspectors and double-glazing salesmen to penetrate
your defences.
And you don't need to be a robber baron to own your own historic castle. Estate
agency Allen &amp; Harris is selling Hatton Castle, a traditional Z-plan
fortification dating from 1575, which stands on an elevated position over the
vale of Strathmore between the Sidlaw Hills and the Grampians.
Situated on the edge of Newtyle at the base of Hatton Hill, the B-listed castle
commands the paths through the Sidlaws to Dundee. The accommodation comprises:
traditional great hall, laird's drawing room and study, kitchen, dining room,
two store rooms, seven bedrooms, four bathrooms, oil-fired underfloor heating,
enclosed garden, and around one acre of ground. But the estate agent warns that
completion work is needed to make it habitable.
The lands of Hatton were granted by charter by Robert the Bruce in 1317 to his
daughter, when she married Sir Walter de Oliphant, Chief Justiciary of Lothian.
Her loving dad also threw in the lands of Balcraig, Ochtertyre, Balgonie,
Newtyle and Kinpurnie. This charter was later confirmed by David II. Their
heirs were raised to the peerage in 1463, and in 1575 Laurence, the fourth Lord
Oliphant, married the Earl of Errol's daughter and built Hatton Castle.
The property was sold by the fifth Lord Oliphant in 1627 to the neighbouring
Hallyburtons of Pitcus. It was garrisoned for the Covenant in 1645, but
Montrose managed to take it. In 1690 it was sold to Sir George Mackenzie of
Rosehaugh and is believed to have been inhabited until 1770, after which it
fell into a ruinous condition.
In the early years of this century it was bought by the Cayzer family, owners
of the surrounding estate of Kinpurnie, who in 1986 feued it to the Hutton
Castle Trust, which has restored the structure to its original design.
The castle has two unusual architectural features: the scale and platt (square)
staircase in the south-west tower is believed to be the first built of its
type, a spiral staircase being more common; and the main living section has
been divided asymmetrically by a wall, giving different floor levels throughout
the core of the building.
The castle is built of harled stone under a slate roof. Flagstones form the
floors at ground and first level, while those on the second and third level are
of oak. As are the internal doors. The garden, enclosed by a boundary wall,
extends to about an acre.
Unlike in Montrose's day, neither battering ram nor conquering army is required
to take Hatton Castle now. A piece of paper offering more than #125,000 will
see Allen &amp; Harris's defences crumble.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
