<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plan for a #2m clash of codes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUGBY ROUND-UP
RUGBY Football Union secretary Tony Hallett claims that talks have taken place
between the two codes regarding a proposed #2m showdown involving rugby league
side Wigan and union's Bath.
The game, which would consist of two matches - one at Twickenham under union
rules the other a league game at a major football ground in the north - would
be designed to establish the best rugby team in England.
The clubs are keen on the plan, with May considered the most suitable month,
but Hallett denied that any official approach had been received.
``I talked with Maurice Lindsay in London about the idea,'' said Hallett.
``Neither of us has been approached officially, but both codes would wish to
examine the implications of such matches before agreeing to them.''
q.FRENCH flanker Philippe Benetton has broken his right arm for the second time
this year and will miss this season's Five Nations' tournament.
Benetton, one of the stalwarts of the French team, broke the arm three minutes
from the end of Agen's match with Nice at the weekend. He broke the same arm
while playing for France against Scotland in Pretoria during the World Cup
finals in June.
q.PETER Walton is poised to complete his recovery from injury by playing for
Newcastle this weekend. The Scotland flanker, who has been in rehabilitation
from a knee operation, is aiming to play for one of Newcastle's sides on
Saturday following his return to full training.
q.WESTERN Samoa were caught cold at the end of each half as they slumped to yet
another pounding when the North won 34-8 last night to make it three defeats in
12 days for the tourists.
As snow blizzards hit Huddersfield, North wings Jim Naylor and Jim Mallinder
warmed up the crowd with sparkling scores just before half-time that put their
side 17-3 in front.
In the second half Western Samoa did little to dent the North's superiority,
which was emphasised when Rob Liley and Richard Arnold crashed over for tries
in 78 and 81 minutes to give their team an overwhelming margin.
Western Samoa fielded none of the Test team that so proudly drew with Scotland
last month.
q.SWANSEA became the first club to clinch a Heineken European Cup semi-final
place when they edged out French club Castres 22-10 in a thriller at St Helens
last night. The Welsh club had needed a six-point margin to win the pool.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
