<DOCNO>GH951206-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bridge crash disrupts trains</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of rail passengers throughout Scotland were delayed yesterday, after
a lorry struck a bridge near Kirkintilloch, Dunbartonshire.
The damage forced engineers to close the bridge for repairs and virtually all
services from Glasgow Queen Street were affected, including the busy Edinburgh
shuttle service, Stirling, Dunblane, Perth, Dundee, and Aberdeen.
Nobody was injured in the accident yesterday afternoon, in which a lorry struck
the parapet of a bridge carrying a road above the railway line. Engineers were
last night attempting to remove unstable masonry before they could carry out
repairs.
A spokeswoman for Railtrack said it was hoped that the work could be completed
overnight.
The line closure forced ScotRail to divert services via other routes, which
meant long delays for many passengers.
A ScotRail spokesman said last night that all services out of Glasgow Queen
Street had been affected, with the exception of Maryhill and the West Highland
Line. Worst hit had been the Glasgow-Edinburgh shuttle service.
``We are trying to run as normal a service as possible but there will be severe
disruption, delays, and probably cancellations.''
The accident also disrupted road traffic, with the B8048 Kirkintilloch to
Twechar road remaining closed last night as repair work continued on the bridge.
Last night, Strathclyde Police revealed that the lorry driver had failed to
stop after the accident at the Drumgrew bridge.
They are appealing for anyone who witnessed the accident or who has any
information about the lorry or the driver, to come forward
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal help for crofters</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO Government agencies are preparing to help crofters who want to take control
of their own land, by guiding them through the legal process once a thorough
study has indicated it would be in their interests.
So far, two private meetings have been held between the Crofters Commission and
Highlands and Islands Enterprise. The first move was made by the commission
even before the Secretary of State made his surprise announcement in October
that he was prepared to hand over control of Scottish Office-owned crofting
estates to local crofting trusts.
No-one at the commission was willing to comment yesterday but a HIE spokesman
confirmed that the agency had been represented at an informal meeting to
discuss crofting issues.
He would say only: ``The issue of crofters buying their own land is likely to
become more important in the future and it is important that good advice is
available to them.''
It is understood that a working group is expected to be set up in the new year
to advise crofters on the legal and financial aspects of taking over estates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A dame good night out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kate Rafferty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028243</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF your idea of festive entertainment is an armchair, a bottle of port, a box
of Belgium's finest soft centres and a Morecambe and Wise repeat, forget this .
. . if you're happy to let some of the most enjoyable festive family
experiences pass you by, that is.
It's a bit nippy out this time of year, but theatres are filled with warmth,
especially when they're filled with the joy of pantomime.
The King's in Glasgow has its usual traditional approach to panto, with Jimmy
Logan turning a shapely leg as The Dame in Babes In The Wood from December 14
to February 3, ably supported by comedy duo Cannon and Ball. The Citizens
Theatre are producing the more traditional Pinocchio story from November 28 to
January 13. Another more unusual choice for panto time is Sinbad The Sailor,
presented at the New Athenaeum Theatre by final year students of the Royal
Scottish Academy of Music and Drama. It runs for one week only from Monday,
December 11 to Friday, December 15 with a 10am performance on Saturday,
December 16.
For traditional entertainment (aimed at pre-teens), there's no one to touch the
success of The Singing Kettle. The fabulous Fifers - Cilla, Artie and Gary -
have put together a new show which runs at the SECC from December 13 to January
4.
The SECC also has the traditional Christmas and New Year carnival running from
December 15 to January 14.
Edinburgh is buzzing with shows over Christmas and the New Year, with
Cinderella, the ``glamour-panto'' being staged at the King's, with Una McLean,
presenter Ross King, Scottish comedy stars Jonathan Watson and Andy Gray, who
joins actor/angler Paul Young as an ugly sister.
Stuart Paterson's Merlin The Magnificent is being staged at The Royal Lyceum
Theatre from December 8 to January 6. Paterson has been described as
``Scotland's finest Christmas show writer'' by entertainment weekly The Stage.
The Theatre Workshop have their own Christmas show in the shape of Baba Yaga
And The Magic Doll, an adaptation of a Russian folk tale. Performances between
December 4 and 23.
The most enduring of stories, A Christmas Carol has been translated into a
beautiful piece of dance by the Northern Ballet Theatre at the Edinburgh
Festival Theatre from January 3 to 13.
The world's top skaters will be taking up residence at the Edinburgh Festival
Theatre from December 19 to 31 in Hot Ice.
There are entertainments outside Scotland's two main cities, of course.
Stirling's MacRobert Arts Centre is presenting the magical story of The Snow
Queen, while the town's Albert Halls will be visited by the storytelling
spaceman Mr Boom in his Christmas Sing-Song. He'll be beaming down on December
21, 22 and 23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Demons rise again to tempt the Scots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028244</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE patron saint of Scotland ought not to be St Andrew but St Nicholas. His
most famous miracle occurred while he was a young man, long before he rose to
his later episcopal eminence. Journeying through his native Asia Minor, he
stopped at an inn and asked what was for dinner. The landlord replied that he
had nothing but pickled bacon, rolled out three barrels of it and, with a leer,
invited Nicholas to taste.
But, by divine grace, the holy youth at once saw through him. He realised that
this was not animal but human flesh, the remains of previous wayfarers unlucky
enough to have halted overnight were he had. Quite likely he would end up in
brine himself unless he did something. He resuscitated the three dead bodies,
who disconcerted him by turning out to be demons. They tempted him, needless to
say without success. But at least he made the landlord repent, so he had the
salvation of that soul to his credit anyway.
I nominate Nicholas as the new patron saint because he provides one enduring
image of Scottish politics: the pork-barrel. It is fitting that in popular
tradition he should have changed into an old fool with a white beard who, after
our insistent pleading and merely nominal promises to be good, showers us with
undeserved presents. There could be no more eloquent metaphor of the actual
operation of the political system in Scotland.
Certainly St Andrew should be sacked after the way he allowed last Thursday to
degenerate. Three demons rose again, which might be called Scotland past,
Scotland present, and Scotland future (maybe). None struck me as an edifying
sight.
When, after that day's announcements by Michael Forsyth, I seek a master plan
behind his tenure of the Scottish Office, I am still foxed. I think I know what
Conservatives ought to be, if I understand Conservatism at all. They ought
first to be patriotic, because a nation or any other genuine community is a
concrete product of history, arisen through processes we cannot fully fathom,
and anyway need not. That it exists is enough. The task is to preserve it.
Given that, Conservatives can proceed straight to a quest after the best
practical means of preservation, for which they are well-fitted because
encumbered by universal ideologies. On purely pragmatic grounds, liberal
capitalism must count in the present state of experience and knowledge as the
best means: a capitalist economic order to make us all richer and generate the
resources for resolving social tensions, a liberal political order for us to
act towards those ends so far as possible for ourselves, free of coercion by
our governors.
If Conservatism can be summed up in these two principles, the first presents
Forsyth with an obvious problem: which patriotism? He is of Scotland past in
the sense that he harks back to a time when his countrymen had two patriotisms
in a stable and unproblematic relation to each other. He asks them to accept
that this remains in essentials true.
He may be right, but to prove his point he is led into compromising the second
principle. To preserve that kind of patriotism he sees himself also obliged to
preserve in Scotland an order less capitalist and less liberal than it might
be. It is the kind of order, with excessive public expenditure and bureaucratic
direction of the economy, which failed when applied to Britain as a whole, and
diminished British patriotism.
This relic of the past survives here on a supposition that the Union would
break without it. I do not agree, because I believe the Union rests on a great
deal more than subsidy. In any case, seeing that liberal capitalism works, this
compromise makes Scots less rich and less free. It is also a drag on Britain as
a whole in reaping the rewards that liberal capitalism offers. If that is the
price of the Union, it may not in the long run be worth paying, by either side.
Still, none of those deep questions troubles for one moment the demon of
Scotland present, resuscitated in the proposals of the Constitutional
Convention. Though resuscitated, this Scotland remains a victim to which the
rest of the world owes a living. Since money grows on trees, the only
requirement is for the English to hand over every year a bloated bag of it, so
we can proceed to nationalisation of the whisky industry and other
pleasantries. Why should we care what they think, or if it incommodes them? Our
business is to manufacture grievance, theirs to solve our problems for us. The
details can be left to corrupt local bosses handing out the cash to the most
clamant of their clients. This is an insult to patriotism.
Even for Conservatives, the third demon is less repulsive. But judging from its
muted tones on St Andrew's Day, it has not quite awakened from its pickling in
1707. Its brain is certainly addled. It maunders on about something called
``real socialism'', and thinks the best way to prepare Scotland for
independence is to promote greater independence, to demand at every turn yet
more subsidies in the confidence that England will at some stage refuse to give
them. Here, however, it is wrong. There is no price - no price at all - that
the Labour Party, chief target of the strategy, would decline to pay to hold on
to 50 Scottish seats at Westminster. That is why this Nationalist demon remains
the demon of Scotland future only maybe, and probably not.
Perhaps St Nicholas as a new patron saint is a bad idea after all. I could
suggest St Michael, not because I bear his name, but because he was frightened
of nothing and could look out for himself. I doubt, though, whether modern
Scotland would find his attributes attractive.
</TEXT>
