<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Savings deny patient legal aid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028245</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
A PATIENT seeking legal aid to contest his further detention in a psychiatric
hospital has had his approaches to five law firms for representation rejected
because he has too much money.
His savings of #1400 make him ineligible by a few hundred pounds.
The Legal Services Agency says there is better treatment for similar patients
in England and Wales, where no financial threshold now exists. The law there
was changed last year.
One reason for the man wanting out is that medication, including injections,
can be forced upon him.
Mr Graeme Keay, of the agency, said: ``It's iniquitous that people in Scotland,
being faced with such powerful measures which intrude upon their liberty and
body, should not have the same access to legal representation as in England.
``It's our view he should be able to get advice from any solicitor and should
not be precluded because of financial circumstances.''
The patient, who is in his 40s and receives #13 weekly income support, had been
in Royal Edinburgh Hospital for a spell and a community care plan for his
discharge was carried out.
The man was taken in again under the emergency provisions of the Mental Health
(Scotland) Act 1984 which allows an initial 72 hours detention then a further
28 days. Now the authorities want to hold him for six months.
Last night, Dr James Dyer, director of the Mental Welfare Commission for
Scotland, invited the man to contact the commission with details of his case.
He felt that means-testing for legal aid for psychiatric patients should be
abolished.
``We are going to approach the Secretary of State for Scotland on this because
something has to be done. People should not be inhibited by cost in getting
legal representation.
``We think it is wrong there should be different rules in different parts of
the UK. People here are being disadvantaged by this and Scotland should be
brought into line with England and Wales.''
q A conference to discuss whether the time has come for a fundamental review of
mental health legislation in Scotland is being held today at the Royal College
of Physicians.
</TEXT>
