<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Librarian loses sex discrimination case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN industrial tribunal yesterday rejected a sex discrimination complaint by a
male librarian against Glasgow Caledonian University.
Mr James Digney had told the tribunal he had been applying for jobs since May
last year but had been either unsuccessful or not allowed to apply. On each
occasion, a woman had been selected for the job.
Mr Digney, 36, of Strathbungo, had claimed the women appointed were no better
than he was.
Eight vacancies had arisen within the library at Caledonian University since
May last year while he worked two-and-a-half hours a week serving behind the
counter. In July, Mr Digney was short listed for a library assistant's post but
was not successful at interview.
He was interviewed for another job in January but failed to make the short list
for a research assistant's post as he was considered to lack the relevant
experience.
At one stage, following an unsuccessful interview, he was interviewed by his
head of department and suggestions were made as to how he might improve his
interview technique.
The tribunal heard that, in common with most university libraries, there were
more female than male librarians.
In their findings, the tribunal accepted that Mr Digney had not performed as
well at interviews as he might have thought he had.
No evidence of sex discrimination in the way the university handled the
selection procedure was found by the tribunal.
It was satisfied the university did not only have an equal opportunities policy
but actively took steps to fulfil the spirit of the policy.
In each case it was accepted that the university had appointed the person they
considered to be the best for the post.
The tribunal was satisfied Mr Digney had been treated fairly at all stages.
</TEXT>
