<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A sore point for Dobbin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RACING ROUND-UP
TONY Dobbin has given up his race to be fit in time to partner One Man at
Haydock on Saturday, postponing his comeback until next week.
The rider admitted that the broken hand and dislocated shoulder sustained three
weeks ago is still causing some discomfort and he will not be able to partner
the grey in the Tommy Whittle Chase.
All of this is good news for Mark Dwyer, who has been offered the mount on One
Man but he cannot confirm his availability until connections of Jodami finalise
their plans.
Dobbin's decision to ride out on One Man at Gordon Richards' stables recently
appears to have set back his return to racecourse action.
``It's very frustrating for Tony,'' said Richards. ``He's trying hard to get
fit again. I'm now waiting on Mark Dwyer but I know Peter Beaumont will not
want to keep us hanging on.''
Beaumont, who trains Jodami, said: ``It's 50-50 he will run. We are keen for
him to go to Wetherby on Boxing Day and we don't want him to have a slog in bad
ground a fortnight before the race.''
Should Dwyer be claimed for Jodami, Richards could turn to Richard Dunwoody,
though the champion is set to ride at Lingfield for Kim Bailey on Saturday.
q FRANCOIS Doumen has confirmed the presence of So Far Bold in the December
Novices' Chase at Lingfield on Saturday. Philipe Chevalier rides the French
raider.
So Far Bold has won two of his 21 starts over jumps and has also been placed
four times. His career earnings amount to almost #104,000.
The five-year-old won the #59,880 Prix Montgomery (handicap chase) at Auteuil
last time, beating Blanville (gave 6lb) by two lengths.
Should the Lingfield mission prove fruitful, So Far Bold may return to Britain
on Boxing Day to contest the Tripleprint Feltham Novices' Chase at Kempton Park.
q CHALLENGER du Luc takes to the stage for his second outing over birch in the
Spruce Novices' Chase at Leicester today, where a performance similar to his
debut effort should be enough to win, writes White and Gold.
Martin Pipe has moved steadily to the top of the trainers' championship table,
where he has won more than #250,000 in win and place prize money and is fast
approaching 80 winners, and his Challenger du Luc looks the best bet of the day.
The five-year-old looked as though he needed the run at Chepstow last month,
winning a sustained duel with Jacob's Wife after the last, but having no answer
to the power-packed finish of Seek The Faith.
The Pipe gelding showed when winning two well-contested novice hurdles last
season that he appreciates cut in the ground and a galloping track - he won at
Chepstow in heavy and Uttoxeter on soft - so Leicester's stiff circuit should
suit.
Jenny Pitman's good early season start continues and her Gilpa Valu looks a
good bet in the Sycamore Chase. Gilpa Valu has risen 8lb since his eight
lengths win at Warwick last time, making a total of 13lb since the start of the
current season in which he has won over #9000 for connections.
</TEXT>
