<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh New Tiger Trust roars downhill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH New Tiger Trust runs on narrow rails that oblige it to invest in
smaller companies in Asia's riskiest stock markets. So over the last year, it
has rattled downhill at a cracking pace.
The Mexican financial crisis in December 1994 triggered a crash in share prices
throughout the Far East and predictably, smaller companies suffered more than
their larger counterparts.
But New Tiger found itself weighed down by #25m of borrowings, which only
served to make the situation worse.
Net asset value plummeted 30.4% to 31.13p per share, overshooting a 14.7%
decline in the MSCI Emerging Markets Free Asia Index.
Even the creation of a new index, tailor-made to reflect the trust's investment
in companies with a market capitalisation of less than $500m, failed to
disguise the full extent of the damage.
This Edinburgh IFC Smaller Companies Index, devised for the trust by the World
Bank, fell 23.2%.
Edinburgh Fund Managers raised #135m to launch the New Tiger Trust in January
1994, but net assets are now worth only #87.2m.
``We are aware that it was a disappointing performance,'' said fund manager
Mike Balfour.
But he said the trust had no plans to radically reshape its portfolio. At
present, nearly half its assets are invested in Thailand, Indonesia and
Malaysia.
``The corporate results of the companies we have been investing in are very
good. There have been some fantastic rises in profits, but their shares have
still fallen,'' Mr Balfour said.
The trust must simply take a long view and wait for the rollercoaster stock
markets of the Far East to start climbing again. A recovery depends on foreign
investors flocking back and local investors switching money back from the banks
to the market.
As Asian inflation rates start to come down, local investors may be encouraged
to buy more shares next year. But prospects for a return of international
confidence are difficult to guage and Mr Balfour warned that a sharp fall on
Wall Street could trigger a new crisis.
``If the US market were to crash, the markets of Asia would, as always react
with it and come down more heavily,'' he said.
</TEXT>
