<DOCNO>GH951206-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Electric Sound Theatre, Traverse, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Clark</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUND speakers are not the most aesthetically pleasing of objects. Although
they serve as the main exponents of electro-acoustic music, there is something
slightly unnerving about a large group of people sitting staring at a
collection of black boxes. None the less, the music emerging from the speakers
in Monday night's ECAT concert offered much to please and, eyes closed, you
could quite easily have been in your favourite armchair at home with a
collection of CDs.
Commissioned by ECAT, the first performance of Robert Dow's When All Is Silent
presented a new-age collection of sounds suggesting a vivid dream sequence.
Saturated (if you'll excuse the pun) with water effects, the balance between
the natural and the electronic was perfectly conceived.
Most entertaining was Larsson's Opening A Can Of Worms. Do you ever feel that
your radio transmitter has been touched by the hand of Techno-death? Larsson's
piece sounds like an unintelligible, nonsensical radio broadcast. Quirky but
never cliched, the blowing raspberries and snatches of Copland's Fanfare For
The Common Man prompted more than a few giggles in the audience.
The cyborg contribution came in Mikael Grahn's The Turing Rejects, a musical
representation of mathematician Alan Turing's test to distinguish man from
machine. Developing into an electronic ``Round Conversation'' culminating in
the vocal triumph of the human over the synthetically produced robot. Creating
an electronic language from the human language, this piece enters a whole new
sound world.
Further contributions from Kim Hedas, Erik Mikael Carlsson, and Jens Hedman
were overshadowed by grandfather of the electronic generation Iannis Xenakis
who showed everyone how it's done in his 1960 Orient-Occident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Care plea fails</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth has rejected a plea for changes in the way
money passes between the health service and social services to pay for Care in
the Community.
The Scottish Affairs Committee had criticised the present arrangements in its
report on the closure of NHS psychiatric hospitals, particularly the variation
in the joint working of health and social work authorities.
The chairman, Mr Willie McKelvey MP, said the committee considered that the
Scottish Office policy of leaving strategy to local agencies was wrong.
The committee heard evidence of consultants pressured to discharge patients
prematurely, and that bed occupancy rates exceeding 100% had raised the
threshold of severity required for admission.
But while Mr Forsyth welcomed ``the support given throughout the report'' to
key areas of Government policy, he added: ``The committee recommended a change
to the current arrangements for the transfer of NHS monies to local authorities
for care services in the community. I support the existing arrangements, which
take careful account of local variations in need across the country.''
</TEXT>
