<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>POWER Midlands Electricity feels #4m draught</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE high financial cost of the recent spate of electricity company bids was
apparent yesterday when Midlands Electricity said the #1950m bid from PowerGen
had cost it about #4m in the first six months of the year. Further costs are
expected as Midland awaits news following the referral of the bid to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission, writes NICOLA REEVES.
Bryan Townsend, chief executive of Midlands, has not ruled out talks with
another bidder. However, he believes the company can survive as an independent
entity, citing the 100p-a-share special dividend and #54.60 rebate to customers
following the demerger of the National Grid, as evidence that it is delivering
value to shareholders.
PowerGen had promised a 200p special dividend, but planned to keep the National
Grid stake. Midlands will now distribute that to customers so the special
dividend has been reduced to 100p, at a cost of #191m. News of the special
dividend came as Midlands reported a #9.7m drop in first-half pre-tax profit to
#92.7m.
</TEXT>
