<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>England in flurry over a few flakes of snow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A deep depression fell over England's media crews yesterdayas the predicted
Siberian weather failed to materialise. But Anne Johnstone explains how they
made the most of it
YOU'D have thought the second Ice Age had arrived. Television reporters in ski
jackets hunched their shoulders, rubbed their hands together and anxiously
scanned the sky. Film crews scoured the country for snowball fights.
Journalists and sub-editors from all over England picked up their shovels and
dug out every tired old cliche they could think of to describe the day's big
event. Yes, hold the front page: two inches of snow fell on Kent yesterday.
(Well, parts of Kent anyway. And well, nearly two inches.)
There can be few prospects better designed to tickle the Scots funny bone than
England grinding to a halt at the first hint of a snow flurry. North of the
Border we were only just recovering from the shock news that English cricket
may not turn out to be an endless source of humour when they turned up trumps
with the next best thing: a weather story, or rather, a weather non-story.
``Britain set for wintry blast from Siberia'', announced the Daily Telegraph on
Monday's front page. By that night reporters, photographers and cameramen were
staked out all over England in anticipation of the big freeze-up.
``It was the big story overnight. We put up a couple of live satellite links in
anticipation and all our crews were on alert to get some snow shots,'' said
Phil Wardman, news editor of Sky News. By breakfast time a few flakes had
started to drift down in the South-east but the crew braced to capture the
``White Hell'' in Yorkshire were feeling a bit let down. It wasn't even raining.
GMTV's Martin Frizzell, resplendent in luminous orange ski jacket, had also
been sent to Yorkshire. He entertained viewers from a muddy field which looked
decidely unlike a Christmas card and occasionally examined the heavens to judge
the imminence or otherwise of the big white-out. ``Our weatherman had been
predicting lots of snow and after the mild weather we've had recently, it was
going to be a big news story,'' said the GMTV spokeswoman.
Though the tabloids decided they had better things to write about, the
broadsheets went to town on the story too. ``Cold snap to bring snow,''
announced the Times. A spokesman for the London Weather Centre warned readers:
``The weather is going to be miserable unless you are a skier.''
The Telegraph ran the story on page two and focused on reassurances from
British Rail and Railtrack that unlike four years ago, the network will not be
crippled by ``the wrong kind of snow''.
``We have now modified the filters on the chokes in our engines which could not
cope with the 1991 snow,'' said a comforting BR spokesman. The paper also ran
two helpful weather maps, under the titles ``Why it was warm'' and ``Why it is
cold''.
The Guardian too ran a map, wittily entitled ``Vicious circle'', explaining how
an anticyclone over Scandinavia is the villain of the piece. A second article
offered handy tips on keeping warm during the anticipated freeze-up, including
``Even walking up or down stairs can help to keep you warm.''
Even the normally restrained Press Association was running a story warning of
``treacherous'' journeys to work as Britain was ``gripped by the first icy
chill of the season''. Norfolk was said to be ``grim'' and Suffolk ``bleak'',
with conditions set to worsen in the afternoon.
By lunchtime, despite falling odds on a white Christmas, weathermen, motoring
organisations, and newsdesks were reluctantly admitting that maybe it wasn't
such a big story after all.
``I'd love to tell you that we're in the grip of an icy Siberian winter down
here but it just isn't true,'' said a jovial AA man in London, adding that the
worst problem he could come up with was reduced visibility in parts of Kent.
``The story wasn't what we'd expected. Now we've got the Duchess's diamonds and
frankly snow has slipped down the schedules,'' said Phil Wardman at Sky News.
The Press Association started running a replacement story, explaining that
cloudy skies were keeping most of the country above freezing.
Only the dear old London Evening Standard seemed reluctant to let the facts get
in the way of a good story. ``Snow from Siberia fell on London today,'' said
their front page report, a terrific example of hyperbole in the best
journalistic tradition. The report continued: ``Several small communities
reported a fear of being cut off,'' and reaches an exciting climax with the
memorable words: ``Drifts of up to three inches of snow could arrive by this
evening.''
q PS. A two-line report from the Tass news agency yesterday reported that more
than 160 drunk Muscovites have frozen to death since winter set in last month.
The MAXIMUM temperature in Moscow yesterday was minus 10 Celsius.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Designs with a golden eye</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Darren Rodger</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S a bit of a fairy tale really: small family-owned construction firm takes
on building barons in the UK's most prestigious housing awards and emerges Best
Luxury House Developer in Britain.
But that's precisely what happened when Mactaggart and Mickel entered the What
House magazine's annual competition - regarded as the ultimate yardstick by the
construction industry.
The Scottish builder won the Gold Medal in the Best Luxury Development category
for Hillpark Pines, which nestles at the foot of Corstorphine Hill, a few
minutes' drive from Edinburgh city centre.
``These are the awards the building trade goes by and the winners can
justifiably claim to build the best houses in Britain on the strength of their
success,'' said Ed Monaghan, Mactaggart and Mickel's general manager. ``We were
thrilled when we heard we had won the luxury development category.''
Not only that, but the accolade follows hot on the heels of a remarkable double
in the National House Building Council's annual awards. Alan Hunter, 36, site
manager at Gilmerton Mews, also in the capital, won both a Pride in the Job
quality award and a Seal of Excellence for his key role in creating a
development of which Mactaggart and Mickel are quite rightly proud.
Situated in a conservation area, Gilmerton Mews is a tasteful development of
two and three-bedroomed terraced and semi-detached houses, priced from #54,170,
which blend in with the existing listed buildings.
The other good news is that Mactaggart and Mickel operates a Major Ownership
Scheme (MOS) through which purchasers need, if they wish, finance only 80% of
the purchase price of a property. At Gilmerton Mews, for example, that would
reduce the basic purchase price to just #43,336.
The remaining 20% interest in the property is retained by the company but can
be bought out at any time by the owner, or it can be maintained to be repaid on
the sale of the house, or if the original buyer ceases to live in it.
As well as Hillpark Pines and Gilmerton, Mactaggart and Mickel has three other
Edinburgh developments.
At Colinton there are Torphin Bank, a mix of three-bedroomed semi and four and
five-bedroomed detached villas, priced from #94,113 (Major Ownership Scheme
price #75,290); and Bonaly, a development of three-bedroomed terraced villas
from #108,320 (MOS #86,656).
At Corstorphine, South Gyle is a development of two and three-bedroomed houses
from #58,803 (MOS #47,042).
Meanwhile in the West of Scotland there are four developments at Newton Mearns:
Mearnscroft - three and four-bedroomed bungalows and villas from #180,107 (MOS
#144,085); Castlefarm - two and three-bedroom terraced and semi-detached houses
and three, four, and five-bedroomed villas from #79,539 (MOS #63,631);
Broomcastle - three-bedroomed semi-detached villas from #82,574 (MOS #66,060);
Higher Broom - two and three-bedroomed detached bungalows from #125,746 (MOS
#100,107); and Eaglesham Park - two-bedroomed detached bungalows and
four-bedroomed detached villas from #152,314 (MOS #121,851).
The Bankhead development at Rutherglen offers one-bedroom flats and
three-bedroomed semi-detached houses from #49,965 (MOS #39,972); and there are
two sites in Ayr, at Greenan - two and three-bedroomed detached bungalows from
#98,307 (MOS #78,645) and Barassie Links - three-bedroomed semi-detached
villas, five-bedroomed detached villas, and three-bedroomed detached bungalows
from #85,172 (MOS #68,137).
However, Mactaggart and Mickel's flagship development is the award-winning
Hillpark Pines. The company chose the site for this exclusive development of 19
four, five, and six-bedroom detached villas (prices on application), quite
deliberately. Secluded and featuring majestic 60-year-old pine trees, the
development exudes an atmosphere of classical elegance and character
reminiscent, perhaps, of a more distinguished era.
``Our director, Bruce Mickel, drew up the designs for Hillpark Pines based on
the work of the famous Scottish architect Robert Lorimer,'' said Ed Monaghan.
``Sir Robert designed spectacular late-Victorian cottages a few miles south of
Edinburgh during the nineteenth century and insisted that each room should have
its own sense of identity and character - elements which we have retained to
provide a range of family homes with highly individual features.
``And we see the award of the title Best Luxury House Developer as an
endorsement of our commitment to quality right across the board.''
Phase one of the development, comprising 10 houses, is complete. Work on phase
two is already under way and of the two houses built both have sold and a
further seven are scheduled for release over the next year.
The pillared entrance from Craigcrook Road reflects the tone of the development
which is concealed from the road by a decorative boundary wall. Pillars are
also a feature of the entrance porch to each villa, and these, along with
latticed windows and doors, create an imposing first impression.
Entrance halls are bright, spacious, and elegant, with pillars again helping to
create a traditional and luxurious feel. Generous sitting rooms will suit all
family and entertaining purposes and at the heart of each, giving a warm and
welcoming focus, is a splendid Inglenook fireplace. Again, formal entertaining
or intimate comfort is easily achievable in the superb dining rooms.
Upstairs, the master bedrooms have carefully co-ordinated wardrobes, and window
seats are another attraction. Ensuite bathrooms, complete with exotic bathtubs
and careful lighting, create a thoroughly self-indulgent mood.
The five-bedroom villa has a garden room and the six-bedroom villa has an added
library corner, a striking feature of the main public room.
Mactaggart and Mickel has gone to great lengths to create a truly unique
development. Inspired by celebrated architecture and built using traditional
craftsmanship, Hillpark Pines offers a welcoming environment of luxurious homes.
Mactaggart and Mickel has struck gold for its luxury Hillpark Pines
development. Darren Rodger finds winning awards has
become a way
of life for the
company as he looks at the
other estates in
its portfolio
</TEXT>
