<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Mixed up' granny joins the millionaires' club</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTTERY winner Norah Kiellor learned that she had scooped the #10.6m jackpot
shortly after watching a young relative appear on the TV draw show.
The 75-year-old widow, who has three children and eight grandchildren, was
glued to last Saturday's programme to see eight-year-old Angela in a film clip
from Calshot Activity Centre, Hampshire, which had been awarded a lottery grant.
Minutes later, Mrs Kiellor became an instant millionaire - 10 times over.
Mrs Kiellor, her son Peter, 37, his wife Mo, and their 11-year-old twins Peter
and David were gathered in the living room of her home in Havant, Hampshire.
The family started celebrating after Mo, 40, made sure Mrs Kiellor had the
winning numbers - and the grandmother herself was overwhelmed.
``She got very excited. I just sat there,'' said Mrs Kiellor yesterday, who
confessed to feeling ``all mixed up'' as she arrived to collect her massive
cheque at a London hotel.
Mrs Kiellor had been a winner with a lottery scratch card shortly before
scooping the jackpot.
Her son David, 33, who shares Mrs Kiellor's #40,000 ex-council home with his
pregnant wife and two daughters, bought her winning draw ticket at a local
supermarket - and won her #40 on an Instants card at the same time.
The pensioner, who admitted money had been tight, now plans to spend part of
her win on buying herself and her sons new homes.
``I want a little bungalow on a hill,'' she said. ``I don't know which hill
yet.''
She also planned to share money among her family, saying: ``I want to get the
children set up.''
Mrs Kiellor added that a foreign cruise with Mo was high on her list of
priorities.
She said her husband Harry, a technician at Marconi, had died 15 years too
early.
``I just said the other day it's a shame he isn't here to enjoy this.''
After talking to reporters, Mrs Kiellor, David and Peter rode off in a carriage
drawn by two white horses to Hyde Park, where she was presented with her cheque
by lottery organisers Camelot.
The champagne was flowing as they posed for photographers, but Mrs Kiellor said
she would rather have a cup of tea.
A pensioner neighbour said of Mrs Kiellor: ``She's a lovely lady and is really
fond of her grandchildren. She's very kind and it could not have happened to a
better person.''
</TEXT>
