<DOCNO>GH951206-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be a mistake to read much historical significance into the wave of
strikes crippling France. This isn't 1968, the communists have lost such
authority as they had, and the socialists, as usual, don't know what to do or
say. If this is revolution, it wants a vanguard.
Besides, many of the people refusing to work not so long ago voted for Chirac
and believed, despite all the evidence, that a cure for unemployment was his
first priority. According to a Gallup poll for L'Express, 62% of the French
``disapprove'' of their President now, but in June the figure was only 32%.
Equally the asinine Alain Juppe, trying his hand at resolute Gaullism, had only
30% of the electorate against him in the summer; now 64% could see their Prime
Minister far enough.
The Marseilles dockers are out nevertheless, and the Renault workers have
walked off the job. Railmen, postal workers, and teachers have struck. From
placid Burgundy come the first signs that private-sector workers are joining
the defence of jobs and welfare and failing to give much of a toss for
Maastricht convergence criteria, or the government deficit accrued, in large
part, because politicians of all parties maintained that a strong franc had to
be defended no matter what.
In Britain, where we still believe in fairy tales, there is a persistent myth
that industrial militancy died with heavy industry. This is convenient for all
parties, since it allows them to devote themselves to reducing social costs -
to making people worse off, in other words - without bothering about the social
fabric. British workers work longer hours for lower wages than almost all their
European counterparts, but if the economy fails to prosper that is, somehow,
their own fault, to be paid for by cuts in welfare.
Thus even - or perhaps especially - Labour will have nothing to do with trade
unionists who strike. Tony Blair is delighted to hear of Frank Field's
ingenious schemes to privatise pensions but he would go a long way to avoid a
striking railway or postal worker. What would he make of the unrest in France,
you wonder? Doubtless he thinks that there, but for the grace of Lady Thatcher,
go I.
A penchant for marches aside, there is nothing that really distinguishes French
public-sector workers from their British peers, after all. The fears are much
the same: of a health service destroyed, of an admired rail network ruined, of
pensions and job security ravaged. A Labour administration would inherit the
pent-up anger of the Thatcher years, and sooner rather than later. Or so Blair
must fear.
Much is expected of him, after all, yet the most he has offered is
inspirational rhetoric. He promises change, but the substance of his project
amounts to a declaration that most things, union legislation not least, will
stay the same. When voters wake up, his approval ratings will doubtless go the
way of Chirac's, however pliant trade union leaders prove to be.
In essence, the upheaval in France is symptomatic of a European problem. Among
politicians in every part of the Continent there is consensus, particularly
over inflation and welfare costs, but it is not one in which voters share.
Unemployment has ceased to be a blight on the labouring classes and has become
the spectre haunting all. No job is safe, no future secure. All the education
and training programmes in the world would be too little and too late.
To that extent, at least, it is impossible not to admire the French.
Our shabby politicians, ministering to an increasingly shabby society, can be
as disdainful as they like about a people who refuse to accept ``reality''.
The chances are, however, that their refusal to put up any longer with brutish
incompetence will strike a chord with a British population that long since lost
faith in the political process.
Not so long ago it was fashionable in France to despise the veterans of May,
1968, for their complacent nostalgia and their middle-aged smugness.
Even now the French students marching to preserve their universities wouldn't
thank you for the comparison. Yet if the analogy could be made (and why
bother?) it would not count for much. France shows two things: that times
change but people do not, and that you cannot, even with all the power of the
state, abolish shared hopes and human dreams.
Thirty years from now, with luck, the veterans of '95 will remember those
simple truths.
</TEXT>
