<HEADLINE>Duchess's  jewels stolen. Royal gems may be recut</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE were fears last night that the diamonds in a necklace and bracelet stolen
from the Duchess of York, part of a wedding present from the Queen, could
already have been recut and placed on the market.
The antique jewellery, valued at #250,000, went missing from the duchess's
luggage during a flight from the United States to London.
The diamonds would find a ready market, according to London underworld sources
- no matter how hot the provenance. It is said the necklace and bracelet had
been in the royal family for generations.
The duchess was not travelling with her jewels while returning from a
promotional visit to America to launch her Budgie the Helicopter products.
She had flown on ahead to London on Concorde, because of an engagement, said
Buckingham Palace. She had to attend a Children in Crisis carol service at
Southwark Cathedral in south London with the Duke of York and their daughters,
the Princesses Eugenie and Beatrice.
The duchess had entrusted her luggage and jewels to her dresser, Mrs Jane
Dunn-Butler, flying on later scheduled flights.
The luggage containing the jewels was last seen disappearing down a luggage
conveyor belt at National Airport in Washington.
Airline officials had told Mrs Dunn-Butler that the suitcase containing the
Queen's wedding present was far too big to take on board the aircraft as hand
luggage.
The theft was reported to the police by the duchess at 11pm on Monday when she
unpacked
her luggage at her home at Kingsbourne on the Wentworth estate near Ascot,
Berkshire.
It has been reported that while Mrs Dunn-Butler is distraught about the matter,
the Duchess of York is not too upset. She believes the necklace and bracelet
will turn up.
London's underworld, however, takes a different view. One Scots-born member
said last night: ``Ice is easy to move.''
Despite the notoriety of the crime, he said had he been involved he would have
expected to pick up #30,000 just for passing them on.
``Already they will have been taken out of their setting and recut.''
The duchess was interviewed into the early hours of the morning as Scotland
Yard launched its investigation.
The missing pieces are part of a set presented to the duchess by the Queen on
her wedding. They are described as matching sets with clusters of diamonds and
are family heirlooms.
A ring and earrings are now all that remains of the set.
Last night the investigation seemed to be centred on Heathrow, an airport which
over many years has gained the not undeserved reputation that it should be
renamed Thiefrow.
A spokeswoman for the duchess said last night: ``The duchess thinks they will
probably get them back. She is quite relaxed, but obviously these items have
sentimental value because they were a present from the Queen.''
A British Airways' spokesman said: ``We have launched an urgent investigation,
in hand with the palace and police.''
Mrs Dunn-Butler has been with the duchess for the last seven years. ``The
Duchess wants to make it clear that she does not in any way hold Jane
Dunn-Butler responsible for what has happened. She has been a loyal member of
staff for many years,'' said a spokeswoman.
The duchess wore some of the now stolen jewellery at a White House reception
given by President Bill Clinton and his wife Hillary on Sunday.
The first leg of Mrs Dunn-Butler's journey from Washington to London was on
board a United Airlines aircraft. At New York she changed to a British Airways
flight.
Last night an expert in the jewellery and precious metals industry said:
``Quite frankly, these diamonds could be anywhere in the world by now.''her
