<HEADLINE>10,000 jobs in NHS at risk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CUTS in administration costs ordered by the Government could result in 10,000
NHS management jobs being lost, it was estimated yesterday.
Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell ordered #300m to be cut from red tape over the
next 12 months, and spent instead on patient care.
He claimed that his blitz on bureaucracy - which applies to both health
authorities and trusts - would mean ``more white coats and fewer grey suits''
in the health service, but refused to state the number of jobs involved.
However health officials said a typical managerial salary was #30,000, putting
the number of jobs at risk at 10,000.
On the same basis some 600 jobs could be at risk in Scotland after Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, the Scottish Health Minister, announced his contribution
yesterday.
His call for 5% - approximately #4m - to be cut from health boards'
administrative budgets follows a similar demand on NHS trusts announced by
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth in October, which would yield #14m.
The Government was immediately attacked by its opponents for creating the
red-tape mountain as a result of the 1990 reforms, and a trade union official
warned that the axe was liable to fall on lower-echelon staff making a genuine
contribution to patient care while the ``fat cats'' remained at the trough.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said that NHS administration costs
had risen by #115m a year in Scotland since 1991.
``These figures are absolutely breathtaking,'' he said. ``They show bureaucracy
in the NHS has risen by almost 50% since the Tories introduced their crazy
internal market.''
However Mr John Lambie, health officer for Unison, which represents health
workers in nursing, manual, and white-collar grades, said: ``It is not widely
understood what is meant by senior management.''
``Where people are encouraged to have personal contracts you will find that
someone who was an administrator yesterday will become a senior manager today.''
Apart from the three island health boards, administration costs per head of
population served range from #10.50 a year (Lanarkshire and Ayrshire and Arran)
to #18.80 (Highland).
The big spenders in overall terms, Greater Glasgow and Lothian, come about the
middle of the league in spending per head.
A spokesman at Lothian said that the board had already carried out a programme
aimed at cutting back administration in the terms being required.
Greater Glasgow said that following the decision to reduce administration costs
in trusts, it was already working on plans to change its own organisation and
to accommodate the target.
The Scottish Office said that some of the relatively expensive boards would
need to deliver higher savings than others.
</TEXT>
