<HEADLINE>Solicitor wins law firm case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Scottish law firm has lost an unfair dismissal and sex discrimination
case brought against it by a female solicitor.
Mrs Eileen Paterson, 36, of Pollokshields, Glasgow, is believed to have been
offered compensation by the firm.
Mrs Paterson was fired by Ross Harper &amp; Murphy after refusing to do night-time
and weekend call-outs to visit clients in custody.
Yesterday, an industrial tribunal in Glasgow released an advance notice
deciding in her favour.
Last month, Mrs Paterson, who is married to advocate Robert Skinner and has two
young children, told the tribunal she was removed from the rota after her first
child was born nine years ago.
The tribunal heard evidence that lawyer Mr John Carruthers, 34, who managed
Ross Harper &amp; Murphy's criminal business at their Ingram Street head office in
Glasgow, introduced a new policy last December requiring Mrs Paterson to go
back on the rota.
Managing partner Cameron Fyfe claimed it was essential for Mrs Paterson to be
on the call-out rota because it created ``bonding'' between clients and lawyers
by having the lawyer who spoke to them in the cells also represent them in
court next day.
However, in his final submissions, Mr Jack Quar, representing Mrs Paterson,
rejected Mr Fyfe's ``bonding'' theory and said: ``It was not anything to do
with the case. It was more to do with the public relations of Ross Harper &amp;
Murphy. He made good play of calming down clients in cells, something he had
little experience of.''
Mr Fyfe admitted to the tribunal that he hadn't investigated Mrs Paterson's
domestic situation before deciding to get rid of her.
Evidence was also given that another lawyer in the firm didn't visit clients in
their cells because he couldn't represent them in court as he became ill at the
prospect of cross-examining policemen in the witness box.
Mr Quar said yesterday: ``I am delighted at the decision and so is my client.
We were never in any doubt that the tribunal would find in our favour.''
A spokesman for Ross Harper &amp; Murphy said there had been discussions with Mrs
Paterson regarding settlement of the case before the judgment.
He added last night: ``This has already been agreed in principle between both
parties and we have agreed that her application will be withdrawn.
``We are very hopeful that the matter can be concluded to the satisfaction of
both parties in the very near future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Robertson given cold shoulder for lunch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is no such thing as a free lunch in Scottish politics, as Mr Michael
Forsyth discovered to his cost yesterday, after accidentally excluding his
Labour Shadow George Robertson from the top table at an official function in
London.
The slight was enough to set tongues wagging at Westminister: had the new-look
``listening'' Scottish Secretary exacted revenge for the drubbing he received
from Labour last week over his constitutional plans?
At the lunch in honour of the Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church
of Scotland, Mr Forsyth and his wife Susan were joined at their table by SNP MP
Margaret Ewing, Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace, Northern Ireland
Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew, President of the Board of Trade Ian Lang, and The
Herald.
However, in a radical departure from tradition for this annual, all-party
event, Mr Robertson and his wife Sandra, who travelled from Scotland to be
there, were left out, and found themselves in another room with junior MPs and
the man from the Scotsman.
By tea-time, Mr Forsyth had apologised in person to Mr Robertson for what was
an inadvertent mix-up. A Scottish Office spokesman said: ``This was an informal
lunch. No doubt Mr Robertson will be invited to join the Secretary of State in
future years.''
Although he was said to have been surprised by his treatment, Mr Robertson was
being diplomatic about the affair last night and would say only: ``The
Secretary of State told me it was a mistake''.
The mistake may come at a cost, as observers claimed it was proof of
deteriorating relations between the two men as the devolution debate
intensifies.
Mr Forsyth's colleagues last night were swift to retaliate by pointing out that
Mr Robertson left before the closing speeches, in which the Moderator, the Rt
Rev James Harkness, warned politicians not to deny the Church its right to
speak on current affairs.
Earlier, Mr Harkness, on his annual St Andrewstide visit to London, gave a
sermon at the Commons in which he evoked the sacrifices of those who lived
through the Second World War and called for a rediscovery of the spirit of
service.
In a message of comfort for Mr Forsyth, who has been accused of failing to
deliver on devolution, Mr Harkness said Jesus never avoided issues: ``He stood
out for what was good, honourable, and true whatever the cost in unpopularity,
even when the cross loomed ahead.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's magic and they mean it . . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart McINtosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN they run out of inspiration for their marketing brochures, many estate
agents would admit that they can sometimes lapse into an over-poetic hyperbole
that prompts them to describe a house as: (a) a hidden gem, (b) an
architectural treasure, (c) a place of of special magic.
Aberfeldy-based agents Finlayson Hughes have come up with all three in their
sales campaign for a house in Perthshire. But this is no flight of fancy - the
Old Library at Keltneyburn, seven miles west of Aberfeldy, has the lot. The
house was originally built as a traditional estate cottage and then converted,
around 1880, into a library and reading room. It is believed to have been
designed by James MacLaren, an architect who pioneered the use of the Arts and
Crafts style in a distinctly Scottish manner.
After serving as village hall from the 1950s, neglect set in and the building
fell into dilapidated condition and has been virtually derelict for the last 20
years. But it has now been triumphantly brought back to life as a dwelling by
Blairish Restorations, a firm with an award-winning track record in in
conversions in Perthshire. Since both the interiors and exteriors are listed,
the old reading room had to be restored as it once was - including panelled
walls, stained glass, plasterwork and fireplace.
Such is the quality of the restoration, the property has been shortlisted for
an important award. And, along with its distinguished architectural predigree,
the house has its own touch of magic. It sits in its own ``fairy dell' above
the fast-flowing Keltney Burn - viewable from  its own platform over the stream.
Accommodation comprises: living room, three bedrooms, kitchen, bathroom, and
shower room. The back of the house has been extended to provide a large, glazed
dining room and bedroom opening on to the viewing deck. Finlayson hughes is
inviting offers over #150,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
