<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ten Labour MPs break ranks to make protest over Budget measure Left-wing defies Blair and votes against 1p tax cut</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEN left-wing Labour MPs voted against the 1p income tax cut at the end of the
Commons Budget debate last night in defiance of party leader Tony Blair's
orders to abstain.
They joined Liberal Democrats and Scottish and Welsh Nationalists in opposing
the cut, but the Government won by 313 votes to 38, a majority of 275.
The 10 Labour MPs were: Tony Benn (Chesterfield), Ronnie Campbell (Blyth
Valley), Jeremy Corbyn (Islington North), Denzil Davies (Llanelli), Dr Lynne
Jones (Birmingham Sellyoak), Terry Lewis (Worsley), Eddie Loyden (Garston), Max
Madden (Bradford West), Colin Pickthall (Lancashire West) and Dennis Skinner
(Bolsover).
The Labour leadership had decided to abstain on the tax cut plan in an attempt
to shed its image as a ``high tax, high spend'' party.
The outcome is good for Mr Blair as the majority of left-wing MPs decided to
toe the party line.
The party last night played down the scale of the rebellion. A spokesman said:
``Only 10 people is a very good result. As far as we are concerned, this is a
very small number of people. It means 260 MPs have abstained.
``After the campaign we have conducted against the 7p increase in taxes under
the Tories, it was not right to have voted against today, and the overwhelming
majority of the Parliamentary Labour Party accepted that.''
Labour Chief Whip Donald Dewar said the 10 rebels would not be disciplined.
``They are all well known to take an idiosyncratic line,'' he said.
The SNP opposed the increase in petrol tax, but was defeated by 305 to 40, a
Government majority of 265.
Earlier, Labour's bid to cut VAT on domestic fuel and power from 8% to 5% - the
minimum permitted under EU rules - was defeated by 307 to 290, a Government
majority of 17.
Then a technical vote to pave the way for all the Budget measures to be
introduced was backed by 315 to 285, a Government majority of 30.
Winding up the five-day Budget debate, Chancellor Kenneth Clarke said the
Government had made ``big progress'' towards its aim of a 20p basic tax rate.
He warned of Labour: ``Handing over to them a great economic recovery would
take us back to recession in a very short time indeed.''
Shadow Treasury Chief Secretary Andrew Smith said: ``This Budget fails the test
of investment, of prudence, and of fairness.''
Earlier, deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine argued that Labour would bring
in a top rate tax of 60p in the pound, claiming that Labour Front Bencher Nigel
Griffiths, MP for Edinburgh South, had put down a parliamentary question on
November 2 asking the Chancellor what the yield would be from introducing such
a rate.
There was some confusion as Mr Heseltine described Mr Griffiths as a Shadow
Treasury spokesman - he is in fact a Trade and Industry spokesman - but Mr
Heseltine countered: ``If I have revealed I wasn't sure he was a Treasury
spokesman, have I revealed something else? That there is a split within the
Labour Front Bench between the Treasury trying to keep expenditure down and and
some other departmental responsibility trying to find the money to pay for
increased expenditure.
``I don't mind which way it is, all I tell the people of this country is that
Labour is planning a 60% tax rate and they are doing the calculations on that
basis.''
For Labour, deputy leader John Prescott said: ``We have made very clear that we
disagree with the general strategy of this Budget, and we have showed
specifically . . . the opportunity to reduce VAT on fuel.''
On Mr Heseltine's claim that Labour was planning a return to a top rate of tax
of 60%, Mr Prescott insisted: ``I have made it clear that we are not prepared
to return to those penal rates.''
Intervening earlier, SNP leader Alex Salmond asked Mr Prescott to explain why
Labour had abstained on a Scottish Nationalist bid on January 21 to reduce VAT
on fuel and had called it a ``cynical ploy''.
To Tory cheers, Mr Salmond demanded: ``Why was it a cynical ploy in January but
right tonight?''
Tory ex-Minister Sir Peter Lloyd (Fareham) said that instead of the 1p tax cut,
he would have preferred the money to have been used to cut the Public Sector
Borrowing Requirement.
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Alan Beith invited Sir Peter to join his party in
voting against the 1p tax cut.
He said: ``The Government was right to identify as priorities education, crime
and health. But close examination reveals the Budget doesn't shift more money
to schools, hospitals or the police.''
For the SNP, Mr Salmond told why his party was voting against the reduction in
the basic rate of tax. ``It is quite reasonable after 21 Tory tax rises -
that's #1000 a year for the average family - for the Chancellor to give back
some of that money to the people he has taken it from.
``If it's #3bn, that's fair enough. But a choice has to be made as to how that
#3bn would be best spent.''
He said the SNP's choice would be to bring the current 20p lower rate of income
tax down towards 15p instead of reducing the basic rate from 25p to 24p.
q During the debate, Mr Heseltine went on the offensive over the impact a
Scottish parliament would have on inward investment. He claimed that England,
Wales and Northern Ireland would be the direct beneficiaries from the ``tartan
tax.''
The Deputy Prime Minister told the House: ``As I understand the Scottish
dimension, the cost of an assembly in Scotland would be of the order of 3p in
the pound.
``That would be the tartan tax, the cost the people of Scotland would have to
pay. The effect on inward investment in Scotland would be dramatic but it
would, of course, be hugely advantageous to England, Northern Ireland and
Wales, because we would get the inward investment that socialism in Scotland
would deter from going there.
``Those are the obvious consequences of a Scottish assembly and that is why I
do not expect to see it happen.''
Earlier, at Question Time, replying to Tory Bill Walker (Tayside North), the
Prime Minister said: ``If the devolution plans proposed by the Opposition
parties were to proceed, they would undoubtedly lead to conflict between
Scotland and other parts of the United Kingdom.''
</TEXT>
