<DOCNO>GH951206-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Muster goes out with #235,000</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRENCH Open champion Thomas Muster crashed out in the first round of the Grand
Slam Cup in Munich yesterday - but still picked up around #235,000 for his
trouble.
Struggling with injuries to his right hip and left foot, the Austrian never hit
top gear as he was beaten 7-6, 2-6, 6-1 by Zimbabwe's Byron Black.
But, as a grand slam champion, Muster walked away from the richest tournament
in the game with around #165,000 simply for turning up, and another #70,000 for
being a first-round loser.
In the quarter-finals Black, a replacement for injured American Andre Agassi,
faces Boris Becker, who played with the nerves of his home German fans before
clinching a 6-1, 6-7, 9-7 win over Frenchman Cedric Pioline.
The 28-year-old former Wimbledon champion's serve-and-volley game is perfectly
suited to the fast indoor court. Becker, fresh from victory last month at the
ATP Tour world championship, will be a much harder opponent than Muster.
The 16 players with the best records in the four Grand Slam events in a year -
the Australian, French and US Opens, and Wimbledon - are invited. Other results:
Goran Ivanisevic (Croatia) beat Petr Korda (Czech Republic) 7-6 (7-3), 6-3;
Jacco Eltingh (Holland) beat Michael Chang (USA) 7-6, 6-3.
q BRITISH No.1 Clare Wood reached the second round of the Challenger event in
Paris yesterday, beating Christina Papadaki (Greece) 7-6 (7-4) 6-4.
TENNIS
</TEXT>
