<DOCNO>GH951206-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trapped by the siege of Paris</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028266</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I CYCLED 10 miles home through Paris, weaving in and out of traffic, and did
not see a single car move: around 6pm the entire city had congealed into a
monstrous traffic jam. All the way down the Boulevard Saint Michel across the
Ile de la Cite past the Palais de Justice, to the Chatelet and northwards, past
the Pompidou Centre, each crossroads was a snarled mass of vehicles, often so
tight that even wheeling a bike through them was impossible.
Westwards, near to the church of Saint Augustin, two bemused and
worried-looking coachloads of Cockney tourists clambered down into the road to
leg it to their hotel.
On the whole trip I saw only two policemen attempting point duty. Everywhere in
the city, Parisian motorists, usually so short-fused and snappish, were taking
the strain with an unnatural calm born of fatalism. The jam only began to clear
four hours later.
Without buses or suburban trains or mainline trains into the big stations, with
dozens of potential customers for every taxi, and without the Metro, whose
locked gates have forced the city's tramps into the cold, where they beg at
busy crossroads, getting around Paris is everybody's obsession.
It is an exhausting one. People living out of town are getting up in the early
hours to brave several hours of congested traffic on roads leading into the
city. The private coaches hired by the Government to supply some semblance of
transport leave their pick-up spots in the suburbs at 5.30am.
Bicycle shops have sold out, and Paris has a touch of an old university city -
the jangle of bicycle bells and the squeaking brakes of old and ill-maintained
bikes are new sounds. Banks close early in the afternoons as employees try to
beat the hours of jams which await them later on. The city's museums have
closed down altogether, for lack of staff to maintain them. Yesterday, groups
of Japanese tourists braving the snow and sub-zero temperatures, posed for
photographs at the entrance to the Musee d'Orsay, for a souvenir of sorts.
Sales of newspapers have dropped dramatically - not because supplies are
failing to get through. But because people no longer have Metro and bus rides
during which to read them. Police have stopped giving parking tickets and
fines, and motorists have started leaving cars anywhere and driving through
traffic lights regardless of the colour.
In addition to weariness, the strike has brought its own sort of chaos and
day-to-day improvisation. Roller-skaters, skateboarders, and even people on
motorless children's scooters weave in and out of traffic, irrespective of
one-way streets and skirt between the heels of pedestrians on the packed
pavements.
Hitch-hiking inside Paris is a whole new pastime. The bateaux mouche tourist
boats on the Seine are ferrying up to 1000 people at a time, free of charge, up
and down the river. With everybody suffering from fatigue, cancelled or missed
appointments, not to mention the crush, the cold and the pollution of so many
cars, there is even a new spontaneity and friendliness among fellow sufferers
on the streets. Everyone has horror stories to swop but people's anger is
directed more against the Government than against the unions.
Paris theatres are all but empty and cinema attendance is down by 70%. Big
hotels are hard-hit by a drop in clientele but smaller ones are packed solid
with out-of-town workers who prefer the extra expense to the misery of
travelling. Spending in shops has been reduced by half, even if last weekend,
motivated by some sort of consumer masochism, thousands came into town to visit
Christmas displays in the big department stores.
Firms are arranging for their employees to share cars - ``le car pooling'' as
it is called. Radio stations have phone lines to put passengers in contact with
drivers. Coach companies are lining their vehicles up, illegally, in front of
train stations, to attract passengers for provincial cities.
And more and more people are staying at home, working via telephone and fax.
They call it ``le tele travail'' in French and it will probably be one of the
long-term results of the strikes.
Nicholas Powell gets on his bike as Paris grinds to a halt
</TEXT>
</DOC>
