<DOCNO>GH951206-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Richards wants to make peace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIV Richards has offered to help settle the dispute between Brian Lara and West
Indies cricket officials.
Lara pulled out of the current tour of Australia at the last minute after
having been fined, with three other players, by the West Indies Cricket Board
of Control for misconduct during the recent tour of England.
``I carry no weight with the board,'' said Richards, ``but I am so dismayed by
the affair that I volunteer to mediate in an attempt to get a batsman, better
than I was, back on track to help West Indies mount a serious challenge for the
1996 World Cup. They need only to pick up a phone.''
Lara withdrew from West Indies' tour of Australia because, it is believed, he
was upset at being penalised for an incident he thought had been settled by the
tour committee in England.
Richards thinks the special privilege granted to Lara to return to Trinidad in
June - just a few weeks after the tour started - has come back to haunt the
WICBC.
``In allowing Lara to quit the England tour briefly and return home on private
business, the board set a precedent that bred more resentment than I have known
in a tour party,'' said Richards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peers defeat Howard on probation training</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was hit by a surprise defeat in the Lords last night as peers
insisted, by 108 votes to 85, on higher standards of training for probation
officers.
The first defeat of this session followed strong criticism from peers of all
parties, including Tory former Home Secretary Lord Carr of Hadley, of Home
Secretary Michael Howard's new system for probation training.
New rules that came into force this week end the requirement for probation
officers to take a two-year social work course. It will be replaced by a
National Vocational Qualification with some higher education content.
Peers, led by former senior Home Office civil servant Lord Allen of Abbeydale,
demanded that the new rules ``ensure that the proposed higher education element
of the required training of probation officers will lead to a professional
qualification which is of a high standard, and is subject to external
validation''.
There were cries of ``resign'' from the Opposition benches when the result was
declared.
A Home Office spokesman said later: ``We will reflect on the points made during
the debate.''
It is unlikely that last night's result will have any major effects on the
Probation (Amendment) Rules.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Penny drops after church receives token offering</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL contributions are welcome when the church collecting plate goes round but
some donations are more interesting than others.
The priests at St Cadoc's Church in Halfway, Cambuslang, were intrigued to find
this week among their offerings a coin which appeared to be an old penny. On
closer examination it was revealed to be not a coin of the realm but a token
with the inscription ``They recorded every man a penny.'' Around a
triangular-shaped symbol were the letters TKSHTWSS.
The penny dropped, so to speak, when the words ``Lodge R.R.A.No.116'' were also
to be read on the coin. It was surmised that the coin had some sort of masonic
connection, but how had it ended up in the collection plate of an RC church in
the West of Scotland, not an institution one would immediately associate with
freemasonry?
We checked with the Grand Lodge of Scotland, where a nice and not at all
secretive chap called Martin McGibbon, Grand Secretary, explained that the
artefact was most likely a mark token. These tokens are issued to mark the
progress of a mason through the craft. The Lodge R.R.A.No.116 was most likely
Rutherglen Royal Arch.
So how did it end up in the collection plate of a Tim place of worship? It was
probably a case of someone ``putting their hand in their pocket and including
the token by mistake with their loose change''.
But in Catholic St Cadoc's? Mr McGibbon pointed out that contrary to some
public opinion many members of the freemasonry brotherhood might ``attend such
a church''.
It looks as if we're Halfway to ecumenism.
Family affair
WE place entirely no significance whatsoever on the information that on the
occasion of the Labour Party conference on local government in Dundee last
weekend, at the Thistle Hotel, where the conference-goers were to be found
socialising, the music was provided by a band called Mafia.
Military stardom
THE Diary was puzzled to hear some of the foot soldiers of the Amalgamated
Union of Engineers and Electricians and Plumbers, or whatever it is called
nowadays, refer to Sir Gavin Laird, their dear and recently pensioned-off
general-secretary, as The Brigadier.
Sir Gav recently took early retirement in return for a deal which gave him a
#30,000 lump sum and his salary until he retires at 65. He will also keep on
the extra-curricular activities, of which there are many since he was and is
one of the busiest boys on the trade-union scene. These include directorships
of such as Scottish TV, Greater Manchester Buses North, and the Edinburgh
Investment Trust.
But it is Sir Gav's devotion to queen and country which has earned him the
military sobriquet. He is a member of the Armed Forces Pay Review Board whose
remit is to advise on pay and conditions for our soldiers, sailors, and
air-people to make sure they keep pace with equivalent jobs in civilian life.
As such, Sir Gav has to travel to inspect armed forces locations and talk to
the troops. In the Services, travel, accommodation, and your tea are organised
strictly on the basis of rank. The civilians who become involved are allocated
a notional rank.
In his senior position on the pay review board, Sir Gav is equivalent to an
army brigadier. Hence his nickname. His friends in the engineering union might
also like to know that Sir Gavin is the equivalent of an air commodore in the
RAF and a commodore in the Royal Navy.
This is a one-star rank compared with the five-star status of a field-marshal.
We wouldn't bet on Sir Gavin getting promoted all the way.
Designs on the job
WHEN Glasgow City Council advertised the post of director of its 1999 year of
architecture and design celebrations, it was obvious that the winning candidate
would come from a small, not to say incestuous, group of people qualified to
run such a beano. But just how small and incestuous is indicated by some of the
names on the short list of five to be interviewed this week.
Candidates for the attractive five-year post (salary not yet specified but the
budget for the whole show is about #8m) include one Rory Coonan and Victoria
Thornton. Mr Coonan is currently director of the architecture division of the
Arts Council of England which was in charge of handing out the title of city of
architecture. Mr Coonan was one of the officials who set up the scheme and
assisted the judges in their deliberations as to who should win it.
Ms Thornton, education officer with the Royal Institute of British Architects,
was one of the judges.
Surely some mistake
DEPT of We Think We Know What They Meant: A news release from East
Dunbartonshire Liberal Democrats tells how pleased Mr John Morrison is to be
selected to stand against sitting Labour MP Sam Galbraith in Strathkelvin and
Bearsden. In fact, he says: ``I am erroneously privileged to carry the Liberal
Democrat standing in this constituency......''
Nice try
IN festive mode, we flicked through the list in this month's issue of Scottish
Rugby which details what stars of the game want for Christmas. David Hilton may
be sleepless with anticipation on Christmas Eve, waiting for Santa to deliver
his Scalextric set. We were not shocked to read that Kenny Logan lusts after a
Barbie doll. Rob Wainwright is not asking for much - ``10,000 acres of the West
Highlands. Knoydart would be nice, but anywhere would do.''
Confusion looms
WE mentioned classroom confusion when a teacher asked pupils about their
parents' jobs. A Hawick correspondent is on with a story about a new teacher in
this Borders town of many hosiery mills who made the mistake of asking this
question and was bamboozled by replies including ``a twister'', ``a greasy
binder'', and ``a bar-filler''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Procurator-fiscal pitches into the louts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jock Brown</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO the procurator-fiscal is involved in football again. The football
authorities seem to think it is an unwarranted intrusion into their own little
world. But it has become increasingly obvious that there has been a total
failure to control loutish behaviour on football pitches. Until football takes
the necessary action to keep its house in order, I fear we need Crown
intervention. I would much prefer that not to be the case.
In 1987 the procurator-fiscal in Glasgow fired the opening warning shots in the
Butcher, Woods case.
The message was clear. Behaving badly and contrary to the law on a football
field carried no immunity from the rigours of the law, and a clear opportunity
emerged for the Scottish Football Association to take the initiative in
ensuring there need be no further involvement on the part of the police in
football matches. They failed to take it.
The sense of responsibility expected of every citizen extends to footballers at
work. There is no doubt that players consent to the risk of injury when they
take the field - injuries resulting from tackles made in the course of the
match. They do not consent, however, to calculated assaults by boot, head, fist
or elbow, and it is surely in the public interest for such behaviour to be
rooted out of society wherever it happens.
After the warning shot in 1987 came Duncan Ferguson, a player who, sadly, had
come to the attention of police on earlier occasions unconnected with his
footballing activities. Here he was, on probation, head-butting an opponent.
The football authorities, belatedly, by virtue of the report of the referee
supervisor, tried to head off the Crown with a swingeing punishment
administered without considering the best evidence available, namely the video
evidence, and ignoring the fact that the police inquiries were well underway.
But was it in the public interest for the procurator-fiscal to call to book a
citizen on probation for an assault which breached that probation, even though
the offence took place on a football field? Of course it was.
Discussion is now continuing about whether guidelines should be issued by the
Crown. They would be welcome. Let's hope such guidelines differentiate between
on-the-ball offences, which should be the domain of the referees, and
off-the-ball offences, which could be of interest to the police.
Thus the over-zealous late tackle which may cause injury to an opponent should
be dealt with by the referee but felling your opponent with a right hook to the
chin 50 yards from the action should be dealt with not only by the football
authorities but also by the police. There is surely no injustice there.
The cry for such guidelines has grown louder following the most recent
involvement of the procurator-fiscal - at the Rangers v Aberdeen match on
November 11 and then at the Partick Thistle v Aberdeen match on December 2. The
timing shows that the Crown's patience is wearing thin. Think of it; 1987 to
the Ferguson case in 1994, and now the latest quick response to on-field
indiscipline in November and December 1995.
All these incidents took place in Glasgow. That prompts the suggestion that the
procurator-fiscal in Glasgow is exercising his discretion differently from his
counterparts elsewhere. That may be so, but many of the high-profile games are
played in Glasgow and if you want to make a point in the public interest,
choose a high-profile game.
If you are a high-profile footballer, then with the high salary comes the
high-profile responsibility.
Throughout, the Scottish Football Association has remained consistent in one
particular aspect - they are not prepared to consider what is usually the best
evidence available, namely video evidence. In these circumstances how can
anyone have faith in football's capacity to deal with its own problems when it
maintains the charade of ignoring such evidence. It is interesting now that the
SFA Council will consider the question of video evidence early in 1996.
So what about the players and their employers accepting some responsibility? It
is club officials who sit on the SFA disciplinary committee, and clubs play a
major part in the constitution of the Scottish Football Association. They have
the solution in their hands - to ensure a code of conduct among their players
which must be honoured, and, if breached, the culprits denounced and punished
swiftly.
Further, the current SFA rules could permit a player to be cautioned 16 times
before he is suspended. Cautions are rated on a points level from 1 to 3. If a
player commits 16 one-point offences only then would he be suspended. In Italy,
the equivalent number is 4. Their system is to employ an independent magistrate
who sits every Wednesday to rule on the weekend's activities and issue
appropriate suspensions and punishments. Any appeal is dealt with on the Friday
and there can be no spurious appeal designed to ensure a player is available
for a vital match coming up that weekend.
In football, we have even had the incredible situation where a player is
virtually encouraged to be booked in certain matches to take himself over the
points limit and have a suspension served prior to a major match in the future.
How can anyone, quite apart from the Crown, have any faith in such a system.
Football must get its house in order. It is only in the wake of initiatives
from the procurator-fiscal that this appears likely.
Football is the national sport and plays a very important part in the lives of
a huge number of Scots. It is a major interest, a discussion point, a release
from day-to-day drudgery and even from social deprivation. It is critical to
the fabric of Scottish society.
In these respects, our thanks are due to the procurator-fiscal.
q Jock Brown is a sports broadcaster and a sports law consultant with Harper
Macleod.
Jock Brown argues that football has failed to clean up its act and can hardly
complain now that the procurator-fiscal has stepped in to do it
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prescott taunted over poem about kiss</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEPUTY Labour leader John Prescott (above) was taunted in the House yesterday
over the poem, A Political Kiss, by New Zealand author Fleur Adcock. Published
in the latest edition of the Poetry Review, it is a fantasy about Mr Prescott.
Deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine read an extract, to Tory laughter: ``In
the dream I was kissing John Prescott, or was about to kiss him; Our eyes had
locked, and we were leaning forward avidly forward, lips out-thrust, certain
protuberances under our clothing brushing each other's fronts - when my mother
saw us, and I woke up.''
Mr Heseltine commented, to renewed laughter: ``I must say it was a merciful
release for somebody.''
Fleur Adcock has already shared a passsionate moment with one of Mr Prescott's
parliamentary colleagues, it emerged yesterday.
She says in the poem that she has never actually kissed an MP, but Labour MP
Austin Mitchell admitted he had a ``long passionate, unforgettable embrace'' 35
years ago with Ms Adcock, when they were both at the University of Otago.
Mr Mitchell, MP for Great Grimsby, said: ``I suppose Fleur would say I was not
an MP at the time. Well, I am now. She was librarian at the university and I
was a lecturer in history. It was after a university party.
``She may have totally forgotten the occasion, but I haven't. How could I?''
Mr Prescott has declined to comment on the poem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TRYING TO LOSE A FEW PONDS</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOMETIMES the grandest place names turn out to have rather prosaic meanings.
Near St Boswells in the Borders, ``Tripondium'' sounds as if it might have
connections with the Roman invasion - in fact it's just a posh name for a trio
of recently-created fishing ponds.
The site, along with planning permission for a farm house, is being sold
through the Kelso office of FBR Ltd and the Edinburgh office of Knight Frank &amp;
Rutley at an asking price of over #95,000.
Located about 40 miles south of Edinburgh, Tripondium offers the opportunity to
develop a private home with its own field, established wood . . . and, er,
ponds.
Alternatively, it could be developed as a self-contained business with three
fishing ponds and holiday chalets on the 35-acre site. Outline planning consent
for the holiday chalets has been granted by the local authority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government `broke Post Office pledge'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was accused last night of deliberately breaching its commitment
to grant the Post Office greater commercial freedom, following a Treasury
decision to almost double the amount of profits it claws back each year.
Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman Malcolm Bruce said a pledge given in May by
the-then President of the Board of Trade, Mr Michael Heseltine, had been
ignored in favour of the ``short-term interests of the Tory Party''.
Figures published in last week's Budget show the amount the Post Office will
have to hand back to the Treasury over the next three years has been increased
from #524m to #925m as part of the Government's efforts to find money to pay
for tax cuts.
Mr Bruce today will table questions in the Commons in an effort to force the
Government to concede that it has broken its promise to keep the figure - the
External Finance Limit (EFL) - ``at about half the Post Office's forecast
pre-tax profits'' in this year's Budget.
Under last year's plans, the Post Office was to have paid the Government #178m
over the next three financial years, roughly half its #472m profit before
paying corporation tax. Instead, it will have to come up with #298m in 1996-97,
#317m in 1997-98 and #310m in 1998-99.
Post Office managers claim the Treasury's larger-than-expected slice of their
profits will sharply reduce the amount they have available to invest, and may
lead to a 1p increase in the price of first and second class stamps next year
after a two-year price freeze.
Mr Bruce said Mr Heseltine's statement in May, after the Government failed to
persuade its back benchers to back Post Office privatisation, had been supposed
to usher in an era of greater commercial freedom for the company.
``It is now clear that in their desperation to buy votes with tax bribes, the
Government has decided to dump the commitment to let the Post Office keep 50%
of its post-tax profits and is determined to milk it for all the money it can
decently get its hands on.
``The result will be higher prices for stamps and less investment in this key
industry. Yet again, we see how in this Budget the national interest comes
second to the short-term interest of the Tory Party.''
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday insisted it remained committed
to achieving an EFL of 50%, and made clear the decision to increase the figure
over the next three years was imposed by Treasury Ministers.
A spokeswoman said: ``The Government remains committed to the May statement,
but the objective will take longer to achieve than planned.
``All of us recognise that the public expenditure round this year has been
extremely difficult, with pressure for additional savings.''
A Post Office spokesman said the ``huge amount'' of money the Treasury will
draw from the Post Office's forecast profits will force the organisation to
seek efficiency savings, and will ``almost inevitably'' lead to an increase in
the price of stamps.
In his May statement Mr Heseltine said: ``Although no responsible Government
could undertake to ring-fence the Post Office entirely from the pressures on
public spending, I am prepared to agree that in future we shall aim to set the
EFL at about half the Post Office's forecast post-tax profit.''
He added: ``I hope to make progress in that direction this autumn.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Campaigns boost sales Caledonian enjoys 23% profits rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CALEDONIAN Publishing, which owns The Herald and Evening Times, raised
operating profits by 23% to #10.2m in the year to end-September.
The increase in profits was achieved in spite of the fierce newspaper price war
and an #800,000 increase in newsprint costs.
Even though newsprint costs are set to rise by another #3m in the current
financial year, Caledonian expects to achieve a slight increase in trading
profits.
After interest charges of #5.4m, Caledonian, the management buy-out company
which acquired The Herald and Evening Times from Lonrho in May 1992, made
pre-tax profits of #4.7m. It made a #2.8m loss in the previous period, after
taking a #5.8m exceptional hit for redundancy costs and the move to electronic
pagination.
Turnover was up 3% at #60.5m.
Caledonian, which began printing the Scottish Daily Mail on January 9, brought
in more than #1m of revenue and #321,000 of profits from this activity.
Liam Kane, Caledonian's chief executive, highlighted the success of The
Herald's recently-launched radio and television advertising campaign and of the
promotional campaign to boost sales of the Evening Times.
During the year to end-September, the average daily circulation of The Herald
was down 3584 on the previous 12 months at 107,259.
However, the advertising campaign boosted average daily sales to 110,633 in
October from 104,712 the previous month. Sales in November were maintained
around the 110,000 level.
Mr Kane said: ``Under new editors, they (The Herald and Evening Times) are
looking better, have much more to read in them and are attracting new readers.''
He added: ``We are pleased to have managed a creditable performance in a very
difficult market, with cover price cutting squeezing us from one side and huge
rises in the cost of newsprint squeezing us from the other.''
Mr Kane believed Caledonian Information &amp; Media Services (CIMS), which has put
The Herald and Evening Times on the Internet, was one of the most exciting
developments anywhere in the British newspaper industry. CIMS has also launched
prestigious clients such as Bank of Scotland on to the Internet.
Commenting on recent press speculation, he said Caledonian had not received a
bid and was not in talks with any potential purchaser.
Referring to the recent #85m sale of Scotsman Publications to David and
Frederick Barclay, Mr Kane said: ``It is unlikely that any of our shareholders
would be excited by a pro-rata bid for Caledonian.''
Acknowledging that flotation had been held up by the Daily Telegraph's decision
to join the newspaper price war, Mr Kane envisaged that Glasgow-based
Caledonian might be able to come to market in the ``early days of a new Labour
Government or a revitalised Tory one''.
He said Caledonian might consider the acquisition of one or two metropolitan
morning newspapers prior to flotation, adding: ``A larger, weightier vehicle
should be easier to float and easier to get the right price for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NIE continues to make progress</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE electricity company reporting season continues with Northern Ireland
Electricity (NIE) announcing an 8% increase in interim pre-tax profit to
#47.7m. Controllable costs were reduced in real terms by 6% per unit sold.
Chairman David Jefferies said the continued progress had been achieved even
though the recovery of #10.1m of allowable costs was postponed. The 14.9% share
buy-back in August, at 397p, boosted earnings per share and further benefits
are expected over the full year.
The proposed 250MW Scottish interconnector represents a major investment for
NIE and is expected to be an important source of revenue.
NIE is one of the few remaining independent electricity companies. Despite the
encouraging trading statement its shares dropped 9p to 450p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prost's technical role at McLaren</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALAIN Prost will be driving for McLaren Mercedes next season, though not in
Grand Prix races.
The Frenchman, who quit Formula One two seasons ago after winning his fourth
title, had fuelled speculation that he was about to return by taking part in
practice sessions. But McLaren announced yesterday he will join the team next
year only as part of their background technical group.
``There is no question at all of Alain Prost racing for us next season,'' said
McLaren spokesman Norman Howell. ``He will be driving our cars, but not in
Grand Prix races.''
Prost said he would enjoy his new role. ``I am looking forward to working with
McLaren in such an exciting new position,'' the Frenchman said. ``It will be a
great challenge for me to take on the technical aspects of this role.''
McLaren managing director Ron Dennis said Prost would add his knowledge and
experience as an F1 driver for 12 years to help McLaren catch up technically
with Williams and Benetton, who have dominated the championship for the past
four seasons.
With Finnish driver Mika Hakkinen still recovering from head injuries sustained
during practice for last month's Australian Grand Prix, McLaren may have to
look for another driver to team up with Scot David Coulthard, who has switched
from Williams.
MOTOR RACING
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour plans to consult pupils on teaching</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCHOOL pupils are to be asked what they think of Labour's plans for Scottish
education when they are published early in the New Year.
Mrs Helen Liddell, who speaks for Labour on Scottish education, said the party
plans a major consultation exercise on its key framework document for schooling.
She said it was important to consult pupils because they would experience the
impact of Labour's plans in the event of the party forming the next Government.
The Monklands East MP was speaking after party leader Tony Blair yesterday
outlined Labour's programme for raising standards in English schools.
Mrs Liddell made it clear, however, that the framework document would have
Scottish solutions to Scottish problems. Some of the key English proposals draw
from current Scottish education policies, including capping class sizes,
emphasising the importance of homework, forging stronger home-school links, and
introducing school development plans.
Mrs Liddell said she was at one with the Labour leadership on raising
standards. ``The issue of standards will be up front. We have to celebrate the
achievements of Scottish education,'' she said.
The Scottish document will focus on the ethos of schools - the characteristics
which make them effective - and how the value which they add to the experience
of pupils can be measured meaningfully.
Mrs Liddell said it was crucially important to equip pupils with the basic
skills needed for a rapidly changing world.
At yesterday's launch, Mr Blair ran into trouble with the teachers' unions for
claiming that three out of 10 English schools were failing.
He said: ``There is no more important issue than raising standards in our
schools, particularly the 30% of schools that are failing.''
According to the English inspections body, the Office for Standards in
Education, only about 2% of schools are failing to deliver adequate education,
while about 10% are said to have serious weaknesses. It said 30% of lessons
were unsatisfactory.
The general secretary of the National Association of Head Teachers, Mr David
Hart, said: ``Labour's policy seems to be based on false statistics.''
Labour's proposals for English schools include:
q Launching tougher appraisal for heads and classroom teachers and streamlining
dismissal procedures for those who are not succeeding.
q Introducing more adults - drawn from business, the professions, and local
communities - into classrooms as ``teacher associates'' working under the
guidance of teachers.
q Introducing a maximum class size of 30 for pupils under seven and ensuring
access to a computer for every child.
q Strengthening home-school links through new associations.
q Setting minimum standards for homework, with each seven-year-old expected to
do half an hour a night.
q Requiring local authorities to produce education development plans, with
goals for improvements based on school-set targets. There would be sanctions
against those which failed to meet the targets.
Shadow Education Secretary David Blunkett said the programme would produce a
``quantum leap'' for standards, offering excellence for the many, not the few.
In a newspaper interview yesterday, Mr Blair said: ``In the past, we have been
accused of being more concerned with equality than excellence, of being more
interested in meeting the demands of the teaching unions than the demands of
parents. From today, no-one will be able to make that accusation.''
</TEXT>
