<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>That touch of quality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
QUALITY Street's latest venture in the west of Scotland is extensive internal
refurbishment of its flats at The Waterfront. The first phase has just been
completed, and Glasgow service team-leader Jim Rennie was on hand to show off
the changes.
The first thing to point out was that Glasgow has to reach, or surpass,
standards in other parts of the UK. Your busy executive flat-renter wants the
best going, wherever he is.
He also wants that pleasant feeling of luxury - as in new light and airy decor,
polished beech flooring, and interesting trees and plants (in large pots on a
spacious landing); not to mention fine prints of Richard Akerman's work inside.
Pleasant, soothing, but not distracting. Good to relax with, beside the latest
satellite TV, video and CD stereo systems.
For the first tranche of flats the theme is carried in striking cane furniture
- with tall Rennie Mackintosh-style chairbacks. Designer kitchens have polished
beech floor and maplewood units; and what used to be called white goods are now
the latest in stainless steel appliances.
QS has spent up to #8000 per flat on this refurbishing spree. But it's not
grudged. Quality is a necessity, the company insists.
Demand for two-bedroom flats at The Waterfront - a popular place - is normally
steady. It's interesting that the new situation is creating a strong demand
also, even at prices from #950 a month. The first units were effectively
pre-let before the work began. There are still decisions to be made, of course.
Do you want a utility room, or a dressing room as an extra?
Letting is all about meeting customer needs. And that's why Glasgow is one of
the areas where QS is offering homes available for rent by the week. The usual
period is six months minimum. So, rent by the week is on the menu at London,
Bristol, and Glasgow - for executives who don't fancy hotels. And new leasing
arrangements are also available, from one month to a year, with not only a more
flexible arrangement but a much-simplified format.
According to Paul Mugnaioni, this is probably the first time in the UK such
easy-to-understand and comprehensive leases have been made available. It's what
customers want. It's also a pilot scheme that can be extended as interest
develops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Racal pushes its income up by 28%</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RACAL Electronics lifted profit 28% to #30.1m in the six months to mid-October
and confirmed its purchase of British Rail's communications business for
#132.7m.
BR Telecommunications has a network of 27,000 kilometres of cable providing
phone and data links for the rail network. The deal will double the size of
Racal's existing network services division.
Racal's data communications division raised trading profit to #3.43m. The
contribution from Racal's 22.5% share in the Camelot lottery consortium came to
#8.2m.
Radio communications' profit dipped 16% to #9.3m. There were lower orders for
major strategic systems and margins suffered from increased competition.
Defence and radar trebled profit to #8m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rail regulator demands assurances on investment</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rail regulator, Mr John Swift, QC, is demanding assurances from Railtrack
about its investment plans for the coming year after the disclosure that the
company has boosted its pre-privatisation balance sheet, by setting aside
#1.4bn which could have been spent immediately on Britain's railways.
He may also invoke his right to require Railtrack to keep its accounting
records in a specific way which will allow him to take decisions on its charges
for access to the network and will ensure that the accounts accurately
represent ``the underlying financial position of the company.''
His concerns are set out in a letter to Labour Transport spokesman Brian
Wilson, who wrote asking him to ensure that money paid in access charges is
used for the purpose intended - investment and maintenance of track and
signalling.
Mr Wilson last night called for the postponement of Railtrack's privatisation
until all questions relating to its accounts are resolved. He said it would be
``monstrous'' if privatisation took place on the basis of the single year's
accounts now available.
Mr Swift's letter to Mr Wilson states that he is putting in place monitoring
systems and will take any necessary action to ensure that Railtrack's customers
enjoy the improvement in performance they are entitled to expect under the
terms of the access agreements,
Mr Wilson said ``This letter leaves no doubt that the regulator recognises that
Railtrack's accounts leave a great deal to be desired.''
FEARS that privatisation will mean a less safe railway increased yesterday when
the Government's chief rail inspector confirmed that privatisation was
``inevitably accompanied by uncertainties and risks''.
The situation was aggravated by news that the Health and Safety Executive's
railway inspectorate had deployed all 25 rail inspectors plus ``other accident
prevention specialists'' to monitor Railtrack and its contractors.
In addition to his warning on ``uncertainties and risks'' Mr Stan Robertson,
HSE chief inspecting officer of railways, says in his annual report that the
industry has been restructured ``to a form never previously seen'' and that
with more than 100 separate units heading for privatisation ``many more
companies will be pressing their own interests''.
Labour's spokesman Mr Wilson said the report provided the ``deeply depressing
warning of what lies ahead if fragmentation of the railways continues........
an inherently less safe railway is being put in place in the name of political
dogma''.
The main thrust of the report was that although safety standards were being
maintained so far there was no room for complacency.
The report showed that:
q.The number of train accidents fell from 977 in 1993-94 to 907 in 1994-95,
with significant accidents - those potentially the most dangerous to passengers
- falling by eight to 110.
q.The total number of people killed on the railways, excluding trespassers and
suicides, rose by two to 42.
q.Fatal accidents to passengers increased by one from 16 to 17.
THE Government's rail privatisation policy would not survive a free vote in the
Commons, according to a new poll which shows that nearly a fifth of Tory MPs
want a rethink on the issue.
A survey, carried out for the pressure group Save Our Railways, also found that
two thirds of Tories believe rail privatisation to be unpopular with the
travelling public and 37% think it will be a key election issue.
The findings of the poll - conducted between October 27 and November 17 by
Business and Planning Research International - were disclosed yesterday in
advance of tomorrow's return to the High Court when the pressure group will
apply for a judicial review which it hopes will delay rail privatisation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rave debate for Ayr</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth said last night that Ayr should be the
meeting place for a cross-party Parliamentary committee debate on new measures
to protect young people at raves.
Three people have died from the effects of taking ecstasy at the Hanger 13
dance venue in the Ayrshire town. Mr Forsyth said the town had ``sadly
experienced the tragic consequences of drug misuse at dance events''.
He said he would recommend that a special standing committee of MPs would come
to Ayr early in the New Year, to discuss the new Bill designed to protect the
health and safety of young people at raves.
People involved in the rave scene, local doctors, community workers, local
councillors, and members of the public are likely to be among those asked to
give evidence to the committee. Under Mr Forsyth's plans, more powers will be
given to licensing boards to impose conditions with which rave organisers must
comply before getting the go-ahead.
Last night, Labour's home affairs spokesman John McFall described the move as
``long-overdue."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP faces winter in the cold. Labour romps to record poll lead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was last night celebrating one of its biggest ever leads in 20 years of
System Three polling for The Herald, with its 57% standing being hailed as a
vindication of its UK performance and its home rule campaign.
Our poll puts Labour 36 points ahead of the SNP, which had closed the gap to
just 16% only two months ago in what was ascribed to the summer's Braveheart
factor.
Any failure to improve on this over the winter will lead to renewed criticism
from nationalist hardliners that SNP leader Alex Salmond's tactics are not
sufficiently hostile against devolution.
At the same time, one of the most energetic campaigns ever waged by a
Conservative administration at the Scottish Office - with promises of
decentralisation coupled to dire warnings of the slippery slope to separatism -
has left the Tories mired in the same 13% rating for three successive months.
But there was an indication that Government and Opposition ratings at UK level
may have loomed large - the Blair versus Major factor. This comes with the fact
that fellow proponents of home rule, the Scottish Liberal Democrats, who might
have been expected to share in the home rule glory, have slipped two points to
just 8% in the poll.
The poll was carried out by System Three between November 23 and 28 among 987
respondents in 39 constituencies, and the results include a slightly higher
than usual proportion at 21% of those who could not or would not answer.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson was jubilant: ``Labour's record
standing in the polls is all the more remarkable given that we have the
four-party system in Scotland.
``This poll makes dismal reading for the nationalists, but is even more
worrying news for Michael Forsyth, given that he seems to be stuck on a
humiliating 13% in the polls despite the most hysterical campaign of lies and
disinformation ever launched against Labour.''
The Government always declines to respond to polls but Scots Tory chairman Sir
Michael Hirst said: ``The poll was taken before Michael Forsyth announced
significant changes in the governing of Scotland against which Labour cannot
find a credible argument.
``This poll also doesn't take into account the Chancellor's Budget which would
help save the average Scots family #9 every week. These savings would at a
stroke be wiped out in Scotland by Labour's tartan tax.''
The poll is a bitter blow to the SNP, which was riding high in our System Three
poll as recently as October, when its standing of 30% was the highest for years
and the gap of 16% behind Labour was least. In two months this has evaporated.
But party leader Alex Salmond said yesterday: ``The renewed constitutional
debate since this poll was conducted has been extremely positive for the SNP.
Now that the Scottish dimension is centre stage the SNP are determined to keep
it there and our support will grow accordingly.''
Last night Mr Andy Myles, chief executive of the Scottish Liberal Democrats,
said: ``This poll underlines the continuing unpopularity of the Government. In
particular it should tell Michael Forsyth that his tinkering with the
constitution is an electoral failure. He should stop this dangerous course of
action immediately''.
Labour's rating of 57% support is one of the highest in 20 years of The
Herald's monthly poll, and was achieved in January and July of this year. The
36 point gap represents a 20-point widening of the gap from two months ago.
SNP chief executive Michael Russell put a brave face on the result, calling it
the 49th consecutive month above 20% and pointing out that the survey dates put
the poll before both the Budget and last week's St Andrew's Day concentration
on constitutional issues.
He insisted: ``Over the past two months, the British dimension has dominated.
Now that the Scottish dimension is dominating, the SNP relish the opportunities
to advance in the months ahead.
``We are now in a position to contrast the very real benefits of independence
in Europe with the Convention's puppet assembly scheme, and the Tories'
hopelessly inadequate reforms.
``Labour are vulnerable to a high-profile SNP campaign, as previous poll
figures show, and we have as much support as the Tories and Liberals added
together. Michael Forsyth will be extremely disappointed to have made no impact
whatsoever on the Tories' dismal ratings.''
But Scottish Labour general secretary Jack McConnell said: ``This swing in
opinion shows that Labour's campaign and ideas have caught hold in Scotland. We
have defended Scots for three years against the extremes of this Government.
Voters recognise the benefits that have been achieved.
``This is a vote for real change, not just in the constitutional, but for
social and economic change at the heart of government.''
Mocking past SNP attempts to coin vote-winning slogans, he quipped: ``The
nationalists are in a fix for '96 and after three months in a row, 13 is
obviously a very unlucky number for Michael Forsyth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Top Euro rookie passes US test</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF
THE PGA European Tour, whose strength has been diluted by the transfer of
allegiance to its United States counterpart of Nick Faldo and Sweden's Jesper
Parnevik, who are soon to be joined by Sandy Lyle, has been further reduced.
Parnevik's compatriot, Jarmo Sandelin, has survived the final qualifying school
just completed in Florida.
Sandelin, Finnish-born and aged 28, was chosen as Europe's 1995 Rookie of the
Year. He won the Canary Islands Open, had four first 10 placings, including two
as runner-up, and finished No.21 with #173,000 in prize-money. He was equal
twenty-ninth in the six-round endurance test held at Bear Lakes Country Club in
West Palm Beach.
The three other Europeans in the starting field of 190 were not among the
leading 40 players and ties who earned their cards. Another Swede, Mathias
Gronberg, finished equal seventy-third and his countryman, Robert Karlsson, and
Ulster's David Feherty failed to make the four-round cut.
Perhaps the outstanding achievement was Andy Bean's. The hulking 42-year-old
former Ryder Cup player was one of six players in equal thirty-seventh place.
The winner of the competition was a 24-year-old Virginian, Carl Paulson, who
had failed to retain his card in this season's campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hendry makes it 13 wins in a row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD champion Stephen Hendry completed his thirteenth successive victory in
the first round of the German Open in Frankfurt yesterday. Hendry beat Joe
Swail 5-2 and today faces Tony Drago for a place in the quarter-finals.
But the Scot found the atmosphere in Frankfurt so different to Preston Guild
Hall where a capacity crowd of 1200 watched him defeat Peter Ebdon 10-3 in the
UK Championships final on Sunday. ``It was so difficult to keep going
considering there were only a handful of spectators,'' he said.
Hendry was close to going 3-1 down. He won frame four only on a respotted black
after overturning Swail's 58-point lead.
John Higgins, second to Hendry on the provisional ranking list and this time in
the opposite half of the draw, beat Chris Small 5-2. Scotland's Alan McManus
beat Welshman Mark Williams 5-1 while Ronnie O'Sullivan, 20 yesterday, lost to
Romford's Mark King, who meets Higgins today.
Other first-round results (English players unless stated):
K Doherty (Ire) bt D Reynolds 5-3, J Parrott bt M Clark 5-2, D Morgan (Wales)
bt B Snaddon (Scot) 5-4, bt N Bond bt W Thorne 5-0, P Ebdon bt Y Merchant
(India) 5-2; S James bt J White 5-3, S Davis bt D Finbow 5-2.
q HOPES of saving next week's #60,000 Belgium Masters appear bleak.
Difficulties have arisen over the non-inclusion of James Wattana and Alan
McManus. A final decision will be made today.
SNOOKER
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Royal's challenge is successful</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Bank of Scotland has successfully challenged a decision by the
Banking Ombudsman through the courts, the first time a member of the ombudsman
scheme has done so.
The case related to a complaint against the bank in 1992. The Royal said that
in his original finding against it, the Ombudsman held that where one customer
paid a cheque from another of the same branch into his account the mere making
of computer entries to the customer's account meant the cheque had been paid
and could not thereafter be bounced.
In a lengthy written judgment, the Scottish Court of Session judge Lord Penrose
rejected this view, stating that the real question was whether the bank had
taken a decision to pay which it had proceeded to implement by making the
transfers between accounts.
The court decision was a blow to the Ombudsman, Laurence Shurman, coming on the
day he published his 1994-95 annual report. This showed that compensation
payments ordered by him in favour of disgruntled bank customers jumped 29% to
#901,000 in the year to September.
Derek Arnott, chief legal officer for the Royal Bank, said the judge had upheld
the group's view that the reasoning behind the Ombudsman's decision was
``fundamentally flawed''. He added that the judgment was ``consistent with
accepted banking practice and removes the doubts which had arisen''.
The Ombudsman has the power to make binding awards against members of the
scheme, but the latter reserve the right to have important test cases heard
before the courts. When this happens the member pays legal costs, which the
Royal has done.
The number of telephone inquiries and complaints in 1994-95 was about the same,
at 18,667, as the previous year, but the total of those looked at in more
detail fell 16% to 6723 and the number accepted for full investigation was down
a similar proportion to 717.
Full investigations resulted in compensation to the customer in 44% of cases,
the same as the previous year. Amounts varied from #10 to #70,000, with the
average up 70% to #2483.
Mr Shurman said there were ``good signs'' that banks were getting better at
dealing with complaints themselves. For the first time in years those relating
to cash dispensers did not top the list. Instead, mortgage-related matters,
which accounted for 15% of the complaints investigated, took this distinction.
Cash dispensers came second at 12%. Mortgages and lending together accounted
for a quarter.
A typical complaint related to underfunding of the mortgage, with the bank
miscalculating the required monthly repayment by, for example, excluding the
capital element in a repayment mortgage. After several years, the mortgage
holder would find that he or she had repaid none of the loan. In other cases,
the bank failed to institute an endowment policy as the customer had expected.
An example given in the Ombudsman's report concerned a bank customer in
Perthshire who remortgaged on stated monthly repayments of #652. After the
remortgage had gone through, the bank said they would be #777. The customer
claimed for the cost of the remortgage of #4000, including early redemption of
the previous loan, plus #38,000 for the additional payments over the length of
the mortgage.
Applying Scots law, the Ombudsman decided the customer was entitled to the
benefit of the original offer. However, this applied only for the first three
years of the loan, during which the interest rate was capped. The Ombudsman
awarded #8777.
</TEXT>
