<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thornton has to wait for ruling from judges</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SARA Thornton's hopes of being cleared of murdering her drunken husband hung in
the balance yesterday after three appeal judges reserved judgment on her case.
Thornton's appeal, on the basis she suffered ``battered woman syndrome'', has
become a cause celbre for women's rights campaigners.
Her bail was renewed yesterday pending the Court of Appeal's ruling.
Thornton, 38, of Atherstone, Warwickshire, was jailed for life in February 1990
for murdering her husband Malcolm with a blow from a kitchen knife as he lay
drunk on a sofa.
Her original appeal was rejected in 1991 but her case was referred back to the
Court of Appeal in May this year and she was released on bail on July 28.
Her lawyers have produced evidence that she was suffering from ``battered woman
syndrome'' and a personality disorder which together made her vulnerable and
liable to suddenly ``snap'' under the stress of prolonged abuse at the hands of
her alcoholic husband.
However, Crown counsel Brian Escott Cox QC said yesterday the violence and
threats Thornton had suffered were ``very sporadic'' over a limited time.
Mr Escott Cox referred to evidence from Mr Thornton's son Martin that on one
occasion Thornton threatened his father with a kitchen knife, and had to be
disarmed.
On the night of the killing, before going out for a drink with Martin, she
wrote in lipstick on the dressing table mirror: ``Bastard Thornton, I hate
you.''
The stabbing incident later did not involve raised voices, a frenzied attack or
multiple wounds, Mr Escott Cox said.
</TEXT>
