<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The scenic route to Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephaine Davis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE traditional image of Christmas is the sight of the munching family gathered
round the television watching the Queen's speech with a devastated table in the
background sporting the skeleton of a turkey, stray brussels sprouts and some
crumbs of Christmas pudding.
It all looks so cosy and comforting, but what exactly is it that provides that
aura of contented luxury so peculiar to Christmas?
The tree, of course, plays a major part in setting the scene. There are two
camps here. The artificial brigade haul theirs from the cupboard where it has
been stored for the past 50 weeks and set it up in its usual glory. The
realists, however, moan that they miss the refreshing scent of woodland pine,
and unless the carpet is scattered with pine needles then the true atmosphere
is lost. Moderates usually settle for a dipped tree and a blast of pine
fragrance air freshener.
If you really don't have time, or are simply not interested, decorated trees
both natural and artificial are available by the foot at garden centres and
most department stores. You can even have one delivered right into your living
room. But if you still have some Christmas spirit, there's no doubt that great
fun can be had from doing it yourself. Whatever your choice of tree, there's no
excuse for it looking anything less than superb because the shops are
overflowing with packets of ribbons, bows, glitter and tinsel.
First of all make sure you have enough lights to make a good show and define
the shape of the tree, and test them before you put them on the branches. Then
mix and match standard coloured sets with more unusual and eye catching shapes,
such as snowmen or Santa figures. A fairy or shining star on the top, a shimmer
of irridescent garlands, bows and baubles, and your living area is lit up. As a
final touch, wrap a few old shoe boxes and cereal packets in Christmas paper to
hide the tree stand.
Carrying on the greenery theme, if you want to introduce an element of log fire
cosiness, and you have a substantial mantel, then a decorated garland of
foliage is ideal. Make sure it's roughly the same shade of green as the tree,
and if possible, try to match up any ribbons or bows. Again there's a natural v
artificial argument, and although many magazines claim these garlands are
simple to make using fresh foliage, they can look a bit challenging. Like
trees, they can be bought in fresh or artificial form from garden centres and
department stores. Some stores even have them made up in the standard swag and
tails widths so that they can be draped along the curtains as well. Smaller
plants also have Christmassy associations, and they make good-looking
decorations. Poinsettias, with their remarkable red leaves, and winter cherries
are inexpensive but look effective on shelves or small tables. In the case of
the winter cherry, make sure it's placed well out of reach of small children.
The indispensable form of foliage at this time of the year has to be mistletoe,
traditionally hung from light fittings in the hall and sitting room. If you
want to play safe, incorporate yours into a candleholder, so that you know
where it is and need only get caught when you want to.
Table decorations are becoming increasingly adventurous, not only are there
loads of varieties of centrepieces, but the actual cloths, napkins, and glasses
are becoming increasingly customised. If you don't have a dishwasher, or just
can't be bothered with the mess of crockery and don't mind a paper plate, you
can eat your turkey from a variety of holly and ivy nests, a Rudolph platter,
or even some Christmassy Mickey Mouse types.
Matching cups and glasses take care of the drinks, there's co-ordinating
cutlery, and the only effort that's needed to clear up the debris is a quick
run with a plastic bag. Once you've got the table looking splendid, a striking
centrepiece will put the icing on the cake. Musical miniature Christmas trees
are the most popular, but there are lots of quite substantial candle holders
with varying amounts of glitter and greenery, which can serve as decorations in
their own right in other parts of the room before being drafted into a starring
role on the table on the day itself.
The finishing touch for the table layout has to be crackers, and it's worth
spending a few bob on a decent box, so that they look good on the plate, the
paper hats fit more than a six-year-old, and the meal doesn't fall flat before
it's even been served.
One of the most striking Christmas decorations is the lighted candle bridge,
which seems to have enjoyed a massive jump in popularity in the past three or
four years. This looks most appealing when placed, as the old song says, in the
window, and given that all you have to do is put it on a suitable surface and
plug it in, it has to be the most cost-effective Christmas decoration in terms
of labour that has ever been invented. To get the most from it, put it beside a
bunch of seasonal fresh flowers and it will illuminate them perfectly.
And for that final touch to add the spirit of Christmas? As well as the well
stacked festive cocktail cabinet, go one better and toast the season with some
champers, but don't bubble over in terms of cost unless you really want to.
There's seldom been such a comprehensive selection of good sparkling wines to
suit every pocket, and no matter how much you've spent, if you lash out on a
floor-standing ice bucket, complete with a sprig of holly, you can be sure of
oozing style at least.
Seeing your home take on a stylish and festive look is everyone's aim, and
Stephanie Davis finds that you needn't empty your purse or your reserves of
energy in the attempt
</TEXT>
