<HEADLINE>Seagull rescuer gets damages from driver</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A `GOOD Samaritan'' was knocked down by a car as he tried to rescue an injured
seagull from a busy road.
Andrew MacDonald's good deed left him with a broken leg and face cuts.
Yesterday, he was awarded #12,500 damages after he sued the driver of the car
which struck him in Harbour Road, Inverness, in February 1992.
Inverness Sheriff Court heard that Mr MacDonald, of Torr Gardens, Dores, by
Inverness, stopped to rescue a seagull fluttering about on the road.
After lifting the bird into the safety of a garden, Mr MacDonald returned to
his car.
As he was about to open the driver's door he heard the bird squawk and feared
it may make a lunge back on to the road for a nearby bread roll.
Before he could move the bread, he was struck by the oncoming car, driven by Mr
Alexander Ross, of Culduthel Road, Inverness.
Mr Ross claimed Mr MacDonald had been crouched beside the car and he couldn't
see him.
Sheriff Donald Booker-Milburn accepted Mr MacDonald's version, that he had been
standing upright, and that there had been nothing to prevent Mr Ross from
seeing him.
The sheriff said: ``It is probable that he failed to notice Mr MacDonald
because he was paying attention to the flow of traffic ahead being controlled
by a Stop/Go sign.''
However, he added: ``Mr Ross could easily have given Mr MacDonald a wider berth
and, had he done so, the accident would not have happened.
Mr MacDonald was reluctant to comment about his victory last night in case of
an appeal.
Mr Ross, 73, said: ``I obviously hit the man but whether it was my fault is
debatable. The police did not charge me.''
</TEXT>
