<DOCNO>GH951206-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sentence delayed on reformed addict</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN addict was caught with a large haul of drugs the day after he was jailed.
Prison officers found heroin, cannabis resin, diazepam, and Temazepam capsules
when they searched William McKay.
However, a judge showed McKay, 32, mercy yesterday after he admitted possessing
the drugs with intent to supply them in Barlinnie Prison, Glasgow, on January
12 last year.
Mr Murray McAra, defending at the High Court in Glasgow, said McKay was now
drug-free and counselling young addicts.
Mr McAra read out a letter from one teenage addict who wrote: ``It is a lot
easier to talk to Bill because he has been there and done it.''
Asking Lord Weir to defer sentence, Mr McAra said McKay had been an addict for
16 years but he added: ``His life has changed and he has become a powerful
voice for good.''
Lord Weir told McKay, of Sumburgh Street, Cranhill, Glasgow, that if he were to
sentence him on his record and for the offence, he would go to prison for seven
years.
The judge said it may be a risk but he was deferring sentence for six months to
see if McKay could keep out of trouble. In that event, said Lord Weir, he would
probably defer sentence for a further year.
Lord Weir continued the case to the High Court in Edinburgh on June 6.
Mr Colin Harris QC, prosecuting, said the prison governor got information that
McKay, who was in the prison hospital, possessed drugs.
McKay was taken from the hospital unit to a cell, where he produced a tobacco
tin from his trouser pocket. It contained heroin with a street value of up to
#2640.
Mr Harris said the officers searched McKay and found cannabis resin, 100
diazepam tablets, and 40 Temazepam capsules with a total street value of #690.
Mr McAra said that, the previous day, McKay had been jailed for 18 months at
the High Court in Airdrie for drugs offences.
When taken to the prison he was searched and no drugs were found on him.
McKay, who had suffered illnesses - including gangrene - from his heroin
addiction, was in the prison hospital when another inmate approached him.
This man threatened him with violence and gave him the drugs to deliver when he
was eventually transferred to ``A'' hall.
Under the arrangement, McKay was to keep some of the heroin for his own use.
Mr McAra asked the judge to discount the street value of the drugs as they were
found in prison ``where they are part of the prison currency''.
He said the lowest point of McKay's life was on his release when he tried to
commit suicide with an overdose of diazepam.
Since then he has attended Glasgow Community Drugs Project, which has
transformed his life.
Mr McAra said McKay, who is married with two sons, intends to stay off drugs
and devote his life to helping others do the same.
</TEXT>
