<HEADLINE>Snow moves north of border</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first blast of winter snow was heading north across the Border last night
after hitting England.
Some places in Scotland experienced the odd flurry of sleet during the day
yesterday but by evening snow was beginning to fall on higher ground in the
Borders, across Tayside, and into the Eastern Grampians.
A spokesman for the Glasgow Weather Centre said: ``Snow is likely to become a
feature, particularly in hilly areas down to a few hundred feet, by the
morning.''
A London Weather Centre spokesman said an easterly airstream, which originated
in the steppes of Siberia and picked up moisture over the North Sea, was to
blame.
In England, motoring organisations reported widespread problems yesterday as
snow and ice made many roads treacherous. East Anglia, Kent, and Cambridgeshire
were badly hit in the morning rush and again as beleaguered commuters struggled
home, by which time the freeze had also spread into many northern areas.
The AA and RAC last night reported problems on roads as far apart as Kent and
County Durham.
RAC head of campaigns, Mr Edmund King, advised motorists to check that their
cars had anti-freeze, to carry a blanket in case of breakdowns, and to allow
more time for journeys.
The snow came as bookmakers reported a flurry of bets on a white Christmas.
William Hill cut the odds against snow falling in London on December 25 from
10-1 to 8-1, while Ladbrokes slashed them still further, from 7-1 to 5-1, after
taking a #3500 bet from one punter in Acton, west London.
``The current 5-1 is the shortest odds we have ever offered in the first week
of December. We are certainly overdue a pay-out as we haven't paid out since
1976,'' said a Ladbrokes spokesman.
q.A squad of four navigation experts has been formed to reduce the death toll
on Scotland's mountains this winter.
The Scottish Mountain Safety Group will teach climbers the technique of using a
compass and map, how to spot avalanche conditions, and the use of ice-axes and
crampons.
Thirty people have died in the Highlands so far this year and a report has
shown that poor navigation and ignorance of avalanche conditions were major
contributors to the fatality figure.
England in a flurry - Page 13
</TEXT>
