<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTER-DISTRICT TOURNAMENT:
EDINBURGH fly south today to fire the first shots in the inter-district
tournament in an effort to prevent the Exiles from repeating last season's
clean sweep at the first time of asking.
Two hours later in Kirkcaldy (7pm) North and Midlands and Glasgow are in action
in a competition which is particularly relevant this season in light of places
in Europe next season probably up for grabs and, of more imminent interest,
competition for places in the national side very much on the agenda.
Glasgow, who had already lost Ian Jardine and Kenny Logan due to injury,
suffered another last-minute call-off yesterday when captain Fergus Wallace
fell victim to flu and was replaced by Jim Brough of Stirling County.
Wallace, who has recently recovered from the leg-break which sidelined him for
much of the premiership season, was keen to press his claim for advancement
during the inter-district series and is desperately disappointed to be losing
out again.
Edinburgh, too, are missing key players. For instance, injuries to hookers
Graham Ellis and Paddy Haslett mean that Grant McKelvie, of Watsonians, makes a
district debut and the Edinburgh selectors have also been denied the servies,
through injury, of Duncan Hodge, Graham Beveride, Jeremy Richardson, and Andy
Macdonald.
Nevertheless, coach Graham Hogg is confident that the Edinburgh selection is a
strong one and that his players all know that the championship is important.
Hogg, who favours districts in Europe - at least districts in some shape or
form which would cater for the country's top players - is convinced that if a
recognisable entity like Edinburgh were to get the nod from Murrayfield then
they would not be lacking in support and would be a combination with which fans
could identify.
Yesterday, the Exiles - who have just returned from training camp in Portugual
- were coy in the extreme about their future role in rugby life. Secretary
Fulton Paterson declared that all public pronouncements about tomorrow's game,
or anything else for that matter, were to come from SRU representative Iain
Laughland, who was en route to Scotland for a meeting, and selector Colin
Fisher, who was unavailable.
The Exiles' reticence is a symptom of the uncertainty which surrounds their
future should the inter-district championship fall victim to fixture congestion
and a revamped district set-up to take account of the European championship.
``We don't want players, or even the coach, Alistair McHarg, saying anything
that we might later regret and that is why everything has to be channelled
through Iain,'' said Paterson.
So, the Exiles will do their talking on the pitch. None will want to speak
lounder than Eric Peters, the Bath back-row man omitted from the Scotland side
which met Western Samoa.
He is at No.8 for the Exiles today, as will be Edinburgh's Stuart Reid, the man
who took his place in the national XV.
North and Midlands (v Glasgow, Beveridge Park, Kirkcaldy, 7pm) - R Shepherd
(Melrose); S Burns (Edinburgh Academicals), A Carruthers (Kirkcaldy), P Rouse
(Dundee High School FP), J Kerr (Watsonians); M McKenzie, K Harper; J Manson, R
