<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Design for the space age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OWNED on a 50/50 basis by Swedish interests and by General Motors, Saab is in
the annoying situation of seeing sub- stantially increased sales, which are up
by one fifth in the UK this year, hit by currency movements and its own heavy
investment in future model programmes.
Linked with the world's biggest vehicle manufacturer, Saab remains an island of
independent technical thought, and the industry needs as many of those as
possible.
It always seems curious that, while Saab is a Swedish-US company, its president
Keith Butler-Wheelhouse is British. But although its production levels mean
that it is, in world terms, something of a niche manufacturer, Saab has a
clearly defined customer base in each of its international markets. The idea of
Swedish design and build quality has its own appeal, and nobody elsewhere has
nationalistic hang-ups about it.
In the 9000 range the appeal is certainly not whizz-bang styling or an
extravagantly presented interior. Saab's larger model, available through the
range as a CD four-door or as a CS hatchback, costs between #17,995 and
#23,995, the higher figure being the price of both the very fast 2.3-litre
turbocharged Aero and the top-rated V6 Griffin.
In either body style the 9000 looks like what it is, an up-dated eighties
design. There are some ungainly lines at the rear of each body type, but they
can be forgiven because one of the great appeals of this model range is its
enormous boot capacity. The passenger cabin is very roomy too, to the extent
that when you settle comfortably in the back seats, you wonder why other
manufacturers in this class are so stingy with accommodation.
There is nothing flashy about any Swedish car interior, and the 9000 continues
that rather austere approach, in materials, colour scheme and layout, although
it has splashed out with two-tone upholstery in the cars with non-leather trim.
An excellent driving position features a low-set steering wheel. The 1996
fascia is virtually unaltered, although marketing logic would seem to suggest
that it is time for some change here. However, Saab is always reluctant to make
minor model-year changes just for the sake of offering something new to look at.
It shows no reluctance at all, however, when it comes to loading its cars with
top-class equipment as standard. All models in the 9000 range come with ABS,
twin airbags, dust and pollen-filtered ventilation, tinted windows with heat
absorbent glass, and many other features which make excellent sense and do not
rate simply as ``goodies''.
As somebody who once wrote for a motoring paper which had an anonymous car
thief as one of its other contributors, I know it is rash to make too many
claims for any manufacturer's security devices. But the Saab system, which is
standard on the Aero and Griffin, and a #400 option on other versions, seems to
be about as good as they come.
The main thrust of Saab's technical development at the moment is towards
second-generation turbocharging, not just as a source of enhanced power and
torque, but also as the best way - in conjunction with advanced engine
management systems and inlet manifold heating - towards reducing emissions.
The 2.3-litre light pressure turbo engine, peaking at a manageable 170bhp and
providing an instant ``lift'' when the throttle is opened, seems to be the best
choice in the 9000, since the two-litre version has a lot of weight to carry
around, and the full pressure jobs pour more power than I like through the
front wheels.
Prices vary from #20,495 to #23,895 according to equipment levels. The cars
using this power unit are lively and responsive when required, relaxed on
motorway runs, and they feel reassuringly Swedish-engineered.
Ross Finlay finds the Saab's roominess compensates for any ungainly lines
</TEXT>
