<HEADLINE>Scotland celebrates as lottery payment enables 30 major leisure projects to proceed. Sporting hand-out of #6.1m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028293</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PAYMENT of #6.1m from the National Lottery was being celebrated as a record
breaker by tens of thousands of sportsmen, women, and children in Scotland
yesterday.
The payment helped the Scottish Sports Council to make 30 awards to a wide
range of recipients.
Mr Graeme Simmers, the council's chairman, said: ``This is a wonderful
Christmas present for sport in Scotland.''
The awards were announced at a festive roadshow at Gyle shopping centre in
Edinburgh, attended by Mr Raymond Robertson, Scotland's Minister for Sport, and
sports stars including Yvonne Murray, Commonwealth 10,000m champion, world
cycling champion Graeme Obree, and former Scotland A rugby captain Kevin
McKenzie.
The biggest single award was #1.5m to help Tayside Regional Council towards the
#3.2m cost of developing the Maryfield sports complex at Dundee.
Councillor Charles Farquhar, convener of Dundee City Council's leisure and
recreation committee, said the complex would be Scotland's largest sports,
leisure, and physical education centre. It would benefit generations of
Dundonians and Taysiders.
Councillor John Wilson, Tayside Regional Council's convener of education, said
the complex was expected to be completed by August 1997. It would serve the
whole community and would be the only centre on this scale in Scotland.
The complex will contain two artificial grass outdoor pitches, an indoor games
hall, a gym, a health suite, and a seven-a-side grass football pitch.
Dalziel High School War Memorial Trust at Motherwell received #290,000 to help
provide floodlighting, a synthetic pitch, a running track, and an indoor
training area at the #647,000 Cleland Estate project.
Mr Brian Millar, trust chairman, said this announcement, coming on top of the
Chunghwa investment of #260m bringing 3300 jobs to Lanarkshire, had ``put a
happy face back on Motherwell''.
