<HEADLINE>Sales of shareholdings in privatised companies will help fund tax cuts Government nets #500m from sale of BP stake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government yesterday set the ball rolling on a series of sales of its
residual shareholdings in privatised companies that will contribute some #1200m
to its coffers.
It has sold its remaining 1.8% holding in BP for just over #500m and other tiny
holdings in the likes of British Airports Authority, British Gas, and Mersey
Docks, which are expected to bring in roughly #700m, will follow in due source.
Economists noted that the stakes will help to fund the Budget tax cuts without
the Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke having to dig too deeply into
the contingency reserve. This will leave him with more ammunition for further
tax cuts in his final Budget before the General Election.
The Treasury pointed out that it had always said that further privatisations
would raise #3000m this year. The lion's share of this will come from the sale
of the second tranche of shares in the electricity generators National Power
and Powergen and the sale of Government loans to the utilities. The balance
will be made up from the disposal of small residual shareholdings.
The BP move finally marks the end of the Government's holding in the oil
company. The 101 million shares were sold to investment bank SBC Warburg for
onward sale to institutional investors. The transaction took place after a
competitive tender organised by another investment house, Rothschilds. About
half the shares went to UK and European institutions and the balance to the
United States.
The Government made a little over #500m from the deal. Market sources indicated
that SBC Warburg had placed the shares at 513p. BP shares eased 14p to 517p.
The sale of first tranche of BP shares held by the Government was made almost
two decades ago in 1977 - under a Labour Government - and further sales
followed at intervals over the ensuing 10 years.
Rothschild is also arranging the sale of the other small shareholdings. The
next largest is a near 3% holding in BAA, the airports group, which is worth
almost #150m. The sale of these shares can also be expected to have some
short-term impact on BAA's market price. But some of the holdings, such as
those in several water companies are so small that they will have no impact.
The sales may be convenient from the Government's view to fund its tax cuts but
it is also a sensible time to sell anyway given the strong performance of the
stock market and there is no point in these small holdings being retained.
Meanwhile, senior Treasury officials cast doubt on hopes of an early cut in
interest rates yesterday by rejecting predictions of a sharp slowdown in
economic growth.
City analysts are warning that growth could grind to a halt in the fourth
quarter of the year and early in 1996 as firms respond to weak demand by
trimming output in a bid to offload excessive stocks.
They predict that the Chancellor will opt to boost growth by cutting base rates
from 6.75% at his meeting next week with the Governor of the Bank of England.
But Colin Mowl, the Treasury's head of economic forecasting, said any
destocking was likely to be spread over the next 18 months. Gross domestic
product was likely to expand by 0.4% in the fourth quarter of 1995 and
strengthen in 1996, he said.
He added: ``I don't think we would expect that one would reduce interest rates
to hurry up the speed of the stock adjustment.''
Mr Mowl was giving evidence on the Budget to the House of Commons Treasury and
Civil Service select committee.
His comments were reinforced by Treasury chief economic adviser Alan Budd, who
was upbeat about growth prospects.
Asked by Quentin Davies, Tory MP for Stamford and Spalding, whether Mr Clarke's
optimistic 3% GDP growth forecast for next year could be achieved without lower
base rates, he replied: ``Yes, I do think it's possible.''
Mr Budd added that the pound's recent weakness and strong growth in money
supply were unlikely to prevent Government hitting its sub-2.5% inflation
target although strong money supply growth could be a threat if it persisted.
</TEXT>
