<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Morrison enjoys a surge in profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORRISON Construction Group's dynamic approach to seeking out new business has
enabled it to buck the deep recession in civil engineering and house building.
The Edinburgh-based company doubled pre-tax profit to #3.18m at the half way
stage.
This was good news for investors who bought shares at 115p when Morrison was
floated on the Stock Exchange on October 6. The shares rose 2p to 123p
yesterday after Morrison met its pre-flotation forecast of interim profit in
excess of #3.06m.
Executive chairman Fraser Morrison attributed the company's success to its
strategy of seeking out new business without waiting for projects to come up
for tender.
``An increasing proportion of our work is self-generated or awarded on value
criteria rather than simply bidding the lowest price in open market tender,''
he said.
Morrison generates 60% of its work on this basis, often forming joint-ventures
with partners to attack problems. It aims to increase this proportion to 80% by
the end of the century.
``We see this as the key to the higher margins which we have secured in recent
years compared with the construction sector norm,'' Mr Morrison said.
Typical of these partnerships is a joint-venture with US engineering giant
Bechtel and North West Water to bid for the #45m Inverness and Fort William
water and sewerage project.
This will be a privately funded build, own and operate scheme under the
Government's private finance initiative (PFI). Morrison said the Government's
Budget announcement of an increase in PFI public works projects was encouraging
since the company was pursuing a wide range of PFI projects.
These include the #70m to #80m Leeds Supertram project. Morrison forms part of
a consortium that aims to bring trams back to the streets of the city.
The company made a profit in all its operating divisions during the first half,
despite a 3% fall in turnover to #98.1m.
Even the utilities and energy and the housebuilding divisions returned to the
black after losses in the first half of last year.
The key to success in housebuilding was Morrison's focus on grant-aided
projects in the lower sector of the market. Its houses typically sell for only
#45,000 to #50,000.
Edinburgh broker Bell Lawrie White is pencilling in full-year taxable profit of
#10.5m, up from #7.6m in 1994-95.
There is no interim dividend for shareholders who joined the company at
flotation, but it has promised a year-end payout.
</TEXT>
