<DOCID>GH951206-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>That sinking feeling as Yarrow fights for survival</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028296</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YARROW Shipbuilders' economic fortunes have always depended on the cyclical
nature of naval orders. In a climate of defence spending cutbacks, up to 1000
of its core workforce may now become peripheral casualties of the end of the
Cold War. The fabled ``peace dividend'' for many will be the dole.
The yard, the last British-owned survivor of the species on Clydeside, has
always been a hostage to changes in UK defence policy and funding. Even as the
lead yard for the new generation of Type-23 frigates and the projected
Euro-frigate due to be ordered in six years' time, its immediate options are
limited.
The yet unannounced decision by a cash-strapped Defence Ministry to delay the
award of a #500m contract for the final three-ship batch of Type-23s until at
least February next year underlines the point. There is no longer a built-in
margin for slippage in bread-and-butter domestic deals.
The Royal Navy itself is down to 35 surface warships. It is a total likely to
decline in coming years, despite the fact that more than 92% of the country's
exports, almost all of its oil, gas, timber and key imports and almost half of
its food is seaborne.
The acquisition of Yarrow by GEC-Marine and the potential rival location of
Vickers Shipbuilding at Barrow can only deepen the gloom at Scotstoun. Instead
of facing diminished competition on the demise of Swan Hunter on the Tyne, the
Clyde yard now has to come to terms with the implications of a long-term
corporate strategy which is no longer in its own hands.
Vosper Thorneycroft is, on paper, the only remaining commercial rival. The
Southampton firm has already carved a niche in the international market for
fast patrol craft, the poor man's high-speed alternative to a blue-water navy.
Yarrow clawed back some lost ground by being first in the market for corvettes,
the compromise vessels now completed for Malaysia, and by its recent order for
offshore patrol ships for Brunei. Both orders represent something which is not
quite a frigate, yet more than an inshore patrol craft. Both are fillers on the
order book, but hardly lifesavers.
The gap between orders, final design, construction and delivery is a long one.
It is certainly too long for GEC-Marine to sustain a 3000-strong workforce on
full pay, and anything up to 1500 subcontractors at any given time.
Steelworkers, the metal-bashers who handle the first, crucial stage of any
warship construction, will be the primary victims.
Even if, as expected, the Defence Ministry awards the contract to the Clyde, it
will come too late to prevent large-scale lay-offs if not outright
redundancies. It would be next spring before steel plate began to arrive to
signal the laying down of the final trio of Duke-class Type-23s.
A cross-party Commons report drawn up jointly by the Defence and Trade and
Industry committees warned yesterday that cutbacks in spending on research and
development and support for the defence industry were coming close to
endangering the country's security and independence.
UK-wide, more than 400,000 workers are dependent directly on defence orders for
their livelihood. They represent about 7% of the country's entire workforce.
At the moment, Britain can produce just over 90% of the equipment needed by its
own armed forces. A decade from now, given the current rate of decline, the
Defence Ministry will have no choice but to go to an American-dominated market
for its hardware. The strategic framework is already creaking.
Yarrow has fought hard to maintain a place in that market, both pre and
post-GEC. Under its former chairman, Sir Bob Easton, its sales team scoured the
world for export opportunities. Some, like Pakistan, wanted Clyde-built
frigates. Unfortunately, the price was too high and Islamabad's credit rating
too low.
Undeterred, the yard sought business in the more fertile waters of the Middle
and Far East. They were aided by Iran's acquisition of three ex-Soviet
Kilo-class submarines among the Gulf states. Every Arab oil-producer in the
region began to think seriously about safeguarding the sea lanes for its black
gold. So far, however, none has signed a deal.
The disputed Spratly Islands in the South China Sea proved a better lure. Oil
is again the prize, although this time China, Malaysia, Singapore, Vietnam and
the Philippines have all laid down markers for ownership and rattled cutlasses
at diplomatic level.
Malaysia has already bought two corvettes to underscore the seriousness of its
claim. More orders may follow as the region squares up for a showdown still
probably half a decade away, although the smart money remains on China in any
confrontation worthy of the name.
Like all British defence companies, Yarrow is constrained by the package it can
offer. Many of the weapons systems inherent to the operational effectiveness of
Royal Navy warships are forbidden fruit in most areas of potential conflict.
Yarrow is then relegated to being a hull-builder, albeit a superb one, with
good connections to the people who supply radar, guns and missiles. These, in
their turn, are limited by the dictates of current foreign policy and official
and technological secrets.
The yard is also fighting in a pool crowded with equally desperate commercial
sharks. Russia is cash-poor and desperate to sell off all but top-of-the-range
warships. German, Dutch and Danish yards, all suffering from the universal and
so far unsuccessful quest for Government peace dividends, are all offering
off-the-shelf ships at rock-bottom prices. Some are even Government-subsidised
on the quiet.
Britain's 1995-96 defence budget amounts to #21.72 billion. Operating,
equipping and supporting the Royal Navy comes to about 25% of that total.
Treasury pressure for economies will probably mean anything up to a 3% cut next
year. Staggering orders is the Defence Ministry's classic method of creative
book-keeping.
The real question for the Government is how much of its strategic defence
industry it is prepared to shed in the interest of short-term savings. The UK
could still - just - stand alone in a conflict. If it abdicates the ability to
build its own warships, aircraft and land weaponry, it will be losing not only
vital jobs, but also any claim to independent action in Europe. For Defence
Secretary Michael Portillo's benefit, that represents the choice between free
market and free will.
</TEXT>
