<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Public criticism of top players uncalled for Wrong approach by drill sergeant Telfer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE man-management skills of the sporting supremos of this world I often find
puzzling.
Did it make Devon Malcolm a better bowler when he was rubbished by both the
England coach and the manager Ray Illingworth? Who picked the guy in the first
place?
How have the West Indies Cricket Board managed to antagonise Brian Lara, their
best player, to the extent that he will not tour with them?
What is Jim Telfer attempting to achieve by criticising publicly two of his
leading players? According to the director of rugby, Craig Chalmers and Kenny
Logan may have lost their hunger for the sport. Really? On what is this
astonishing assumption based?
``Both Craig and Kenny have distractions off the pitch,'' declared Mr Telfer in
a Sunday newspaper, ``and, because they are the kind of guys who are willing to
go away and play in testimonial matches, it could be they are not hungry any
more.''
Let's put the record straight. Craig Chalmers' main off-the-pitch distractions
are a wife and two children. Kenny Logan has a high-profile girlfriend. I
understand this is not forbidden, even by the Free Kirk these days.
Last month they both played in a testimonial match to mark the contribution to
the game of Ieuan Evans, the former Welsh captain. They received no fee for
doing so and both returned saying how much they had enjoyed themselves.
Also taking part were Scotland squad members Scott Hastings and Rob Wainwright,
who happens to be the current international captain. Among the latter's
distractions might be listed his family and his career as an Army doctor.
So why pick on Chalmers and Logan? Craig has probably just helped Melrose to
another league championship; if they are pipped on the post it will be by
Stirling County, Kenny's outfit. No lack of appetite in that department.
Yes, they both had an indifferent game against Western Samoa. In that they were
certainly not alone.
Among the guilty men I would also nominate the selectors, for picking the wrong
side - Eric Peters and Stewart Campbell should have been included - and whoever
dictated the tactics.
I bet Jim Telfer, if Scotland lose to Ireland in the opening Five Nations game,
that the same people to whom he is baring his soul will then be calling for his
head.
A director of rugby is not like any other manager or coach. Telfer has been
handed enormous responsiblities, far greater than anyone else in the history of
the game in Scotland. He is not just the Scotland team manager; his remit is to
develop the sport throughout the length and breadth of the land. Such a figure
has to rise above dishing out personal criticisms.
I like Jim Telfer. He is a deep-thinking man, honest as the day is long. His
record, which includes coaching Scotland to a Grand Slam, stands up to any
scrutiny. But he is not infallible. None of us are.
My worry is that he is surrounded by people who tell him what he wants to hear.
Another of the director's recent quotes was to the effect that the game might
not need heroes. That's just baloney, Jim.
You and I visited a township in South Africa where hundreds of kids mobbed
Gavin Hastings, some of them even put on their best clothes just to be near
him.
It is the special players, the Gavs, the Gary Armstrongs, the Barry Johns, who
attract youngsters to the game, who provide the goal for others to achieve -
why, I even recall the days when all good forwards wanted to play as well as
Jim Telfer.
Craig Chalmers is the most competitive member of the Scotland squad, Kenny
Logan one of the most exciting backs. But they need to have their confidence
boosted, not to be treated like naughty little boys. The days of the drill
sergeant approach are definitely numbered.
I know Jim Telfer does not like the fact that the pair write columns for
newspapers. Again, one has to point out that they are not alone in that, nor
are they prohibited from doing so by any contract.
If the director thinks he has problems with star players, maybe he should have
a word with Walter Smith at Ibrox. I do not think it is any coincidence that
Paul Gascoigne is flourishing under the wise handling of the Rangers' manager.
He can shout a bit too - but he does it in private.
</TEXT>
