<HEADLINE>EU report isolates Major Britain out of step on veto</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
BRITAIN will stand outnumbered by 14 to one on the question of the national
veto in Europe when the Maastricht 11 negotiations begin next year. After
months of planning, the EU's Reflection Group of foreign ministers yesterday
published its final blueprint for the agenda to be placed before the
inter-governmental conference due to begin in Italy in spring.
It shows that Britain is the only member state opposed in principle to
weakening the national veto in areas including foreign policy and home affairs
and replacing it with majority voting. Britain also stands alone in opposing
more powers for the European Parliament.
The report will provide ammunition for Tory Euro-sceptics who have been lying
low since Mr John Major's re-election to the leadership. If the Tories stay in
power until the spring of 1997, when a General Election must be called, they
face running a campaign for a fifth term against the background of the
continuing struggle against the tide of European integration.
They will not be helped by Mr John Redwood's intention to campaign against the
single currency in the meantime, thus reopening the Euro-wounds which have
riven the party and which threatened Mr Major's premiership earlier this year.
Mr David Davis, European Minister, speaking in Brussels yesterday, saw this
difficulty coming when he urged people not to assume the ``British problem'' in
Europe could be overcome by the election of a Labour Government.
He told reporters: ``This presumes Tony Blair will win the election - and that
is not a presumption I would sign up for.''
The Labour-dominated, 217-strong socialist group in the European Parliament
backed the report.
British Conservative insistence that Europe is slowly coming round to Britain's
way of thinking appeared to be turned on its head by the Spanish president of
the Reflection Group, Mr Carlos Westendorp. He told reporters, in the context
of British resistance: ``We are condemned to success. We cannot fail.''
The report confirms that Britain has led a campaign of mutiny on the major
issues facing the EU as it strives to make the Maastricht treaty more workable
in the face of impending enlargement eastwards to bring in the former Communist
states.
It shows that co-decision powers with the European Parliament are being
resisted mainly in Britain.
On the question of qualified majority voting, which would weaken or remove the
national veto in some crucial areas, the report states: ``One of us opposes the
extension in principle.'' The report concluded that many of the EU's 15 members
believed greater efficiency could be enhanced by more majority voting in the
council. Some states went farther, arguing that it should become routine
procedure after enlargement.
The report added: ``Some of us believe that this should only be countenanced if
democratic legitimacy is improved by a re-weighting of votes to take account of
population.'' Mr Davis hinted that this was an early sign of the negotiation to
come.
However, the report also suggests obliquely that Britain could gain some
support from some members on specific issues when the subject of the veto is
discussed. The French, under President Chirac, have also shown signs of
opposition to the Strasbourg assembly having more power and to wholesale
qualified majority voting on certain issues such as defence.
Mr Davis recalled the Prime Minister's promise that Britain would oppose
``massive'' new powers for the European Parliament but he refused to say if
this meant the point was non-negotiable. ``We are not debating negotiations
now,'' he said.
Leader comment -Page 16
</TEXT>
