<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flat rate minimum wage appears to be too rigid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the face of it talk of a minimum wage even of just #4.50 sounds attractive
particularly when one considers that #7 an hour is not an usual amount to pay a
domestic cleaner in London.
However, given the varying skill levels entailed in different types of work and
the differences in the cost of living around the UK, a flat rate national
minimum wage appears to be too rigid.
Employers' organisations have been vocal in their opposition to a minimum wage
and this is not surprising given their attempts to beat off competition in
traditional markets from newly emerging low-cost markets, notably the Far East
and Latin America. Employers' costs clearly would rise if a national minimum
wage was imposed.
For a #4 national minimum wage, economic models suggest that the first round
national rise in employment costs (defined as gross earnings plus employer
national insurance contributions) would be #6400m per year. These costs would
be concentrated among employers with large numbers of low paid workers.
However, increasing wages will mean that more income tax and national insurance
contributions will be collected and the cost of in-work benefits will be
reduced.
In addition, there are those who think a minimum wage would provide some relief
for our burgeoning welfare budget. This is because the wages on offer to the
unemployed are now arguably so low that many have no financial incentive to
work at all.
In the latest edition of *New Economy, Paul Gregg and Jonathan Wadsworth of the
London School of Economics, point out that the average job taken by people
hitherto unemployed typically paid well under half (44%) of the gross weekly
wages observed in all other jobs.
One third of such jobs paid below a quarter of the median weekly wage (#56).
The low weekly wages on offer stem from the fact that hours on offer are
limited (a quarter below average) and because the hourly wages offered are low
(65% of the average).
Messrs Gregg and Wadsworth argue that currently available work, allied with the
current benefit system, all too often does not pay without the presence of a
working partner.
A minimum wage as part of a comprehensive package of tax and benefit reform is
seen as a valuable tool to improve work incentives, reduce the implicit subsidy
on low wage jobs and halt the rise in the benefit dependent workless family.
In the competitive trading environment, companies in all sectors are
increasingly focused on how better to serve customers. Those companies who
value their staff and place a high priority on good customer service tend to
pay staff above the minimum rate in the industry.
In retailing, one thinks of the likes of Marks &amp; Spencer and John Lewis. That
way they attract good people and maintain their goodwill. You get what you pay
for and just as we hear about the need to incentivise top executives, workers
lower down the chain also need encouragement of a financial nature, arguably
more so.
On balance, I think there is a case for a free market in wages, but with the
safeguards for workers of some sort of wages council. These were abolished by
the Government in 1993, leaving Britain as the only European Union country
without any formal or informal system of minimum wages.
The need for some sort of wage protection is all the more vital to prevent
exploitation, given the fragmentation of the labour market and growth in
flexible and part-time working.
n New Economy is published by the Institute for Public Policy Research. 30-32
Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Telephone: 0171 379 9400 or fax: 0171 497
0373.
</TEXT>
