<HEADLINE>Trumpet blowing at Wessex</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WESSEX Water blew its own trumpet yesterday by highlighting its ability to
maintain supplies without restrictions through the summer.
Chairman Nicholas Hood said some of the obvious improvements to Wessex's
customers had been ignored by critics, who tended to lump all water companies
together.
``There is a difference between water companies and Wessex will continue to act
in ways which will change these perceptions,'' he said.
If the company found itself having to impose restrictions because of a failure
of its infrastructure, it would compensate them for what it believed to be a
sub-standard service.
The group also revealed a jump in half year pre-tax profit to #68.4m in the six
months to the end of September from #58.2m in the corresponding period last
year.
The interim dividend rises from 4.4p to 5p on earnings per share of 18.6p
against 16.4p.
</TEXT>
