<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On a whinge and a prayer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Immediacy of emotion is essential in the story of an angel's fall from grace.
Sara Villiers views his grounds for complaint
ALMOST a month ago a flock of culture vultures from around Glasgow gathered in
the rehearsal room of the 7:84 Theatre Company to watch a work-in-progress
performance of The War in Heaven, an elegiac play by Sam Shephard and Joseph
Chaikin. A trifle rusty around the edges, with a few fluffed lines and some
mis-timed movement, the work yet emanated a beauty and power which left the
small aduience quite dumbstruck.
A few weeks on, at another sneak preview, the cast's increased conviction of
performance had further heightened the lyricism of the piece. The production,
which opens a 10-day run at the Tramway, Glasgow, tomorrow night is almost
certainly going to be another hit for Outreach, 7:84's ambitious community
theatre programme, with the play an inspired choice by the company's Outreach
worker, director John Heraghty.
The piece will be the first production to fully combine the two wings of 7:84,
Artistic and Outreach, representing the fruition of an evolution which has seen
increasingly professional production values applied to Outreach projects,
resulting in work of the calibre of New Frontiers, Glasgow Generations and Act
Your Age.
While previous Outreach projects have emerged from extensive workshopping as
devised plays, Heraghty was interested in using a scripted piece with a small
group of performers.
He had been attracted to The War in Heaven for some time. The play was written
for radio in 1984 and performed by Chaikin, the American actor and director. It
is an intensely personal piece which was co-written with Shephard after Chaikin
had suffered a stroke and lost the use of the right side of his body and
virtually all speech.
He had previously been working on another play with Shephard and an angelic
character from that took on a life of its own, coming to represent Chaikin's
feelings of alienation and his struggle with his loss of language.
Heraghty, who was familiar with previous Chaikin and Shephard collaborations,
thought that the play would be perfect for this Outreach development. ``I felt
it would be a good piece to move on     to, a scripted piece but one which gave
people a lot of room to put their own thoughts across.''
The poetic, symbolic emphasis of the play, which sketches a fragmented story of
an angel's fall to earth and the subsequent anguished struggle to return to
heaven, offers the cast a chance of          a vigorous and personal
interpretation.
``We could expose things     we could relate to rather than be confronted with
a script with strictly delineated characters,'' says Heraghty. ``Community
theatre tends to put people's own stories across and the script here allows
that. There is a real immediacy of emotion.''
Although orginally performed as a monologue by Chaikin, Heraghty's adaptation
for the stage splits the voice of the Angel and his three characters, played by
Tommy Cannon, Sheila Docherty and Pauline Sweeney.
``Originally we intended to have lots of performers doing it, but the more work
you do on this play the sparser it seems. It could be done in a choral way, but
it seemed more eloquent to limit the voices.''
His original concern that the lyricism of the piece might prove obtuse, was
unfounded. ``It was a little bit confusing at first but once you read it
properly it becomes very clear,'' says Sheila Docherty.
Tommy Cannon, who is blind, had to get the script translated into Braille.
``The people who were doing that were telling me that there were some parts on
the left-hand side and some on the right. At first I could make little of that,
but I understand it quite clearly now. When I learned why the piece was written
I felt a strong conviction about doing it.''
Pauline Sweeney was immediately attracted to the play. ``I loved that fact that
there's a lot of social comment in it. We did some very intensive work on the
script and    for me it is about someone who's had a lot of power and friends
and held a position of authority who has, partly through their own fault,
lost all that and found him-self alone.
``Then the character finds hope for change because they can recognise their own
part in their downfall.''
Although Sweeney's character radiates a serenity and optimism, Docherty's is
contrastingly pained by the dilemma. ``It is someone who has lost power and
feels that the longer they are here they are weakened, and they are just
desperate to get back.''
One of the strongest sections of the piece is Docherty's frustrated
panic-flecked plea: ``Every minute I am here, something's changing in me/
something's diminishing in me. My power slips away.''
That anger is exacerbated with the pounding of a drum - the cast have worked
closely with musician David Young, whose score alternates between celestial
melancholy and thunderous roars.
``The drum coming in on that passage really helps me to fire up my delivery,''
notes Docherty.
Cannon's angel views the situation more mischievously. ``My character is
someone who has always thought of himself as a failure but through this
entrapment he finds out a lot about himself, he is someone who was previously
afraid of rebellion, but now learns to laugh at authority.
``I could really identify with this position because of the degree of
institutionalism in my young life, in my education. My angel has always been
told what to do and has obeyed, but now he can question it all. In some ways
it's a liberating experience.''
The cast, who have all previous worked with Heraghty in 7:84 on diverse
Outreach projects have enjoyed the collaborative nature of this production.
They have been involved in consultations with Young, lighting designer Ian
Scott, costumier Anna Lau, and designer Mark Leese, who has come up with a
simple elegantly constructed set which suggests of a celestial waiting room.
``No-one's been too precious about their work. Everyone's been more generous
with each other, perhaps because the amount of people working on this project
is smaller than usual,'' says Leese.
``We looked at any ideas anyone expressed and took them seriously. The concept
of the waiting room as an island, surrounded by earth, is a fairly obvious one.
But it works because the text is very thick, and if we had been too heavy with
the visual ideas they would have been muffled.''
Heraghty concurs with the principle, applauding the strength of the script.
``We have been asking a lot from the performers and I think that that is right.
We'd be letting them down if we didn't do that. The writing is so sturdy that
they can take their performances quite far. We've tried to realise the beauty
of the piece but it's not wishy-washy - it's got a hard edge.''
n.The War in Heaven, tomorrow until December 16. Free Tramway/Herald debate,
What is Community Theatre? precedes the performance on Thursday, December 14 at
6pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
