<DOCID>GH951206-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Instant wins less addictive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCRATCHCARDS are at the ``soft end'' of gambling and are less addictive than
fruit machines, the National Lottery regulator said yesterday.
Mr Peter Davis, the director general of the Office of the National Lottery,
told representatives of the gaming machine industry in Birmingham that
scratchcards would remain exempt from the advertising restrictions on other
forms of gambling.
He told delegates, who had called for the restrictions to be removed, that the
lottery was significantly different from attractions like fruit machines
because its purpose was to raise money for good causes.
``National Lottery scratchcards are bought under controlled, open, and very
sociable conditions,'' Mr Davis said. ``The atmosphere is open, mundane, and
domestic. There isn't a hint of skill. Any pressure to purchase is very mild.''
He compared the experience of buying a scratchcard to the ``sensory treats
delivered by the lights and noise of an arcade''.
``Fruit machines are played in an environment which is usually inviting, often
large and noisy, mostly pubs or arcades,'' Mr Davis said. ``There is often a
strong, highly charged atmosphere, designed to stimulate and excite. It's a
very tactile experience.''
Other gambling organisations, like Littlewoods Pools, have claimed the
lottery's exemption from normal regulation gives it an unfair advantage.
</TEXT>
