<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yard workers face a bleak New Year</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE stampede of workers leaving Yarrow's at the end of a working day appeared
no less subdued last night despite the anger clearly etched on their faces.
They had just been told by managing director Murray Easton that it was now
inevitable that 1000 jobs would be shed next month.
Of those, 300 are put down to the delay by the MoD in awarding a new contract
for up to three Type 23 frigates.
``We are sick,'' was the reply shouted by one worker when asked for his
reaction.
Many of the workers appeared numbed as they left the yard and refused to
comment on the blow, delivered on the day they expected to hear that the
contract had been clinched - beating off fierce competition from Vosper
Thorneycroft in Southampton.
Those who did comment appeared unanimous in their view that the contract's
delay was ``deeply demoralising''.
Mr Robert Gibb, 60, a sheet metal worker from Dumbarton, said: ``It is very
sad. The Government is to blame. There is a holdback for some reason or other.''
Apprentice fabricator Derek McAuley, 19, said most of the workers had appeared
``very depressed''.
Mr John Dolan, GMB convener at the yard, said: ``The workers are saddened,
shocked, and annoyed at what has happened.''
Mr Dolan, 46, who has been a plater at the yard for 13 years, said he believed
it was ``too early'' to apportion blame for the redundancies.
He added: ``We will be discussing with the company whether pressure can be
applied to bring the frigate order forward.''
Mr James Potter, a temporary plumber at the yard, said the temporary workers
had half expected to be paid off.
However, he added: ``We didn't all expect to be let down the way we were after
management confirmed an order for three patrol vessels for Brunei.''
One white-collar worker, who declined to be named, questioned whether the delay
in announcing the order was political, saying: `` I believe this is about
whether the Government wants to spend #500m on three new frigates.''
While he conceded the mood among workers was one of anger and disappointment,
he said most were not surprised.
``Everyone knew the vessels in the yard were going to be finished off within a
few months of one another,'' he said. ``That was always going to severely hit
the fitting-out trades.''
All but one of three Type 23 frigates and two Malaysian corvettes in the yard
are due to be completed by the middle of next year.
The Brunei order, announced last week and worth an estimated #400m, is a
design-and-build contract for three patrol vessels and is likely to remain on
the drawing board for up to a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Delays hit yard. 1000 jobs on line at Yarrow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028305</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST 1000 workers at Yarrow shipbuilders on the Clyde - a third of the
workforce - are almost certain to be made redundant next month.
The gloomy forecast follows a dearth of orders and a decision by the
Government
to delay by up to three months the announcement of a contract for three Navy
vessels.
The move, which will follow 230 redundancies at the Glasgow yard this Friday,
will bring the total number of job losses to more than 1200 in the next few
weeks.
Union officials had been anticipating ``several hundred'' redundancies next
month because of a shortage of work, but the company revealed yesterday that
the number would be between 650 and 700 and said a further 280 jobs would be
axed as a direct result of the delay in announcing the order for the final
batch of Type 23 frigates.
The news will have come as a bitter blow to the Scotstoun yard and its 3150
workers - who had been hoping to learn that the Type 23 bid had been
successful
- although management had warned in August that staff would have to be laid
off, even if it won the contract, because of gaps in its order book.
The order for up to three Type 23 frigates, worth up to #500m, is believed to
be crucial for the yard's long-term future.
Yarrow, which is still confident of securing the contract, had been expecting
an announcement by the Government early this month, but said the Ministry of
Defence had now indicated that no decision would be taken until the end of
February.
The Ministry has been considering bids to build the Type 23s from Yarrow and
rival shipbuilders Vosper Thorneycroft of Southampton since mid-August.
Yarrow, which yesterday described the situation as a ``short-term crisis'' and
said its long-term future was secure, is deeply concerned that the matter is
to
drag on and will continue to lobby Government Ministers on the impact of a
delayed decision on jobs for the yard and Clydeside.
Opposition MPs yesterday reacted angrily to the development, with Labour
accusing the Ministry of Defence of ``bungling incompetence'' and the SNP
claiming that the ``disgraceful'' treatment of Yarrow highlighted severe
limitations in Scottish Office lobbying of London-based Government departments.
The yard said yesterday that it had done everything in its power to reduce the
number of redundancies, but admitted that the scheduled completion of all but
one of three Type 23 frigates and two Malaysian frigates next year meant it
had
run out of work for many employees.
Mr Murray Easton, managing director, said: ``We had
already been anticipating major redundancies at the beginning of the year and
we have taken account of that in our planning. That is because a number of
contracts we have at the shipyard will be complete by the middle of 1996.
``If we had been awarded the Type 23 contract by the MoD then we would have
started steel cutting immediately, and I mean literally immediately, in order
to maximise the savings and to reduce the number of redundancies.
``We are extremely disappointed about the delay quite obviously, because any
impact there is on employees of the company is one we try to avoid and
minimise. Regretful is not a word that satisfies the way we feel.
``In the short-term, the situation is very negative, but the long-term future
of the yard is secure as demonstrated by the announcement last week of the
excellent news from Brunei.''
Mr Easton said Yarrow was still confident of winning the contract, adding that
it had previously delivered six Type 23 frigates to the satisfaction of the
Ministry and was building another three.
Mr Stewart Crawford, the yard's union convener, said yesterday that union
officials were shocked by the news.
``We had started the day hoping that Mr Easton was going to come to us and say
you've won the Type 23 order and describe a healthy situation. Instead, he
told
us that the order has been delayed and the result was that the number of jobs
losses would be up to 1000.
``It is a blow to us, coming at this stage with the redundancies on Friday,
and
it brings a further element of insecurity into the place which we hadn't
foreseen this side of the new year.''
He added that he could not fault management because ``they have done all they
can to reduce the number of redundancies.''
Labour's armed forces spokesman, Dr John Reid, said last night: ``Every month
there is another indication of waste or incompetence from the MoD - this time
it's incompetence.
``The warship market is now cut-throat in its competition. It is insecure
enough without the bungling incompetence of the MoD, especially in the run-up
to Christmas. They make it impossible for companies, managers, or ordinary
workers to plan ahead.''
SNP defence spokesman Colin Campbell said: ``This is disgraceful treatment of
Yarrow by the Govermment and shows up the severe limitations of Scottish
Office
lobbying of London-based departments. It seems to be a case of the Treasury
leading the decisions, rather than defence priorities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Still attracting an inordinate amount of flak</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR institutions that are apparently dying on their feet marriage and the
Church still manage to draw an inordinate amount of flak from their opponents.
Perhaps it is they who really believe in (and fear) resurrection. Professor
Steve Bruce now joins the fray with his fanciful perspective of history
(December 1).
If the Church of the Middle Ages tried to control the price of bread perhaps
this was connected to the sin of usury. Likewise the control of sex was perhaps
connected with the power of lust, not the lust for power. For if the Church has
shown an inordinate interest in sex, so too has mankind.
His gossamer-thin argument that marriage was about land and the inheritance
thereof, a buttress against the usurper, hence its patronage by the rich and
powerful, was an entertaining flight of the imagination. But a nodding
acquaintanceship with the history of Richard III and Henry VII and VIII puts
such bosh in its true perspective.
The institution of marriage is much older than the Church. When the curtain
rises on history, marriage is an established fact in Babylon, Egypt, Israel,
Greece, and Rome.
Why was it instituted in the first place? The failure of the more recent ``free
love'' experiment in post-revolutionary Russia may hold the answer.
When ``inheritance ceased to sit at the core of our economy and polity'' it was
more because of the dispossessed. It was the dissolution of the monasteries and
the enclosure of common land that made the urban community.
The peasantry, to avoid penury and starvation, were forced in droves off their
land to seek corporal and corporate salvation in parish charity or the hellish
factories of capitalism's New Jerusalem.
These crimes against humanity happened when the Church was at a low ebb, not
when it was in the driving seat.
Finally it may be true that ``committed church-going Catholics'' practise
artificial contraception but, after denigrating the Church for its omnipresence
in matters sexual, is his sociological interference in the bedrooms of others
any less reprehensible?
Tom McKay,
29 Manitoba Crescent,
East Kilbride.
IT is Steve Bruce's contention that the falling Catholic birth-rate is evidence
that committed church-going Catholics do not follow the church's teaching on
contraception (December 1).
The Catholic Church advocates responsible parenthood and recommends a method of
natural family planning which is at least as effective as any method of
artificial contraception when used by motivated couples.
I would argue that church-going Catholics by and large have that commitment.
Patrick P Kearns,
36 Kirkliston Road,
South Queensferry.
</TEXT>
