<DOCNO>GH951206-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Air monopoly to Amsterdam</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE again it has been my misfortune to fly from Amsterdam to Glasgow on an Air
UK flight. Yet again Air UK were between one and one-and-a-half hours delayed
at both ends.
The reason for this letter is not only to try to discover why Air UK always
have delays (always blamed on something else rather than their own
inefficiency) but also to find out why Air UK hold the monopoly into Scottish
airports.
One has to book via Air UK when flying from the Netherlands to Glasgow,
Edinburgh, or Aberdeen and one must pay astronomical fares because they are the
only carrier.
For example, a weekend return between Amsterdam and Glasgow costs us #252
whereas a weekend return between Amsterdam and London can be purchased for as
little as #99, the latter being run by four or five different carriers. We can
understand a slightly higher price but certainly not a #153 price difference.
Have British Airways abandoned us (Scottish) expatriates to a carrier which has
liaisons with the Dutch national carrier KLM?
With Air UK in the past years we have witnessed consistent delays, flights
being lumped together (fly to Glasgow and end up in Edinburgh only to find your
own way back to Glasgow) and flights being cancelled at the last moment.
Is it not about time that we had some competition on these routes which might
lead to a bit more efficiency on the part of Air UK and also to cheaper fares?
J D McLaren,
Oosterkade 115,
3011TV-Rotterdam,
Netherlands.
</TEXT>
