<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not dawn of new barbarism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANDOM acts of violence against innocent bystanders, who just happen to be in
the wrong place at the wrong time, appear to be a regrettable part of modern
life and the attack on the playwright Peter McDougall on Saturday, November 25,
was a case in point.
Given the high degree of public anxiety about the problem, it is most important
that stories such as the McDougall assault are covered in a responsible way and
not sensationalised by the media.
Mr McDougall's assault was given front-page prominence in The Herald,
presumably because he is a well-known personality. I am not trying to play down
the seriousness of the attack, but would a similar assault on an ``ordinary''
person have received such coverage? I think not.
In addition, Mr McDougall was given the considerable luxury of airing his
thoughts in an article which took up half a page in The Herald on December 1 -
a considerable amount of space. Does the ``ordinary'' assault victim have the
same luxury? Again, I think not.
The title, Dawn of new barbarism, set the tone of the article. Mr McDougall
used highly emotive language and made sweeping generalisations. To suggest that
a whole generation is completely amoral and has totally rejected ``our'' moral
standards is wildly inaccurate and very unfair.
He also appears to yearn for a return to some mythical golden age when there
was a code of conduct among thugs: when they fought among themselves and did
not attack ``civilians''.
If, as Peter McDougall suggests, drink plays a big part in the committing of
violent acts, I fail to see how a ``traditional thug'', out of his mind on
drink, could distinguish between a legitimate target and a civilian.
How common is it for middle-aged men like Peter McDougall to be the victim of a
random assault? How common is it for 86-year-old ladies to be attacked?
Statistics would suggest that it is not that common and that most victims are
young men.
Yet it is the attack on the middle-aged playwright and the poor old lady which
is given prominence in newspapers and TV, often for purely cynical, commercial
reasons. These stories sell newspapers and increase ratings.
Every act of violence is to be abhorred and I extend my sympathy to Peter
McDougall for what must have been a terrifying attack. I am an admirer of his
work and he is obviously a man in touch with the culture of the streets.
However, because of the considerable impact that an article so prominently
featured in a national newspaper would have, it might have been better to have
reflected longer before committing his thoughts to print.
Gordon Whitelaw,
24 Luss Brae,
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Game of artistic consequences</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>mary brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY'VE met, they've talked. Laurie Booth - one of the most resiliently
experimental choreographers working in Britain - has gone through a few
movement patterns, highlighting various rhythms as well as visual elements.
Alasdair Nicolson - a composer with a real feel for theatre in music, and vice
versa - has responded to the dance and the discussion by sending Booth a taped
score. Now comes the payoff in this game of artistic consequences - otherwise
known as Glasgow Commissions.
Friday night sees the first performance of the first commission: The Last
Meeting, when Nicolson's score is played live by the Scottish Chamber Orchestra
and Booth dances the solo that has evolved for the occasion. Neither of them
can say, at this point, what the end result is likely to be - that might emerge
during one of the two rehearsals scheduled for later this week.
What does seem certain is that the piece will not be exactly the same on either
night of performance. The difference in venues - the City Hall in Glasgow, the
Queen's Hall in Edinburgh - will, for instance, affect the stage picture that
Nicolson has in mind. He has deliberately changed the usual seating
arrangements of the orchestra, splitting the players into groups and using
these to ``frame'' the dance space rather like the on-stage chorus in Greek
drama.
The starting point for the whole piece does, in fact, lie in Greek mythology -
the legend of Orpheus and Eurydice - but Nicolson is quick to point out that
The Last Meeting is in no way a narrative retelling of the final part of that
story. His interests tend more towards the exploration of distance, separation,
endings. Hence the physical statement of the divided orchestra.
This dividing and rearranging also reflects his wish to give the audience
something far removed from the concert protocols of the nineteenth century. ``I
want to bring about this `theatre-in-a-concert-situation' where lighting is
important and the look of the thing has a dramatic visual impact.''
Into this arena - and bearing ideas of his own - comes dancemaker Laurie Booth
whom Nicholson describes, with real enthusiasm, as having a kind of electricity
about him, a quality that realy captures and holds an audience's attention.
This is particularly important given the context.
``Orchestras generate their own movement,'' says Nicolson. ``Niggly, small
movements - even when they're not playing. And you need someone like Laurie,
who is quite a mesmerising performer, to hold the focus against that. Otherwise
it just breaks up, the audience is distracted, they lose sight of what you're
trying to communicate through the structure of the music as well as the dance.''
Booth, meanwhile, has been working on his own expression of the themes. His
work - whether with other dancers, or with artists like sculptor Anish Kapoor -
has regularly concerned itself with images of perspective. With how movement
can evoke the relationships we have with time, space, other people ..... but
also, and most poignantly, with out own inner selves. His hallmarks are a
fiercely gentle strength - he often draws on the regime of capoeira, a
Brazilian form of martial arts discipline - and ``invisible'' improvisation.
``Invisible'' because there's never any obvious indication on stage that he's
dancing as the mood takes him - certainly none of the hesitation or trial and
error commonly associated with spur-of-the-moment stuff.
``Actually I don't think of it as `improvisation' when it's a solo,'' says
Booth himself. ``It's more about me working with current choreographic concerns
that are in my mind anyway, sifting through them, bringing them into focus -
like you choosing words for a sentence.''
What amuses him, however, is the way in which he has started working more and
more with actual music. ``I seem to be going backward,'' he says laughing.
``Usually people start out making dance to pieces of music, then venture into
freer forms of sound, no sound at all, text, whatever. Well, I started out with
all that and now I seem to be moving towards melodic forms. I think it's the
discipline of trying to understand specific melodic forms that intriques me.
Seeing what the structures are, how I can play about with them, like in Tango
Variations last year.''
Tango Variations was, as it happens, one of the performances that made Nicolson
fix on Booth as his choice of fellow-artist.
When they subsequently met in Booth's studio, to discuss the new commission, it
was a case of quickly establishing a vocabulary of rhythms and sounds that both
could use, independently, as a springboard for developments.
``Alasdair wanted to know what kind of rhythm patterns I was likely to use,
what kind of sounds I might make,'' recalls Booth. ``It was a case, really, of
me saying `Well, if I use a stick I can do this, this or this with it' and us
agreeing on a set of likely rhythms, possible sounds.''
How that initial agreement has evolved - separately, as seems thoroughly
appropriate given the themes of the piece - can be seen when The Last Meeting
premieres this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coating of haute chocolate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMAGINE rich, dark chocolate poured from an old-fashioned pewter coffee pot.
Imagine leather burnished with a subtle metallic gleam. Or satin, oiled so that
it assumes a finish which could almost pass for the binding on a fine
antiquarian book. Velvet which shimmers gently when it catches the light. Fur,
quite faux, yet sumptuously reminiscent of chinchilla or Persian lamb.
Such are the unexpected colour combinations and unusual textures which
characterise some of contemporary fashion's most beguiling clothes for women.
And they distinguish the current work of American designers Donna Karan and
Ralph Lauren. Each could be labelled a romantic modernist. For they soften the
stark austerity of minimalism with a lyrical quality.
Their realistic, refined clothes bridge that massive credibility gap in fashion
between the alienating runway excesses presented by so many designers (fixated
with youth, skinniness, and a very shallow idea of sexiness) and the real
consumer of designer fashion - a woman who is invariably neither particularly
young nor desperately thin.
Simple clothes of subtle distinction suit this woman very well. But simple
clothes rarely make fascinating runway presentations. No fireworks, and little
excitement. To the wearer, however, their qualities are self-evident;
wonderfully, they are out of the ordinary, yet neither weird nor wacky.
The unlikely juxtaposition of chocolate satin with pewter leather could be worn
just as readily by a 65-year-old as any 25-year-old. And just as happily next
winter (or the one thereafter) as this. Unfortunately, such distinction carries
a hefty price tag. But, as with all great investments, you are at least
guaranteed a high rate of interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Bull lives.  Euro defiance is scream from the bunker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S defiance in the run-up to the Maastricht II summit next year can be
interpreted in two ways. Either it is a brave, if singular, campaign of
patriotic resistance to a dominating and bureaucratic superstate, or it is a
scream from the bunker of a stricken government trailing Labour by a record
margin which gets daily wider. Take your choice. It is not difficult. Europe
divides the Tories more than any issue since the Second World War. If they lose
the election they could split formally into the two parties they really are at
present: the mainstream centre-right Tory Christian Democrats in the European
tradition, and the far-right Little Englander nationalists. The Conservatives
have much to play for in getting their act together as the Maastricht
super-summit approaches.
Just how critical this occasion will be depends on your source of information
these days. If you listen to British diplomats, earnestly bending ears around
Brussels, this is no more than a routine 10,000-mile service for a treaty which
was disfigured at birth. No argument about its failings: the need to put them
right was recognised when a review was built into Maastricht I. The deadline
for doing so was deemed to be next year. This is not, therefore, just another
Euro-adventure being foisted on the unwilling by plotting federalists in
Brussels. John Major signed up for it like everyone else. And it is true that
the EU on this occasion is not seeking vast new competences. Rather the
opposite, in fact. What this review seeks to do is simply to make the present
treaty work. In Brussels there is talk of the existence of a commission
document in which some bureaucrat has calculated that if there is no more
majority voting in a European Union of 25 or 30 member states, the difficulty
in reaching a decision by unanimity will be increased by a factor of 40,000.
Even if that is a ridiculous exaggeration the fact remains that the days of the
unanimity rule must be numbered. Europe simply cannot function - ever - in
total and absolute unanimity on everything. The idea is preposterous.
In their hearts British Ministers know this. But a show must be put up to
demonstrate to recividist Europhobes on the back benches - and gullible
electors - that John Bull lives. Like John Major's opt-out from the social
chapter, this owes much more to style than substance. Those running the
European Union are not daft: they are not about to let Britain drift off as
just another irrelevant, crumbling nation state on its own. They want Britain
genuinely at the heart of the Europe of the 21st century - potentially the
world's pre-eminent superpower - which is why the Maastricht II meeting will
last beyond the next election if it suffers from a British blocking campaign.
This assumes, of course, that the Tories will in the meantime be replaced by a
Euro-friendly Labour government. But that's another story.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forced into cars</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT IS no wonder that car dependence is high when large employers such as the
Royal Bank, Bank of Scotland, and even Lothian region move large numbers of
Edinburgh staff to the Gyle and Chesser House respectively. Many staff were
forced to buy a car, or give up their job, and the impact on custom for the
likes of ScotRail was measurable.
True, some determined souls could still manage without a car, but this would be
at immense cost in time, which has been shown to be the key determining factor
in choice of travel.
Invest in public transport? I doubt that the provision of swish new buses and
trains will have more than a marginal effect when the total journey time - door
to door - is never going to match that of a car which can be driven into an
attached car-park, from a domestic driveway.
The new unitary authorities should look carefully at the means of making the
catching and disembarking from public transport suitably provided for, to make
it safe, quick and convenient to the likes of Scotstoun Leisure Centre -
temptingly visible from the train and the cyclepath which runs along its
eastern flank without any access provision.
Dave Holladay,
95 West Graham Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why a minister may say No</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM not sure if I am one of the ministers of the Church of Scotland who should
feel chastened by Stewart Lamont's strictures on colleagues who refuse to marry
couples who cohabit or who only agree to perform the wedding if certain
conditions are met (December 2).
The charge of inquisition doesn't stick: I don't see it as my business to pry
into whether a couple sleep with one another or live together.
If a couple who cohabit wish to be married in church because they have come to
see that marriage is the best way and wish God's blessing on the life they
share, then, of course, I am glad to affirm them in their decision.
However, a problem arises when a couple who seek Christian marriage talk of a
wedding in a year or 18 months' time while at the same time indicating that
they will continue to live together until the big day.
Some of us feel that to acquiesce to such a situation is to compromise the
integrity of both the Church and the couple.
Of the Church, because at a time when the boundaries between right and wrong,
particularly in the realm of sexual morality, have been moved, if not removed
altogether, the Church should not add to the uncertainty and confusion by
sending out ambivalent signals which imply that it is one and the same whether
a couple cohabit or live apart before the wedding.
Of the couple, because their intention to cohabit over a long period of time up
until the wedding suggests a less than compelling desire to embrace the ethic
which Christian marriage represents. One is reminded of St Augustine's prayer:
``Give me chastity and continence, but do not give it yet!''
Stewart Lamont may feel that we should allow couples, in the circumstances I
have described, to use the church.
Others of us, while willing to live with many of the ambiguities which surround
weddings in church, feel, after much heart-searching, that there is a ``fudge''
which so compromises the integrity of the couple, of the Christian
understanding of marriage, and of the Church, and that we have no alternative
but to decline the request.
That gives us no joy. The price we pay in terms of misunderstanding and
misrepresentation is sometimes high.
David Easton,
59 Blairbeth Road,
Burnside, Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Musical mix and match</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS weekend, the first of the Glasgow Commissions will be unveiled. A
collaborative project between the Scottish Chamber Orchestra and Glasgow City
Council's department of performing arts and venues, the Glasgow Commissions
will bring four of Scotland's leading composers together with front-rank
artists in other disciplines in a conscious attempt to extend the boundaries of
the combined art forms.
Over the next two years, the #50,000 project will see new works produced by
Icelandic-born Haflidi Hallgrimsson and painter Craigie Aitchison, Sally
Beamish with writer Janice Galloway, and James MacMillan with sculptor Sue Jane
Taylor. The series is launched on Friday with The Last Meeting, a collaboration
between composer Alasdair Nicolson and choreographer Laurie Booth.
The idea of combining art forms is not a new one, says Roy McEwan, managing
director of the Scottish Chamber Orchestra. ``It started before my time, with
Glasgow very keen on exploring the concept of inter-relationship between
different artistic disciplines.''
Initially however, says McEwan, the project was intended to feature only solo
instruments from the orchestra. The expansion of the venture to include the
entire Scottish Chamber Orchestra in each of the commissions not only shifts
the goalposts, but introduces an entirely new ball game.
The point is, says McEwan, that each of the artists will be working within very
particular constraints. The first commission, featuring a composer and a
choreographer, is a case in point. ``Dance and music come together all the time
in the theatre,'' he said. ``But Alasdair Nicolson and Laurie Booth have been
asked specifically to come up with a work for dancer and orchestra rather than
a theatrical event. That is the constraint: it has to be with a full orchestra
on a concert platform, and not in a theatre.''
The first commission, and the third - with Sally Beamish and writer Janice
Galloway - at least combine art forms which marry relatively easily, said
McEwan. ``The interesting problems come in the others,'' he said, where there
will be two distinct pieces of work emerging: music and a painting, music and a
sculpture.
``How we present a concert hall audience with a visual concept and music, how
we integrate the separate art forms, is the problem and the challenge. These
are all experiments; some will work better than others. Each is a trial.''
However, as Roy McEwan pointed out, the SCO is not exactly moving into virgin
territory. Over the years, the orchestra's prolific development programme has
drawn many art forms together, mostly behind the scenes, in educational
projects. Music has been combined with movement, with film, with lighting, and
even with portraits in a gallery. It is this sort of work, in fact, as much as
the performing qualities of the orchestra, that has secured the SCO's
international reputation and won it big awards and vast sums of money.
What is absolutely new in the Glasgow Commissions is that the entire concept is
broadened to include the full orchestra, and that it will be brought on to the
concert platform in the regular winter series of orchestral concerts: project
work comes out of the closet and into the limelight.
n.The Glasgow Commissions: City Hall, Glasgow, Friday 7.30pm; Queen's Hall,
Edinburgh, Saturday 7.45pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>HIV risks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DR DAVID Delvin gives advice to a salesman who had a ``one-night stand'' with a
young lady he met in the West Highlands. His comments are blinkered and out of
touch with reality.
He states that the chances of contracting HIV in this area of Scotland would be
very low. You can never be completely sure that someone you hardly know has
never indulged in unsafe practices or had unprotected sex with someone who has.
The way in which he covers this subject is to wax lyrically about how ``safe''
straight sex is. Such views are among the reasons why the risk of HIV is
becoming more prominent in all aspects of life and sexuality.
He seems to add a comment about the use of condoms as an afterthought. Surely
he should not only stress the use of them but also their proper use as they are
not infallible. Dr Delvin also quotes figures for the number of known women
with HIV in Scotland but failed to stress that this was the known number and
not the actual number.
In the same issue Alan MacDermid writes about the number of deaths from Aids in
Scotland. On World Aids Day, the lights in Edinburgh's public buildings were
turned off for 10 minutes and 10 seconds this year whereas the time was six
minutes for the previous year.
This rapid rise will be curbed when people are educated about and, more
importantly, practise safer sex whether they deem a geographical area to be
``safe'' or not.
Brian J McGhee,
6 Calderwood,
Kilwinning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Humane killers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the great steeplechaser Red Rum was found lying on his stable floor it was
clear to everyone that his life was drawing to an end and that its continuation
would cause enormous suffering and indignity to the great animal.
He was therefore put to sleep with a humane killer.
The British public found this decision both brave and compassionate and indeed
humane killers are used every day by my veterinary colleagues.
The major difference between a human being and other animals is our
intelligence which allows us free will to make our own decisions. Why is it
that we are allowed to make these decisions for animals and yet we are
forbidden to make them for ourselves?
Dr Richard J M Wilson,
11a Westbourne Gardens,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dirty-tricks campaign hits immigrants where it hurts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alex Salmond</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028317</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is unlikely that Jasmine Sorabjee and Abiodun Igbindu will ever meet. For
one thing Mr Igbindu is a full-grown man and a Nigerian while Jasmine is but
three years old and British born.
However, within the past week both have been the victims of deportation orders
which beggar belief in any civilised society. In addition they have been the
targets of shameful Tory dirty-tricks campaigns involving ``background
briefings'' from those who scuttle around that party's darker corriders.
To take Jasmine's case first - this little girl was given a choice, at least of
sorts. She could have stayed in this country if she had been placed into care
with the possibility of never seeing her mother again. Although her mother has
a British passport and though she had married a British man the immigration
service took the view that this had been a marriage of convenience and that Mrs
Sorabjee had to go.
This might seem a remarkable conclusion to reach about a marriage which
produced a child but it is possible that the Home Office assessment is correct.
The question is, however, does not the arrival of Jasmine, whose rights as a
British subject should be as certain as those of any Government Minister,
change matters fundamentally both in terms of principle and of human compassion?
The London Evening Standard took up Jasmine's case last week and launched a
withering attack on Michael Howard, a man whose own forbears were offered
refuge in Britain.
At this stinging assault from a normally Tory paper the Home Office machine
moved up a gear. Its response was to leak to a less scrupulous and even more
loyal Tory tabloid damaging details about Jasmine's mother. It seems Mrs
Sorabjee is no angel. She has a criminal conviction and a number of minor
points against her character.
It is perhaps as well that the Home Office officials, acting on the orders of
their political masters, were unable to find anything too damaging against
three-year-old Jasmine or no doubt she as well as her mother would have been
the target of this vicious brand of character assassination. Perhaps the spin
doctors could have designated the toddler as a potential future criminal or,
even worse, a likely future single parent.
So at the end of this sorry tale there was no room at the inn for Jasmine and
her mother who now face an uncertain future in Kenya. Michael Howard remains
Home Secretary and the Evening Standard is left openly musing what manner of
people it has supported in office as Ministers of the Crown.
Unlike Jasmine, Mr Abiodun Igbindu is not yet on the plane for Africa, although
few would give much for his chances of hanging on in Britain for long. Mr
Igbindu arrived in June at Heathrow and sought political asylum, citing his
previous torture and arrest in Nigeria as a pro-democracy activist. Over the
period his case has been heard there has been ample evidence that Nigeria is
not a healthy place to be and among those who have made representations include
the former Home Secretary Douglas Hurd.
However, things have gone downhill at the Home Office since Douglas Hurd was in
charge. Rattled by the extent of cross-party support Mr Igbindu was receiving,
details of his application were passed to Conservative Central Office who then
offered them to newspapers because ``we do not feel we have got our case across
on this one''.
That statement from a Tory spokeswomen, printed on the front page of the
Guardian yesterday, betrays a great deal. Clearly in Tory central office these
cases are regarded as essentially political battles where there is no
distinction between the role of the political party and that of the Government
department.
Tory central office now acts as a sewer for whatever slime can be directed at
any unfortunate applicant whose case is in danger of stirring the public
conscience.
The Guardian quotes the former director of research at Tory central office on
the Government's re-election strategy as placing the attitude to the new Asylum
Bill in its political context. He said: ``Immigration, an issue which we raised
successfully in 1992 and again in the 1994 Euro-elections campaign, played
particularly well in the tabloids and has more potential to hurt.''
Those hurt to date by this shameful playing of the race card include a
three-year-old child and a Nigerian dissident.
One of the attractions of a written constitution and a Bill of Rights proposed
by the SNP for the constitution of a new Scotland is that it would afford all
our citizens the protection of entrenched rights, separated from the whim of
any politician on the scrounge for the cheapest form of votes.
In two weeks' time the Home Office will host its annual Christmas reception.
Perhaps over the sounds of merriment Mr Howard and his Scrooge-like Ministers
might just hear the occasional rattle of Marlow's chains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gift of a rebel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN COMRIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE exhibition celebrating 75 Years of Painting recently held at Glasgow School
of Art, has led to the gift of a large collection of drawings, and a book of
newspaper cuttings, by the family of the late Paisley artist Archibald A
McGlashan (d.1980).
The drawings witness some of the concerns of the life class before the First
World War while the cuttings reveal much about art in Scotland in the 1920s.
In his best drawings, McGlashan captures anatomical form with a rugged outline,
achieving structure by vigorous diagonal hatching. Used together, the drawings
and cuttings reveal the career of the artist and the stylistic and moral
influence of the school on its students, while Fra Newbery was its director
(until 1917).
The present director of the school, Dugald Cameron, shares important values
with Newbery: the value of drawing to artists, its link to the values of the
past, and the beneficial role of the artist in society. Cameron describes
drawing as ``the one golden thread'' that links the past to the present.
At present, he sees the artist's role as limited by a public perception of
self-indulgence, a view he would like to see changed. As McGlashan's cutting
book reveals, fads and fashion were secondary to individual personality when he
was a student from 1908-13. Newbery's students had enough strength of
conviction about this, to pay tribute to him for having ``held up to his
students a fine ideal of their personal development''.
The art event of 1919 in Glasgow was the formation of the ``rebel artists''
Glasgow Society of Painters and Sculptors (GSP&amp;S), which included Newbery
students as its leading members: James Cowie, William McCance, McGlashan, Agnes
Millar Parker, Robert Sivell, and the sculptor Benno Schotz.
These ``rebels'' would each gain positions of importance in the Scottish art
world. McGlashan's cuttings give a blow-by-blow account of the arguments and
tensions within the society, leading to a spectacular split at the 1921
exhibition.
This long-forgotten event is of importance to Scottish art because it is proof
that a brotherhood of values existed, shared by the hanging committee members.
Cowie, McGlashan, Sivell, and Schotz rejected half of the 30 members' work, and
displayed 40 of their own works out of a total of 63 at the 1921 exhibition, an
understandably controversial act.
Set in the international context, their action was significant since it came at
a time when European art was in a state of turmoil after the trauma of the
First World War - a time when, as yet, no new art form or style had emerged out
of the chaos of war.
Informed by Newbery's influence, and the Scots sought experience of the war,
which for these artists was a combination of pacifist oppositon to war, and
soldiers' disgust with war. Each would seek to renew the humanist tradition
that had existed in art since the Renaissance, and concern themselves with the
human condition, in a world shattered by war. The events of 1921 were a public
statement of these concerns.
Their values were influenced by socialist ideals. Like the Glasgow leaders of
the Independent Labour Party: Patrick Dollan, David Kirkwood, James Maxton, and
John Wheatley, (Dollan and Kirkwood were painted by McGlashan) they would
strive for the improvement of society, using democratic and traditional moral
values and resisting the alienating qualities of modernism.
At Glasgow School of Art, it was the attempt to identify half its history of
creativity, that persuaded McGlashan's family, particularly his daughter Agnes,
to place the drawings and cuttings where she feels they belong, in the archives
of Glasgow School of Art. A place where students can easily view and learn some
of the concerns of the past that have relevance today from an important
predecessor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT seems to me that all the recent critics of John Macleod are intellectual
pygmies compared to your outstanding journalist. They cannot hold a candle to
him.
Hugh Phillips says we should expect more from a Christian journalist in one of
our quality newspapers. Have your correspondents studied some of the
contributions of so-called top-rate journalists in most of our quality
newspapers?
Believe me, in John Macleod you have one of the best quality journalists and
religious writers.
All your correspondents go on about the saccharine-type Christian love, sickly
ecumenism, the ``need'' for meeting together (no matter what we believe), and,
of course, the bogyman of them all - the hated fundamentalism which was the
doctrinal stance of the early New Testament Church.
Not one of John Macleod's critics, it seems to me, can present him with a
convincing intellectual argument against his doctrinal views, particularly on
the doctrine of the Church. John Macleod is, from a Protestant point of view,
doctrinally sound, historically accurate, and journalistically brilliant.
It is often the aim and objective of less talented men and women to destroy
such writers and apologists for the Protestant faith and, of course, your
recent correspondents are at it again - sack John Macleod!
Tom Gill describes him as offensive, conveniently forgetting that there is such
a thing as the offence of the Gospel. John Knox, John Calvin, and Martin Luther
would no doubt also be described by John Macleod's critics as ``lacking love''
because they attacked doctrinal error in their day.
Robert A Penney,
18/4 Thistle Court,
Donaldson Street,
Kirkintilloch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The devolution dividend.  Poll reflects appetite for change</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLITICIANS, whatever they might tell you, take opinion polls seriously,
especially if their party is reflected to advantage. Mr George Robertson was
undoubtedly happy last night at the performance of Labour in our System Three
poll, particularly as the percentage rise in his party's popularity over two
months was 11%. No doubt he will be able to advance many reasons for this
result, yet it comes against the backdrop of a time in which the Labour Party
has not been particularly active, preferring instead to watch the Secretary of
State for Scotland, Mr Michael Forsyth, work himself into a lather of
``listening'' and activity which appears to have brought his party not the
slightest benefit.
Mr Robertson is not a superstitious soul; he will insist that Labour's
programme, together with the Liberal Democrats, on constitutional reform in
Scotland is the issue which has brought the greatest dividends. He is probably
correct in this analysis. There does appear to be a settled appetite for a
measure of devolution within the minds of the Scottish electorate and it is
likely that this will have been enhanced by the various St Andrew's Day
announcements of which Mr Forsyth's was the least impressive.
The Scottish Nationalists will be disappointed by this poll. They have already
had evidence that some of those who vote for them prefer devolution to
independence and this cast of opinion will probably strengthen as a General
Election approaches. There is little that can be said about the Tories, save
the obvious fact that their hyper-activity of recent months has not impressed
the electorate. There should, however, be real sorrow at the lowly state of the
Liberal Democrats who have persisted in thinking creatively about many
political issues but who appear fated never to get the credit for their
contribution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Only in Glasgow</HEADLINE>
