<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028321</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT can only happen in Glasgow. I asked the girl in the florist's shop for two
roses for two ladies I was entertaining to dinner and she said: ``Don't forget
to iron your shirt''.
Harry Diamond,
27f Greenholme Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>At the Sharp end</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Freeman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LED from the front by Chief Constable Leslie Sharp, Strathclyde Police have in
the past four and a half years achieved results which can safely be held to
have exceeded anything achieved by any other UK police force since the war.
To reach that conclusion it is necessary to believe that paramount among the
primary tasks of the police is reducing the crime rate; explaining how this has
been achieved brings Leslie Sharp close to the areas which cause him fears for
the continuation of those successes in the future. Therein also lies the
explanation for his retiral six months early, and at a point when it is clear
he would have liked to have driven on another two years to see his
self-appointed task through.
Principal of these caveats is the current reorganisation of local government.
The political imperative which informed the changes is outwith his agenda but
he can foresee the possible consequences with attendant difficulties for the
Scottish police service as a whole and Strathclyde Police in particular.
Outwith these current difficulties, he believes that in about the next seven
years Scotland will have just one police force.
Mr Sharp says that the case for the single force will become undeniable if the
devolution debate moves forward at its present pace.
He does not, however, see an all-Scottish force as a national police force
controlled by a ministry of justice, but sees instead, in the current trend
towards widening the role of institutions such as the Scottish Grand Committee
and the Scottish Economic Council, an expanded role for the Scottish Office's
Police Advisory Board. That body, with its elected representatives from Cosla,
the police staff associations, the consumer groups and the Government itself,
could form the basis of a new all-Scottish police authority which need not
slavishly follow the lines of the widely-respected Northern Ireland Police
Authority but which would obviously have similarities.
``I have maintained this point of view since 1991 and the idea has not been
dismissed by the Scottish Office. The Police Advisory Board could form the
necessary buffer between the force and central government, taking out direct
political control.''
He believes there is nothing to fear from such a development.
Turning to the partnership between the Strathclyde force and the police
authority he had only praise. He told the authority only last week - composed
almost 100% of Labour councillors - that Strathclyde had become a ``shining
beacon in terms of law and order'', an extravagant-sounding assertion which
stands up not badly to closer examination. He also said, importantly, that they
- the chief constable and his Labour-controlled committee - had walked a
tightrope amazingly well.
The real sense of regret that this relationship will end with the demise of
Strathclyde Regional Council is something that Leslie Sharp does not disguise.
He puts down much of the success of his policing to the strategic overview
possible under the council's all-embracing wing. This enabled him to take a
wider view, to dovetail specific, on-the-ground police initiatives into
communities hand-in-hand with education, social work, housing and even roads,
drainage and sewage departments. Entire areas, many blighted by crime,
deprivation, poverty, poor housing and degraded infrastructure, benefited as a
result.
``My organisation has a strategic role in the West of Scotland and the regional
council had the same boundary and the same strategic approach to the provision
of services. When the council disappears I find no new organisation which
matches my strategic role. That could create difficulties between the chief
constable and the new unitary authorities, each one of which will contribute
their share of resources.
``Yet I must have mobility of labour to police the area. What will happen when
I move officers away from one town to police disorder, or even floods, in
another? It could be regarded with suspicion, so people will simply have to see
it could be their turn next,'' he says.
The new joint police board drawn from the 12 authorities will therefore have to
attempt to reach a wider vision, he believes, otherwise the new chief constable
(John Orr) will find himself in difficulties.
To focus this problem, Leslie Sharp points to the potential in Glasgow for
explosions of violence, a historical recurrence since the 1930s, and which from
time to time requires intensive policing. On the other hand, because of the
vastness of the territory, Argyll gets greater use of the police helicopter, an
expensive resource.
``That is what the new unitary authorities must take on board,'' he says.
``They will have their own parochial concerns but they must not forget the
strategic overview.''
He is currently trying to impress on them the need to undertake certain
functions jointly, such as emergency planning, child protection and road safety.
``At the moment, I have one-door entry with the roads department on road
safety. Do I now have to share this with 12 roads departments? We had one-door
entry on child protection, with the education department, social work, the
reporter to the children's panel which in practice worked very well. After
April 1, is the chief constable to work with 12 directors of social work on
child protection?
``Law and order in its broadest sense will be entirely dependent on how
succesful the new unitary authorities are at joint working in these key areas.
The other side of the coin, where the tensions could arise, is that if they are
successful at joint working will not the Scottish Office start looking askance
at what looks suspiciously like the creation of another Strathclyde Regional
Council?'' he asks.
There are two other vital areas which Leslie Sharp speaks about which bear
heavily on his retirement decision; pointers to why he wishes to call a halt to
a 40-year policing career. Both are political in the sense that they point
towards the current Government's policies.
At a time when, post Operation Eagle, Strathclyde Police are co-operating as
never before with the Customs service to combat drugs smuggling, to the point
where there is complete sharing of intelligence data matched only by the
Metropolitan Police, he despairs when he sees that the nation's perimeter fence
is crumbling. It does not make sense, he says, to close the Customs office at
Campbeltown just as a new ferry service to Northern Ireland begins; that is one
tiny, but irksome example. He is sceptical of Government claims that the
``new'' Customs operations will be just as effective for being more
intelligence based. Perhaps so, but they will miss the benefits of
knowledgeable pairs of eyes at every port.
And Sheehy. Has the police service recovered from its gutting at the
Thatcher-inspired hand of the tobacco baron?
``Oh no,'' says Leslie Sharp. ``In my 40 years two major themes have emerged
from the policing debate. The first is that the chief constables must have
constitutional independence from political control. Every Royal Commission has
concluded that there should only be one boss for the chief constables and that
is the law of the land.
``What Sheehy has done is to dent that concept. He did not do so maliciously,
but the way his suggestions have been adopted have done the damage. I am aware
of the arguments against jobs for life, but if a chief constable is coming to
the end of a fixed-term appointment it seems to me to be very difficult for him
to exercise impartial judgment. Add to that the fact he can earn up to 7.5%
bonus against objectives set by his local authority and it is a recipe for
disaster. These things could be very dangerous in the wrong hands, and who is
to say that local authority or ministerial powers will always be in safe
hands?'' he states.
When he arrived in Strathclyde, Leslie Sharp says, there was confusion as to
the role of the force. With dwindling resources and rising crime they were
trying to squeeze out as much as possible, but with no great success. He gave
them a clear set of objectives - to reduce crime, increase detection, reduce
disorder and increase road safety - at the same time as making war on
bureaucracy.
When he looks back, that seems to him to have been one of the major factors in
bringing a unified identity to the force. He also found on his desk an
inspectorate report which was harshly critical of the force's lack of success
in tackling housebreaking; a few meetings later and Operation Bud was formed,
targeting every available officer on known housebreakers, and success followed.
Detections jumped from 9% to 24%, which was modest enough, but contained
lessons.
Bud had lasted three months, so the 90-day operation was born. The importance
of better intelligence on the criminals was the salient lesson but it was also
apparent that intelligence in the force had become an exercise in card filing,
cards which were seldom read.
That was still ringing in their ears when the East End of Glasgow erupted in
gangland violence. Leslie Sharp flooded the area with officers, men from Ayr to
Tiree as he puts it, and Operation Interlock broke down the wall of silence.
It became clear from this that Strathclyde crime was floating on a sea of guns,
so Operation Spur became the third intensive 90-day purge. Every criminal
arrested, no matter how minor the offence, was interrogated on where guns could
be bought or hired, how much they cost and who had them. It was surprising how
many people brought in for mere drunkenness knew something which led to a gun.
Around 5000 have been recovered and Operation Spur survives today in its
original form.
Leslie Sharp states openly that he authorised detectives to spend money to buy
in the most dangerous weapons imaginable: Kalashnikovs and Nato semi-automatics
brought back from the Gulf war. But, as The Herald pointed out at the time, his
strategy was wilfully misunderstood by tabloids and tabloid television. It was
the intelligence which was bought, not just the guns.
He makes no bones about the fact that he forced a serious change of culture on
officers, particularly detectives, by the concentration on the gathering and
use of intelligence. Surveillance and targeting requires patience and often
wasted effort, but he declares: ``By golly, it paid off.''
He agrees that it has meant demands on the public's patience, in that the
greater good has sometimes meant that responses to lesser matters have been
delayed. He can point to the successes, however, such as Operation Blade, which
tackled knife crime, Operations Dove and the covert Hawk which tackled
drugs-fuelled violence in Paisley, Operation Turnkey which cut housebreaking in
Strathclyde by a third.
The growth of Neighbourhood Watch has helped, as has the force's concentration
on the crime prevention message and the arrival on the scene of CCTV in town
centres. In the past week Strathclyde Police has completed phase two of
Operation Eagle, the biggest and most comprehensive drive against the drugs
culture yet mounted by a UK force. The results have to be assessed in the long
term but nearly 5000 people have been arrested and #4.5m of drugs seized. The
intelligence gathered has been overwhelming.
The balance sheet of the past four and a half years shows, according to Leslie
Sharp, that no area of Strathclyde is not experiencing the benefits of
decreasing crime. Even the contentious area of crimes of violence, the 3.5% of
total crime which attracts the most comment, is responding. The current figures
which show an increase for the past summer are misleading, because the increase
reflects the increased effort by the police themselves to stop and search for
offensive weapons. Leslie Sharp is conscious that misplaced fear of violent
crime can be debilitating.
He raises fears for the future of such efforts as the Govan Initiative when
urban aid funding runs out in a year, for the many CCTV schemes when running
costs have to be met. Will the new local authorities be willing to take on the
responsibility for providing resources?
As Operation Eagle's caravan moves on, will the new drugs action teams based on
the health boards have sufficient clout and ambition to harness the vast range
of initiatives being undertaken by the health, education, caring and voluntary
agencies, and the enforcement agencies to ensure that everyone is pulling in
the same direction?
Whatever the outcome, Leslie Sharp believes the Strathclyde experience has
demonstrated that Scottish society need not simply flap its hands despairingly
in the face of crime.
``We have convinced everyone that something can be done about crime. There is
no real cause for fear or despair,'' he states.
The context of how the police operate, he adds, is the all-important factor
which facilitates this.
</TEXT>
