<HEADLINE>Companions champion the Celtic connection</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nerys Lloyd-Pierce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH the end of the UK Year of Literature and Writing in sight, the residents
of Swansea were perhaps suffering from a degree of festival fatigue. Maybe,
with half an eye cast towards Christmas, turning out for the penultimate event
of the year-long calendar, the Caledonian Companions took second place.
Whatever the reason, some of the events during the eight days were woefully
ill-attended.
That said, it is to be hoped that the speakers and performers who entertained
sparse audiences will go away with the impression that the enthusiasm of the
few made up for the lack of numbers.
The festival, co-ordinated by Dr Fred Freeman, scholar, broadcaster, critic,
and trustee of the Scottish Traditional Music Trust, was certainly not lacking
in gravitas or diversity. James Kelman, Sorley MacLean, Brian McNeill, Alasdair
Gray, Meg Bateman, Peter Nardini, Rod Paterson, and the Tannahill Weavers gave
voice to the disparate and exuberant elements of Scottish culture, while
re-establishing lapsed connections with Wales.
``Scotland has traditional links with Wales which are virtually forgotten,''
explains Dr Freeman. ``South of the Clyde and Forth the language spoken for
many, many years was ancient Welsh. Names like Strathclyde and Lanark are
derived from ancient Welsh. Even our national heroes like William Wallace and
our patron saints have Welsh connections.
``There are subtler associations too. Our two countries share similar elements
of irony, self-satire and black humour. We also share a tradition of pastoral
and industrial poetry and a parallel commitment to democracy.''
Thanks to the efforts of the Scottish Tourist Board and Hollywood, the outside
world has been spoon-fed a cliched and depressingly limited view of the
country. Dr Freeman is at pains to widen our horizons beyond tartan shortbread
tins, claymores, and kilts to open our eyes to the ``unhomogenous'' nature of
Scottish culture.
``I am trying to put across a broader picture, a more holistic view, for want
of a better word. It might be an unconventional approach when compared to other
literature festivals, but I don't care. I've tried to put song, literature, and
poetry back together. In my opinion, the way we teach each as a separate entity
is utterly ridiculous, they should not be compartmentalised as though each has
nothing to do with the other. I dislike also the way literature and poetry is
taught as a cold text. In many cases it needs music to bring it to life.''
The Living Across Cultures event brought together Meg Bateman, Sorley MacLean,
Hamish Henderson, and James Kelman, a hybrid gathering which threw up issues of
language, nationalism, cultural imperialism, and the tyranny of Middle English.
Both Kelman and Bateman drew attention to the popular notion of the Highlands
as one of Britain's last great wildernesses, a perception which avoids the
uncomfortable reality that the Highlands were once home to thousands.
While avoiding sinking into an anti-English quagmire, Bateman, who writes
poetry in English and in her second language, Gaelic, compared the common
experience of two Celtic nations.
``In Wales you've had the cottage burning. In Scotland we haven't got around to
doing anything so decisive. But bitterness will get us nowhere.''
Romanticism of the past and of the rural idyll earned her scorn. ``I think
romanticism is only a slightly secondary sin to prejudice as it blinds people
to each other's humanity.''
James Kelman, belligerent and vocal, hit the audience like a slap in the face
after the vulnerable charm of Meg Batemen.
Earlier he had attended a reading at the University of Glamorgan in which a
lecturer stated that the language of the African/American male was incapable of
expressing abstract thought. As Kelman pointed out those who speak in so-called
working-class accents are no stranger to this kind of elitism.
``It is really horrible to hear generation after generation after generation of
people inferiorise the native Celt. It appears as though they have no right to
take part in debates on high abstract subjects such as linguistics, art or
theology because their language indicates that their intellect is incapable of
it.''
Those who failed to turn up for Peter Nardini's gig at Wales's new literature
centre, Ty Llen, missed a rare treat. Described as a ``polymath'' and a
``modern Scottish alchemist'', the singer, songwriter, artist, and playwright
captivated a tiny but appreciative audience with his humorous, thoughtful and
articulate compositions. The Scottish people are lucky to have him on their
doorstep.
</TEXT>
