<HEADLINE>Broadside for market forces.  Yarrow's rare skills must be pres erved</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975028324</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is no longer much point in being nostalgic about the lost glories of
shipbuilding on the Clyde but on the subject of Yarrow we might be permitted
sorrow and a measure of anger. The point has been made on innumerable occasions
that Yarrow is a specialist builder of military warships and not very much
else. It is easy to criticise the yard and its management for this state of
affairs but, as is often the case with easy criticism, it is largely wrong. Not
everyone can build a modern, sophisticated warship and the experience of Yarrow
should make the Glasgow yard the favourite for the forthcoming Type 23 orders.
It is simplistic to say that it is this specialisation, and the excellence
which has grown from it, which has penalised the long-term future of Yarrow.
Attempts have been made to diversify into different shipbuilding sectors but
Yarrow is essentially set up to be a builder of warships and the only orders
which have been available in an industry beset by worldwide recession have been
of the sort which are not labour intensive. This is not the fault of Mr Murray
Easton or his workforce; it is a reflection of current conditions. The question
which must be asked is whether there is anything we can do about it.
The first thing the Government should do is to ensure that the Ministry of
Defence delivers orders on time. An announcement was expected by this week but
the end of February is now the likeliest date. There may be good reasons for
this, although we hope that the delay has not been caused by avoidable failures
on the part of the Ministry of Defence. It does not require a high level of
intelligence to understand that a specialised shipbuilding yard is a place of
rare and intermingled skills. Whatever the plans for Britain's surface fleet it
would be folly to allow the expertise which Yarrow personifies to be lost. It
should not be beyond the wit of the Ministry of Defence, perhaps with the
prodding of politicians, to draw up a plan for preserving skills which are
required for strategic reasons. Market forces are against this sort of thing,
of course, but then market forces know nothing of the national interest.
</TEXT>
