<HEADLINE>Premier survives no-confidence vote and pledges to go on with reforms.  Strikers drum up support as defiant Juppe  stands firm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Tuesday . THE 11-day public sector strike in France remained in deadlock
tonight after French Prime Minister Alain Juppe announced live on television
that he would not give into union demands to withdraw reforms aimed at cutting
public spending.
Speaking hours after public sector workers staged huge demonstrations against
the government reforms in Paris and in towns throughout France, Mr Juppe
repeated the argument he had given earlier in the National Assembly, where his
government easily defeated a vote of no confidence by the Socialist opposition.
The Prime Minister acknowledged that the life of many people had become
difficult because of the strikes, and said that the country had to get out of
the deadlock.
``We cannot go on like this,'' he said. However his only concession was to
underline that no decisions had yet been taken on reforming public sector
pensions, which, he said, was to be studied by a government commission.
``I will not withdraw my programme. That would be a mistake and a fault,
against everybody's interests and against the interests of France,'' he said.
There could be no other solutions apart from the reforms proposed by his
government, said Mr Juppe, who went on to justify his measures on health
expenditure, pensions, and French railways.
``Don't believe all the lies you have been told over the past
fortnight.......these reforms are not intended          to hinder but to
help,'' he       said.
Mr Juppe said that reducing the number of those out of work remained the
absolute priority of his government, as President Jacques Chirac had promised
before his election.
The government had made progress in the fight against long-term unemployment,
the Prime Minister said, but had suffered setbacks in creating jobs for young
people.
Rounding off on a patriotic note, Mr Juppe said it was necessary to try to
understand the anxiety of university students who had been on strike for the
past month.
``But is there a single country in the world where you would rather live than
France?'' he asked.
Trade unions were unimpressed by the Prime Minister's statement, his first
since the strikes began.
Strike action in the public sector showed every sign of worsening tonight. The
union Force Ouvriere called on its members to spread the strike and the CGT
said Mr Juppe had let slip an opportunity to start a dialogue.
The Force Ouvriere leader, Marc Blondel, said the strikes would go on until the
plans were scrapped and, in a sign that he is ready for a long battle, he
launched an appeal for cash to compensate rail strikers for lost pay.
Earlier, tens of thousands of strikers braved freezing cold and snow to rally
in Paris against the planned reforms.
Trade unions said there were 160,000 marchers in Paris and one million across
France, including Toulouse, Bordeaux, Rouen, Marseilles, Nantes, and Le Mans.
The march ended in violence in the capital, where riot police intervened to
disperse about 500 youths who overturned about 20 cars. Police arrested 28
people who they described as ``uncontrolled elements'' and ``breakers'' - terms
they use for anarchists and young toughs from the Paris suburbs often bent on
looting under cover of confusion in the streets.
In one incident a dozen hooded youths on the fringes of the demonstration were
detained while apparently preparing to smash the window of a sports shop.
In Nantes, several hundred students, some hurling petrol bombs, battled riot
police firing teargas. Twenty police officers were hurt, mostly by flying
stones.
Meanwhile commuters shivered in mammoth rush-hour traffic jams that snaked into
Paris as the rail system continued at a standstill and the bus and Metro strike
entered its eighth day.
However, despite union appeals for the strike to spread beyond the public
sector, there was little sign of it catching on in private companies.
Financial markets that had been unsettled in recent days by the prospect of a
drawn-out dispute responded well to the government's determination to stick to
its guns. The franc rose against the Deutschmark and the stock market index
closed up 2.25% after a six-day slide.
As the strikes today spread to schools, hit postal deliveries, and disrupted
the telephone and electricity services, public frustration began to boil over
when a man drove his car into a group of strikers in Paris, injuring one person.
