<HEADLINE>School delays ballot threat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028326</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GLASGOW secondary school last night held back from using an opt-out ballot in
its battle to keep it open.
However, the board of Garthamlock secondary expressed its ``earnest and
determined opposition'' to Strathclyde region's proposal to close the school
next June and warned that it might still seek self-governing status if the
council does not back down.
The council's education committee is due to consider the closure plan at a
meeting today. If the councillors approve the proposal, the plan will be put
out for consultation.
As revealed exclusively earlier this week in The Herald, parents have been
considering exploiting the Government's opting-out legislation as a means of
saving the school, which is less than 40% full and needs #780,000 worth of
repairs following a fire in May.
In a statement issued after a meeting last night, the school board said it had
decided not to approve a motion seeking an opt-out ballot of parents ``at
present''. It insisted that Strathclyde could partially reinstate the fire
damage at a cost of #300,000 and allow ``this attractive, well-maintained, and
genuinely successful school to continue to serve its local and distinct
community''.
The board said that it considered Garthamlock compared very favourably with
similar schools in Glasgow, particularly with regard to attendance and
examination results. It added that the prospect of sending the pupils to
Lochend or Smithycroft secondaries did not present an obvious attraction.
``Our school is a major resource for the community, being used every evening,
and on Saturdays and Sundays, by different community groups. It seems short
sighted in the extreme to close a major resource when the Greater Easterhouse
Initiative is committed to the long-term regeneration of this part of the city.
``If the education authority is prepared to opt out of its commitment to its
highly-publicised `social strategy', then the parents of this school have an
obligation to consider opting in to the responsibility of running their own
school.''
</TEXT>
