<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>England call on Barmby</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Ince, Paul Merson, and everyone else outside of England's latest squad,
now know it will take something special to break into Terry Venables' plans for
Euro `96.
With just one change - Nick Barmby for injury-hit Gary Pallister - for next
week's friendly against Portugal, the England manager signals the door to the
finals is closing.
With only the recuperating Darren Anderton and Pallister assured of a welcome
beyond the 23 players named yesterday, Venables already faces at least four
tough decisions to trim down to UEFA's 20-man limit, plus a stand-by goalkeeper.
That lays down the challenge to the likes of Ince and John Barnes, and hopefuls
like Arsenal's Merson. With only 24 hours' preparation, and encouraged by the
all-round performance in last month's 3-1 win over finalists Switzerland,
Venables would not have made many changes anyway for Tuesday's latest Wembley
friendly.
However, he warns: ``The door is not closed, but players have got to fight to
get through it now. It is still ajar, and while it is like that you can still
get through, you don't need the combination.''
``I said before that around this time I would be thinking about getting a
settled side. We're getting consistency from the players we're choosing and
that's what we're asking for. Now they've got to make sure they protect their
positions.''
Venables has included Jamie Redknapp, though he is only just recovering from
the hamstring he injured in the first five minutes against Switzerland and the
FA now face a #30,000 `insurance bill' from Liverpool.
He said: ``I spoke to Roy Evans and he expects him to play on Saturday so,
because he's a young lad, I decided to include him in the squad. Whether he'll
be fit enough to play is another matter but it won't do him any harm to be
around the squad.''
</TEXT>
