<DOCNO>GH951206-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blitz on burglars</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028328</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S biggest-yet blitz on burglars - codenamed Operation Christmas Cracker
- went with a bang yesterday, netting 2334 suspects and #1.5m worth of stolen
goods in England and Wales.
The operation, involving 10% of the nation's police manpower, was launched with
3700 dawn raids by 12,000 officers.
Operation Christmas Cracker involved police from 40 forces and is the biggest
combined police operation yet launched in this country.
It had been developed after the success of other high-profile crime crackdowns.
From 6am, officers were forcing their way into the homes of suspected burglars
and taking away men and women for questioning at local police stations.
In Dorset, a substantial quantity of heroin was discovered.
In Cambridgeshire, one suspect was arrested after DNA profiling by police and
in Devon and Cornwall a 16-year-old runaway was found hiding at a raided
address and returned home.
</TEXT>
