<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland gets a brand new image Initiative's aim is to aggressively market a wide range of products and services throughout the world</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028329</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIRST there was Scotland the Brave. Now comes Scotland - The Brand.
Over the next 18 months, the Scotland - The Brand unit, which was launched
yesterday, will raise the standard for Scotland overseas to try and increase
business generated through trade, tourism and the arts.
Specifically, the four-man unit, which has a start-up budget of #300,000, has
been charged with:
n Co-ordinating the promotion and image of Scotland in three key cities of the
world, New York, Paris and Hamburg.
n Increasing Scottish exports by #5m.
n Reducing export costs for participating companies by 3%.
n Increasing the number of tourists to visit Scotland.
The unit is a joint-venture among Scottish Trade International, the joint
Scottish Enterprise/Scottish Office export body, Highlands and Islands
Enterprise, the Scottish Tourist Board, the British Council and the private
sector.
The concentration on a series of promotions in New York, Paris and Hamburg
follows a successful pilot carried out in Marks &amp; Spencer in Paris in March and
April, which led to a 145% rise in the sales of Scottish food and drink. Six
months later, sales were still up by 40% compared with the corresponding period
in 1994.
As well as events, the unit's strategy will also include networking, the
provision of advice and assistance on how best to use international perceptions
of Scotland to support company brand activity, and promotional initiatives at
some of the world's top stores, restaurants and hotels.
Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch said: ``I very much welcome and
encourage initiatives such as Scotland - The Brand and I hope that it will
assist in aggressively marketing a wide range of Scotland's products and
services throughout the world.
``Whether we are selling to Europe, the US, Japan or the Middle East, it is
important that we convey a message of a dynamic modern country. Scotland - The
Brand will do just that.
``This new promotion unit for trade, tourism and the arts will help raise the
awareness of Scottish products, services and culture and, at the same time,
promote a series of positive images of Scotland.
``Wearing both my industry and tourism hats, I am particularly delighted that
we are recognising the benefits in working together to maximise and capitalise
on our strengths in promoting Scotland and all that is best in Scotland.''
Lord Macfarlane, chairman of Scotland - The Brand, said the setting up of the
unit was a major step forward in marketing Scotland overseas.
``It follows on from our conference last year at which business leaders from
throughout the country supported the concept of a central promotions agency.
This collaboration between STI, the STB, HIE, and the British Council, together
with the private sector, is the start of a journey to use our resources and
target our efforts more effectively.''
Robert Crawford, MD of Scottish Enterprise Operations, said: ``Scotland - The
Brand is a practical pragmatic promotional unit working in three international
cities where the STB is actively promoting Scotland as a tourism destination.
``It is giving greater focus to Scottish products already in the market place
and actively encouraging department stores, restaurants, hotels and speciality
shops to increase their range of Scottish produce.''
Derek Reid, STB chief executive, said the tourist industry had already shown
the benefits of co-operation, having worked closely with the promoters of Rob
Roy and Braveheart to sell Scotland to the world while, at the same time,
increasing revenue.
He said: ``Scotland - The Brand will work in tandem with the STB's overseas
consumer campaigns to enhance the reputation for quality products which
Scotland enjoys abroad. By working in partnership, we will maximise our
marketing effort, ensuring that a wider spectrum of Scottish interests share in
this success.''
George Russell, Scotland - The Brand chief executive, said: ``Next year the M&amp;S
director in Europe wants to spread the Scotland - The Brand promotion to their
28 stores throughout Europe.
``At this stage, Scotland - The Brand will not take on the world, but we will
work initially in the three markets of common interest to the STB and STI - the
US, Germany and France, and to be more specific in New York, Hamburg, and
Paris.''
</TEXT>
