<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call to consider evidence on BSE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE outcry about BSE is over dramatic with insufficient attention paid to
assessment of the evidence, one of Scotland's leading animal scientists claimed
yesterday.
Professor Ian Aitken, scientific head of the Moredun Research Institute at
Edinburgh, said that in all the recent media attention there had been little
reference to the strong scientific support which the Ministry of Agriculture,
Fisheries and Food had available to it.
As scare stories began to spread and people talked of stopping eating beef,
there was a need for a cool, detached assessment of the scientific evidence,
Professor Aitken said. ``That is what has been lacking in the recent publicity
about BSE.''
Such facts came most effectively from scientific experts who had been
particularly concerned with the issue of BSE, he added. They were the principal
source of advice to Government departments.
``Ministry scientists have taken sensible, practical measures based on the
information available.''
Professor Aitken pointed out that the disease had been very quickly identified,
and appropriate measures put in place. ``All credit is due to the veterinary
sceintists at MAFF and elsewhere who have made a remarkable contribution to
understanding this disease.''
He admitted that very few cases had been discovered in other countries,
relative to the numbers found in Britain - but there had been instances
recorded in Ireland, Germany, France and Italy. ``One would have to ask if the
same rigour of diagnosis and scrutiny was being applied in other countries as
in this country,'' he said.
Professor Aitken was speaking during a press visit to the Moredun's new home in
the Pentlands Science Park, near Penicuik in Midlothian. The Moredun scientists
and other staff are about halfway through a #22m project which will see all
their work transferred from Gilmerton in Edinburgh to the new science park.
The development is being partially funded by the sale of the 31-acre site at
Gilmerton - bought for #2999 in 1920 by the four farmers who founded the
organisation to carry out research into animal diseases as a way of improving
the quality of their stock.
The science park, supported by European money and Lothian and Edinburgh
Enterprise, forms part of an animal science ``industry'' which has grown up in
Edinburgh and the rest of Midlothian with an annual turnover of about #75m and
employing about 2000 people.
The next phase of the development will include the transfer of the Moredun's
laboratories from Gilmerton. The present buildings on the new site include the
Moredun Foundation's headquarters which will also provide core facilities for
tenant companies. The aim is to encourage small science-based operations to
``cluster'' around the main facilities provided in the park.
The site also has facilities for housing cattle, sheep and goats. Three
separate flocks of sheep are maintained on nearby farmland to meet the
requirements of the centre.
One of the buildings now nearing completion houses high security isolation
units where animals can be kept in a germ-free atmosphere from birth. Staff
entering the area pass through a system of air locks and are required to shower
twice before entering the negative pressure rooms where the animals are housed.
The stringent precautions, which meet the latest Home Office specifications,
allow work to be done with genetically manipulated organisms which can be
contained within the unit.
</TEXT>
