<DOCNO>GH951206-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Consumers expected to have spent more during November</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028333</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOPES of a modest recovery in retail sales in November after two drab months
were boosted yesterday by figures from the British Retail Consortium, published
for the first time. The retailers' trade organisation again called for lower
interest rates.
The consortium's retail sales monitor showed an annual increase in the
like-for-like value of retail sales of 3.2% last month. This compared with 2.4%
in October and 3.4% in September.
``November was a marginally better month, with the onset of colder weather
proving particularly helpful for clothing and footwear retailers,'' the
consortium said. But rises in sales of food and drink were slightly weaker than
in previous months.
``The retail market remains extremely competitive with widespread price
promotion,'' the consortium added. ``The flat housing market limited sales of
related retail products, including furniture and carpets.''
Andrew Higginson, chairman of the consortium's economic affairs committee,
said: ``This modest improvement in retail sales is welcomed, but the overall
market remains fragile.
``Retailers will be hoping that the rise can be sustained through Christmas. A
cut in interest rates would provide a further useful boost to consumer
confidence.''
The Retail Consortium's new monthly monitor is a welcome additional source of
survey evidence and may prove to be a better guide than the CBI's distributive
trades survey, due tomorrow. But there are two major drawbacks. There is no
volume data and they are not adjusted for seasonal influences.
James Capel's Adam Cole said that, in order to get to the official retail sales
volume figures, it would be necessary to guess price movements and the
adjustments used by the Central Statistical Office. The figures had the
advantage over the CBI's of covering the whole month rather than just the first
two weeks. Values were also quantified.
Mr Cole is forecasting that the volume of retail sales rose 0.5% last month.
The CSO figures are due on Wednesday of next week, the same day as the
Chancellor meets the Governor of the Bank of England to determine whether rates
should be cut.
Andrew Sentance, the consortium's chief economic adviser, said: ``Retail sales
values are not yet increasing sufficiently strongly to provide the basis for
substantial volume growth.
``However, the Budget will put some money in taxpayers' pockets next year.
Helped by falling mortgage interest rates, 1996 should see a stronger consumer
economy than this year.''
</TEXT>
