<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drug dealer claims he `ran circles round the police' while paying a detective for tip-offs.  Court told of `inside information'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Graeme Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By GRAEME SMITH
A CONVICTED drugs dealer claimed yesterday that he ``ran circles round the
police'' because of information from a corrupt detective to whom he paid
thousands of pounds.
Ronald Cormack, who is serving a 15-year sentence imposed earlier this year for
drugs offences, was giving evidence at the trial of Grampian Police officer
Neil Cooper.
Mr Cooper, 36, denies corruption charges involving Cormack.
They include corruptly accepting #6000 and a number of subsequent payments and
giving Cormack details of confidential police information in relation to his
drug trafficking operations.
Cormack said he had been offered ``the services of a policeman'' by his
long-time friend Ian Smith, known as ``Fat Billy''.
He said Smith told him he could get Mr Cooper to pass information for payment.
He said Smith set up a meeting involving the three of them and Mr Cooper
confirmed he could supply information.
Cormack told the court: ``I said I wanted to make sure it was genuine
information. He said he would give me information that would confirm it beyond
doubt.''
Cormack said that, at their next meeting, in the Lochside bar, Mr Cooper told
him where his drugs were coming from and about surveillance operations. He said
he knew the information was good when Mr Cooper named one of his main drug
contacts, and an agreement was reached.
He said: ``Cooper told me he was getting the information from his brother, who
was working on the case.''
He said Smith was to act as their go-between and he paid Cormack #6000 that
day, followed by a weekly retainer of a couple of hundred pounds.
Cormack said his first meeting with Mr Cooper was in the spring of 1993. He
said he wanted ``inside information'', such as the undercover cars the police
used and the names of their informants.
One of the named informants was Kevin Jacks, to whom Cormack was supplying
drugs - so he used Jacks to feed false information to the police. That false
information was eventually fed back to him through Mr Cooper.
``I was feeding other information to see if it was coming back and also to
cause a lot of confusion,'' said Cormack.
He added:``I set up stings to make them look fools. Cooper warned me they were
going to set me up if they couldn't catch me legal.''
Cormack agreed that he had continued dealing in drugs through 1993 and 1994 and
added: ``I ran circles round them due to the information I was getting. I would
wind them up and make them know I was there.''
However, he said he cut Mr Cooper off in early 1994. He said: ``I took the
information but I didn't trust him.''
Cormack said he had no similar dealings with any other policemen.
Asked the total amount of money he had given Mr Cooper, he replied: ``I didn't
keep a tally, thousands. There had been an initial payment of #6000 and another
#1000 to #2000.''
Earlier, Cormack had told the court how Mr Cooper helped to avert trouble on
two occasions.
The first was after counterfeit watches which Smith sold were stolen. Cormack
said he and Smith tracked down Brian Brown, the man responsible, and added: ``I
stuck a gun under his chin and told him if there were any more threats he would
be dead before he hit the floor.''
He said Smith later phoned Mr Cooper to tell him what happened.
Cormack said: ``About two or three weeks later, I got a phone call at the house
and Smith said if I had a gun in the house to get rid of it because I might get
a call from the police.''
He said Mr Cooper briefed him on what to say before he went for his interview,
which was carried out by Mr Cooper and another officer. After the interview, he
heard nothing more of the incident.
Cormack then told of a break-in at the Inn at the Park Hotel, which he claimed
he arranged at the request of someone with ``a close connection'' to the hotel.
While he and Smith were inside, their lookout, Jim Reid, was arrested. After
waiting some time to find out what was happening, Smith phoned Mr Cooper at
Queen Street Police headquarters.
Mr Cooper told him Reid was in the cells but had said nothing. He said Reid was
going to go down only for illegal possession of a mobile phone.
The trial continues today.
Lord Macfadyen yesterday issued a reprimand to the Aberdeen Press and Journal
after a series of inaccuracies in their reporting of the trial.
He warned journalists he would take a serious view of any further inaccuracies
in their coverage of the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
