<DOCNO>GH951206-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Demolition shock as church goes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLANNING officer was ``enormously shocked'' when he learned that a
145-year-old Gothic church was being demolished, he told a court yesterday.
Mr Michael Hayes, 48, told Glasgow Sheriff Court how he sent his staff to try
to halt the workmen.
They failed, and Milton Free Church of Scotland in the city centre conservation
area was razed.
Mr Hayes, Glasgow's director of planning, was asked by depute fiscal Mrs Anne
Currie: ``What was the effect?'' He said: ``We were left with an eyesore
......a hole on what was a high-profile site in a conservation area, leaving
the backs of tenements in view.''
The church's minister, the Rev.John A.M.Mackay, of Aithrey Avenue, Jordanhill,
Glasgow, denies having the building demolished without proper permission.
Mr Hayes told Sheriff James Keegan that he had talks with Mr Mackay, who is
also the minister for the St Vincent Street church, a Greek Thomson grade A
listed building.
He told Mrs Currie he did not indicate that the Milton church in Garnethill
could be demolished, nor did any of his staff or the planning committee.
Mr Hayes sent staff to try to stop the demolition after he received a fax from
two members of the public concerned about it.
But he did not seek an immediate court order to stop the demolition, he said.
Mr John McCluskey, 42, a planning department enforcement officer, told how he
went to the site on Friday, May 26, and found workmen stripping the roof and
demolishing the building.
He told the foreman of the firm, Burnthills, that they did not have permission
to knock the church down.
He telephoned Wiseman Associates, of East Kilbride, the agents for Burnthills,
and informed them as well.
But when he returned after the holiday weekend he found the spire demolished
and the windows smashed and the interior damaged. On his third visit the church
was completely gone.
Mr McCluskey told defence solicitor Mr Alan Thomson that he did not know that
the contract with Burnthills had been made by the deacons' court of the church
before Mr Mackay was its minister. He said: ``As far as I was aware, Mr Mackay
was the minister of both congregations.''
A plan for a new church on the gap site was later refused by the council, the
court heard.
The case was adjourned until January 29.
</TEXT>
