<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devro clinches Teepak deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER just over eight months, Devro International has received US approval to
proceed with its #187m acquisition of the Teepak International edible food
casings manufacturer.
The deal was originally agreed in March whereby the Scottish sausage skin
manufacturer would buy Teepak of Illinois for $133.5m and the assumption of
debt of up to $155m. At a stroke, Devro becomes the world's largest
manufacturer in this sector, but it had to dispose of its own collagen sausage
casings business of Devro America.
Last year, the American subsidiary made pre-interest profits of #1.9m on sales
of #20.9m. That compared with a group total of pre-tax profit of #29.1m and is
just 4% of Devro and Teepak combined.
One slight snag is that the existing subsidiary manufactures casings for
Devro's other international markets and when sold there could be an impact.
Devro chief executive Graeme Alexander said that this was no big headache.
The deal will be satisfied by a mixture of equity, bank loans and using Devro's
own cash. To cover the near #30m cash element, there will be a placing and
clawback of Devro shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>news digestChristmas push on council tax</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028338</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Regional Council is planning a major Christmas crackdown on council
tax debtors. Final notices were issued yesterday offering 14 days to pay before
Sheriff Court proceedings begin. Vice-chairman of finance, Mr Jim Fry, said:
``It is not our intention to spoil anyone's Christmas.''
Lifeboat repairs
ARBROATH lifeboat Inchcape, built at a cost of #600,000 two years ago, has had
to be withdrawn temporarily from service due to structural faults. The lifeboat
is to be taken to Dorset later this week for repairs.
Irish viewers
SCOTTISH Television's High Road soap is to be screened five times a week in the
Irish Republic under a three-year deal with broadcaster RTE. The price was not
disclosed.
Anti-vandal project
THE Easterhouse estate in Glasgow has won #34,000 of European money for a
project to help combat vandalism.
Stress survey
WORKPLACE stress is a problem in nine out of 10 organisations and firms are
doing little to remedy the situation, according to a soon-to-be-published
survey undertaken by the Industrial Society.
Jail for abuser
A SEX offender who abused four young children was jailed for 10 years yesterday
at the High Court in Edinburgh. David Wood, 52, of Grange Pans, Bo'ness,
admitted serious indecency offences in Central Scotland between November 1964
and December 1981.
Suicide pact
A MAN, 21, is dead and a woman, 23, is seriously ill following a suspected
suicide pact. The couple were found in a fume-filled car near Bridgend, Mid
Glamorgan, yesterday.
Critically ill
LADY Celia Vestey, 46, the wife of multi-millionaire Lord Vestey was critically
ill yesterday after suffering a stroke.
Rape arrest
A YOUTH, 15, has been arrested in connection with the rape of an 81-year-old
woman on November 25 in an elderly people's complex in West Yorkshire.
Pay dispute
VAUXHALL workers at Luton and Ellesmere Port are due to start industrial action
today as fresh talks are held to settle a pay dispute.
Three killed
THREE people died when their car collided with a lorry last night. The victims,
a man, a girl and a boy, were in a Nissan Micra when it crashed between Oxton
and Lowdham, Nottinghamshire.
</TEXT>
