<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Dr Death' coins new name for his vocation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028339</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Tuesday. DOCTOR DEATH has chosen a new title for himself: he wants
to be known as a ``obitiarist''.
Dr Jack Kevorkian, who has helped a score of people commit suicide and has, so
far, escaped all legal penalties for his activities, has issued a set of
guidelines for assisted suicide, a process he wants to call ``patholysis''.
Seven other doctors joined him in promulgating the guidelines, which were
promptly denounced by the American Medical Association.
The AMA considers its members bound by the Hippocratic Oath to do patients no
harm, and therefore rigorously excludes assisted suicide by doctors, whatever
they call it or themselves.
Dr Kevorkian's new procedures provide that a patient should offer a written
request for a doctor to kill him. It should be witnessed by a doctor and two
adults who have no financial interest in the patient's estate.
Furthermore, the request would have to be accompanied by a statement from a
specialist in the patient's illness, a pain-management specialist, and a
psychiatrist, to the effect that the patient was in sound mind, and suffering
from an incurable disease that causes insufferable agony. When the
``patholysis'' is carried out, the patient must be in control of the procedure
and able to stop it.
It remains to be seen whether Dr Kevorkian will abide by his own rules. He has
devised a suicide machine and has set it up in patients' apartments, in the
back of a van, and in public parks. He has been prosecuted several times under
the laws of Michigan, where he lives, and the laws have been changed to forbid
his activities.
So far, however, he has escaped conviction and insists that he will continue
with his mission in life, which is to allow terminally ill people to end their
own lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dundee fail to reach the top</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028340</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dundee 1, Dumbarton 1
JIM Duffy's Dundee threw away a golden opportunity to grab leadership of the
first division when they were held to a draw by strugglers Dumbarton at Dens
Park last night.
The visitors, mauled by city neighbours Dundee United by 8-0 at Tannadice Park
last weekend, must have gone in to last night's contest with some trepidation.
But, clearly hyped up for the occasion by manager Jim Fallon, the Sons battled
their way to a worthy point.
With newcomer Ken Meechan in goal for the first time, the Dumbarton defence
looked solid as Dundee found little comfort in a monotonous series of attacking
movements.
Time and again the Dark Blues appeared to carve their way through on goal, only
to be denied by a challenge or clearance.
The home men's biggest problem became frustration, and it showed even when they
were ahead in the latter stages of the game.
Having battered their heads off the Dumbarton defensive wall for much of the
night, Jim Duffy's hosts finally broke through in 65 minutes, Paul Tosh netting
his seventh goal of the season with a powerful left-foot volley from a cross by
substitute Roy McBain.
That looked enough to assure the points which would have seen Dundee leapfrog
into pole position in the promotion chase, but the battling visitors had other
thoughts on the matter.
And as Dundee attempted to add to their lead instead of sitting on it, they
were hit by Dumbarton's last throw of the dice.
Experienced Chic Charnley sent in a deceptive cross from the right and Steve
Dallas found himself surprisingly unchallenged inside the six-yard box to
direct a perfect header home for the equaliser.
In the end Dundee had only themselves to blame for their disappointment.
Territorially they had every advantage, only to fail in front of goal.
