<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blast at Duma  raises fear  for polls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TIMOTHY HERITAGE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MYSTERIOUS explosion ripped through the office of       an ultra-nationalist
MP in Russia's Parliament building today, heightening fears of violence
disrupting an election less than two weeks away.
Nikolai Lysenko was not in his seventh-floor office at the time of the blast.
However an aide said it started a fire and blew out the office door and window,
sending shards of glass crashing to the pavement below.
No-one was hurt but defence and security officials in the State Duma said they
feared violence could mar the election to the lower chamber on December 17.
``Terrorist attacks will go on until the armed bands led by (Chechen rebel
leaders) Dzhokhar Dudayev and Shamil Basayev are wiped out. We also must be
prepared for such acts,'' said Viktor Ilyukhin, head of the Duma's security
committee.
Fears have mounted since rebels seeking independence for Chechnya turned to
guerrilla warfare. At least 12 people were killed in a car bomb blast yesterday.
Lysenko, 34-year-old leader of the right-wing National Republican Party which
is running in the election, had been in the corridor at the time.
He is an outspoken supporter of military action to smash Chechnya's
four-year-old independence drive.
Four MPs have been killed since the last election in 1993. The latest, Sergei
Markidonov, was shot dead during a campaign trip last month.
Security at the Duma is tight. Some MPs, wary of mafia-style gangs, carry guns
to protect themselves, but are obliged to leave them at the entrance.
In another violent incident today, apparently unconnected with politics, three
children were killed and three were hurt when a man took them hostage at a
kindergarten in the North Ossetia region, which borders Chechnya.
The 30-year-old attacker let off two grenades after seizing 16 children aged
four and five in the city of Vladikavkaz. The attacker, two policemen, and
three school staff were also hurt.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Why was jewellery on the plane?'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028342</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE theft of the Duchess of York's jewellery highlighted the chasm between the
wealthy and the poor in British society, a Labour MP said yesterday.
Mr Eddie Loyden, MP for Liverpool Garston, said: ``What the hell was she doing
flying around on this plane with jewellery of this value anyway?
``It highlights the divisions between obscene wealth and dire poverty in a
country that is supposed to be at ease with itself.
``I would like to see the royal family tip all their baubles into a large
container and flog them off and give the proceeds to people who are in
desperate need. They should let the palaces go with the jewellery. They would
fetch a few bob too.''
Mr Paul Flynn, Labour MP for Newport West, said: ``The value of this jewellery
would keep someone in income support for 140 years.
``This just illustrates the inequalities in our society.''
Mr Flynn said he planned to drum home the point in a Commons debate on benefit
changes.
His Labour colleague for Newport East, Mr Roy Hughes, said: ``It seems a bit
irregular to carry such valuable jewellery around. Her ladyship seems to be
accident-prone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
