<DOCNO>GH951206-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seven drown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRENOBLE: The death toll from a school nature trip in the French Alps that went
tragically wrong rose to seven yesterday after the bodies of four children were
discovered in the river Drac. A teacher and two children had been killed when
the river suddenly flooded on Monday.
Mafia dragnet
MADRID: Police in Spain were yesterday holding 25 people after a massive
round-up of Mafia suspects in a joint operation with Italian police. Another 79
arrests were made in Italy. Among those held in Spain in Operation Goya was the
alleged head of one of the notorious Camorra families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forest stand tall against French</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOTTINGHAM Forest kept British interest in European football alive last night
with a goalless draw at Lyon in France to go through on a 1-0 aggregate.
Frank Clark's side displayed great resilience to leave another French team
feeling frustrated, after having removed Auxerre from the competition in a
previous round.
The English side's defenders worked overtime in front of keeper Mark Crossley,
with Colin Cooper at the centre of the back four the pick.
Lyon became desperate as the match progressed and keeper Pascale Olmeta was
booked for lunging at Forest's Jason Lee, before the French team's Florian
Maurice was sent off three minutes from the end for violent conduct. He stuck
out an elbow towards Cooper's face in a gesture of almost total despair, and
Dutch referee Mario Van Der Ende pointed him towards the dressing rooms.
Lyon continued to huff and puff for the remainig time but Forest stood firm,
and their players hugged each other when the final whistle sounded.
In the all-Spanish tie, Jose Maria Bakero opened the scoring just after the
hour mark for Barcelona in the Nou Camp against Sevilla.  And then the away
side's chances were dented when Jose Miguel Prieto was sent off after 67
minutes.
Gica Popescu scored for Barcelona in 80 minutes, Gabriel Moya pulled a goal
back a minute later, but Roger Garcia put the tie out of Sevilla's reach when
he made it 3-1, 4-2 on aggregate.
Francesco Totti brought the home crowd to their feet after 23 minutes when he
gave Roma the lead against Denmark's Brondby. Then midway through the second
half, Abel Baldo added a second for the home side.
Peter Moeller scored for Brondby with six minutes remaining, but in the final
minute, Amedeo Carboni added a third on the night for Roma, who won the tie 4-3
on aggregate.
Werder Bremen had high hopes of reaching the next round at the expense of PSV
Eindhoven, but their dreams and those of most of the 25,000 crowd came to
nothing when the Dutch side came away with a 0-0 draw, winning the tie 2-1 on
aggregate.
In Lisbon, two goals from Juergen Klinsmann helped Bayern Munich to a 7-2
aggregate success against Benfica.
Tonight, Real Betis hope to overcome a 2-0 deficit against Bordeaux, while
tomorrow AC Milan aim to become the fifth former European Cup champions through
to the last eight when they defend a 2-0 lead at Sparta Prague, the same day
Lens play Slavia Prague.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
