<DOCNO>GH951206-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forger used sewing machine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN was persuaded by her brother to help forge bank notes and use a sewing
machine to perforate fake telephone stamps, Glasgow Sheriff Court was told
yesterday.
Machinist Alexandrina Cusworth, 55, worked for hours to put the perforations in
sheets of forged British Telecom #2 stamps, worth #72,000.
The court was told she had been asked to do it by her brother William Smith, a
lifer on licence who went missing after Cusworth's arrest.
Cusworth, a first offender, admitted that while acting with other persons, she
made a quantity of counterfeit banknotes, had them in her control, and
conspired with unknown persons to commit fraud with forged telephone stamps.
Mr Ian Bradley, prosecuting, revealed that when police raided Cusworth's home
at Burnett Road, Barlanark, they also found crudely forged Royal Bank of
Scotland #20 notes.
If they had been successfully passed as genuine, they would have netted
#68,000. Cusworth's job was to print the identifying numbers on them with a
commercial number stamper.
Mr Bradley told the court that while the notes were of poor quality, the #2
telephone stamps were so good that BT withdrew all the stamps and designed new
ones.
He told the court: ``Mrs Cusworth was the labour intensive link in the chain,
rather than disseminator of notes.''
He said her brother played a significant part in the operation and added: ``The
sewing machine was not the common thread. Mrs Cusworth's brother was.''
Defending advocate, Mrs Ruth Anderson, said family loyalty and stupidity had
brought Cusworth, who had not been in trouble before, to court.
Sheriff Daphne Robertson called for a social inquiry report and continued
Cusworth's bail until December 27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greeks call for new leader</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028346</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHENS: Greek politicians have called for Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou,
who has been fighting for his life in hospital for 15 days, to be replaced. The
latest medical bulletin said Papandreou's condition had not changed.
The country has been in political limbo since the 76-year-old leader developed
lung and kidney failure. Plans over his succession are not known and there is
concern over divisions in his ruling socialist party, Pasok.
Nephew flees
MADRID: A man claiming to be a nephew of executed Nigerian human rights
activist Ken Saro-Wiwa is seeking political asylum in Spain. The man, named
only as Victor, had arrived in Valencia as a stowaway after fleeing Nigeria
following a warning of imminent arrest by its military rulers, radio reported.
Police, however, said they had no such name on their list of asylum seekers.
Lava threat
MIAMI: A growing dome of lava in Montserrat's rumbling volcano threatens to
send rock slides and lava flows down the mountain's eastern flank, the governor
of the Caribbean island said. About 4000 residents of the British colony
remained out of their homes on the south end as a result of the alert.
Pride of Gurkhas
HONG KONG: From today, for the first time in their 180-year history, the
Gurkhas will be led by one of their own - a Nepali officer. Lt-Col Bijaykumar
Rawat, who has served the crack battalion in a variety of posts since 1972,
takes over as commanding officer of the 1st Battalion the Royal Gurkha Rifles
in Hong Kong.
House torn down
ST CATHERINES: Canadian volunteers have demolished the house where convicted
murderer Paul Bernardo tortured and killed two teenage schoolgirls in 1992 and
1993. The mother of 14-year-old victim Leslie Mahaffy looked on as the
property, which had been badly vandalised, was reduced to rubble.
Tomato boon
WASHINGTON: Men who eat at least 10 servings a week of tomato-rich foods such
as pizza and spaghetti sauce are up to 45% less likely to develop prostate
cancer, researchers claim. The Harvard University team conducted a nine-year
study of the eating habits of 47,000 men.
Prosit.......
BERLIN: Germans outdrank the rest of the world last year, with the average
citizen consuming 139.6 litres of beer, researchers say. Germans drank the
equivalent of 11.4 litres of pure alcohol in 1994, the German Addiction Centre
said.
</TEXT>
