<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Son and daughter tell of prostitution, sex abuse, and torture at 25 Cromwell Street Gruesome life with the Wests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAMILY life inside the Cromwell Street home of serial killers Fred and Rosemary
West was a chilling round of beatings, prostitution, sex abuse, bugged
bedrooms, and torture, according to two of the couple's children.
In calm, matter-of-fact voices, Stephen and Mae West describe their grotesque
childhoods in an interview to be broadcast on BBC television tonight.
Stephen West, 21, says his father came close to giving himself up to police
during his killing spree. He also says that, as early as 1992, Fred West
admitted to him that he had committed crimes ``worse than you can imagine'' -
and that he claimed he could not stop himself killing.
Both the West children say that if someone in authority had asked them the
right questions, their nightmare could have been ended years before.
In the programme, Inside Story, to be broadcast on BBC1 at 10pm, they say they
cannot believe their mother was guilty of the 10 murders of which she was
convicted. Ms West said her mother would not let her family visit her in prison.
They say that they had little idea of what life was like in ordinary families
and so had no way of realising how abnormal was the Wests' behaviour.
Ms West, 23, says: ``We had nothing to compare it against because we were never
really allowed to go to other friends' houses or to stay over with anybody.
``We obviously did see TV and the way people live but we envied them, we wanted
our lives to be like that.''
The two say 25 Cromwell Street was dominated by sex, with a constant stream of
men going to Rosemary West's bedroom, she flaunting herself naked in front of
visitors, and West making sexual demands on his daughters as they grew older.
Mr West remembers visiting West in a Birmingham bail hostel in 1992, when his
father was on remand on sex charges: ``He started saying that he had been
covering up stuff from all of us. He said that his life began when we went to
sleep at night.
``I asked him what he meant but he wouldn't elaborate. He said it had been
going on for years and went back to when he was in Scotland.
``He said it was a worse crime than anyone could imagine and the police would
find out soon and he would never leave prison again.''
Although Stephen and Mae Westrealised something was wrong in the Cromwell
Street household, they say that it was only after their father admitted to
killing their elder sister Heather that the full horror hit home.
Ms West says: ``I was shocked, because it could have easily been me and I
started to hate Dad from then.''
Mr West adds: ``I just couldn't believe it. I felt like someone had hit me with
a hammer and I just slid down the wall and cried.''
He was appalled to learn that a hole he had helped his father dig in the garden
had become his sister's grave.
As far back as they could remember, life in the West household revolved around
sex.
The children were shown blue movies and pornographic pictures and encouraged to
have sex as early as possible.
Mr West says: ``Dad wanted mum to be with other men and women. Dad was quite
happy for her to do it as long as she gained no enjoyment from it. If she
seemed to enjoy it, they would have a massive argument.
``He would be very jealous that she was with someone else, although he made her
do it.''
Ms West says: ``Dad used to say a father should break his daughters in and the
first-born child of a daughter should be her father's. From 11 or 12, he used
to touch us all the time. If we pushed him away, he would get angry or say we
were lesbians.''
Mr West said his father even offered him sex with his mother.
``Dad always said when you are 16 you are going to sleep with your mum and she
will teach you how you should treat a woman and how sex should be,'' he said.
The children were beaten regularly, especially by Rose, said Mr West.
He remembered one occasion when he was called home from school, forced to
strip, tied up and beaten for almost an hour with a buckle end of a belt,
because his mother thought he had stolen some pornographic magazines.
He was sent back to school with blood seeping through his shirt, he said.
The children were always dressed in shabby clothes - and ridiculed for it by
their schoolfriends.
However, Mr West remembers: ``We felt a lot happier at school, where we felt
that we were safe - even though people were taking the mickey out of us, it was
better than home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UVF man in `web of intrigue'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028348</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOYALIST peace politician Lindsay Robb was the ``spider at the centre of a web
of intrigue'', it was claimed yesterday.
In his jury speech at the Ulster Volunteer Force gun-running conspiracy trial,
Mr Ian Bonomy QC, prosecuting, spoke of Mr Robb's peace process meetings with
Government Minister Michael Ancram at Stormont this year.
``On the face of it, he was involved in political moves towards the peace
process while he was prepared to be a participant in an enterprise to secure
weapons whose ultimate destination was Northern Ireland,'' said Mr Bonomy.
Mr Robb, 28, of Lurgan, Northern Ireland, is accused of conspiring with five
other men to further the cause of the outlawed UVF by acquiring weapons
intending to endanger life in the UK and Republic of Ireland.
The five other accused, who also deny the charges, are John Johnston, 49, of
Laurieston, Airdrie; Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool; William McArthur, 42, of
Bonnybridge; David White, 29, of Airdrie; and Alexander Davidson, 23, of Lurgan.
Mr Robb's defence counsel Donald Findlay QC will address the jury at Glasgow's
High Court today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meanest of thefts as Jesus is kidnapped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF the three wise men know anything, they are remaining remarkably stoney-faced
about the whole affair. Right before their very eyes, someone stole the baby
Jesus.
Glasgow, which for decades has been trying to shrug off its No Mean City tag,
found itself at the centre of one of the meanest thefts of the Christmas
period. The life-size sculpture of the Child in the manger was stolen on Monday
night from the nativity scene erected by the city's council in George Square.
All that was left was his bed of straw. Mary and Joseph, the wise men,
shepherds, assorted animals, and an angel continue to look mutely upon the
scene.
It is not being treated as an opportunist prank, as the glass-encased scene is
kept locked and the thief must have used some type of heavy-duty wire or bolt
cutters to cut the lock.
Tapes from security cameras trained on the square will be checked to see if the
theft was recorded.
Council leader Pat Lally said: ``I appeal to those responsible to return him to
us so that all people can look upon our nativity scene and remember the true
message of Christmas.''
The figures in the group, commissioned in 1988, cost #16,000. They were
originally made in clay and then cast in bronze-effect glass fibre. The thief
may have thought it was valuable bronze but would have realised the mistake
when it was picked up.
Or perhaps a fundamentalist Christian wanted to save Jesus from the crass
commercialism of the Son of God's birth.
Either way, the police have been called in. It is not known whether they are
looking for a man called Herod.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police drop pictures case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NO action is to be taken against ITN newsreader Julia Somerville and her
architect boyfriend Jeremy Dixon over family snapshots, police said last night.
Mother-of-two Miss Somerville, 48, who strenuously denied any wrongdoing,
expressed relief that the investigation was over after a statement from
Scotland Yard.
She and Mr Dixon, 56, were arrested on November 2 after he collected
photographs of her seven-year-old daughter in the bath from Boots the Chemist.
Miss Somerville said last night: ``There has been a deplorable invasion of my
privacy and that of my family.
``However, I have received tremendous support from my friends, colleagues, and
from the public and I would like to express my thanks for that.''
A Boots technician reported the couple after seeing the photographs.
Miss Somerville, who fought a battle against cancer, and Mr Dixon were
questioned separately by police before being released on bail.
She said at the time: ``I am horrified that a wholly innocent family occasion
has been completely misconstrued.''
Scotland Yard said it was decided that, on the advice of the Crown Prosecution
Service, no action would be taken.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firms' role for Union</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Industry Minister George Kynoch yesterday called on business leaders
to speak up for the Union.
Scotland was showing faster growth in manufacturing output than the UK as a
whole but Mr Kynoch warned that a tax-raising Scottish Parliament would
``threaten these successes''.
His plea also followed publication of Scottish exports reaching record levels,
up 23.6% to #14,300m in 1994.
It also coincided with recent surveys which claim up to 15 leading companies
would ``quit Scotland'' if a Scottish Parliament with tax-raising powers was
created - and Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth's claim that devolution could
mean independence by 2002.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No sign of end to `alarming' decline in lamb consumption</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VICTOR ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAMB still has a lot of catching up to do to regain its share of the home
market and build its overseas demand, officials of both the Ministry of
Agriculture and the European Commission agreed yesterday.
Its saving grace is its ability to retain a working population in difficult
areas, but if demand is not boosted even this may test the European farm
budget.
Roelof Benninck, head of the commission's beef and sheepmeat section in
Brussels, said: ``The relatively comfortable arrangement of the premium making
up income loss in the sector will ensure reasonable returns for producers,
although falling prices would put the community budget under strain.''
The introduction of quotas had slightly reduced and stabilised production at
around 1.16 million tonnes a year. But up until their introduction subsidies
had been running at 1800 million ecu a year, which was seen as ``rather
large'', he said. In the meantime, he reminded, delegates to the annual Agra
Europe meat conference in London, consumption had declined not just in line
with the fall in production but also in response to lower imports, particularly
from Eastern Europe, where sheep numbers had fallen.
He added: ``The decline in consumption in the UK, however, is alarming given
its important position in the sector.''
Jean Pierre Garnier, the UK Ministry of Agriculture's meat and livestock
adviser, had an equally tough message for British producers. Home consumption
was showing no signs of recovery following a drop of nearly 9% last year in
spite of heavy Meat and Livestock Commission promotion.
``Their task is difficult. The over 65-year olds are too large a part of lamb
consumers in Britain. The cuts for stewing and the shoulder have lost one third
of their sales in five years, with the only increase attributed to steaks and
marinated meats for barbecues.
``This would show that lamb sales recovery in the UK will also depend on the
ability of lamb to convert to further processed products - admittedly a
difficult task.''
The marketing of sheep meat was also unique in that it was the only meat to
have shown price increases in real terms in Europe over the past 30 years.
European consumers were also showing a stronger price resistance than was the
case for other meats, although this was being overcome by special promotions.
``I would, therefore, issue this warning. In order for lamb sales to progress
in Europe, they need reasonable prices in relation to other main meal items
that the consumer can afford.
``If lamb was to price itself out of the reach of mainstream consumers, a
decline similar to the decline of the veal market in Europe would be
unavoidable.''
Mr Benninck pointed out that beef also needed to remain sensitive to price.
Plotting prices against demand curves had shown a decline in demand for beef
once its wholesale price rose to more than double the pig meat price.
He also revealed a new veterinary report on the welfare of veal production
would be issued shortly with recommendations on diet and housing which would
become the basis of European law.
The resulting later maturing animals would add an esti-  mated 500,000 tonnes a
year to European meat production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#250,000 for a Landseer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PAINTING which once graced the walls of Beaufort Castle, the Highland home of
the Masters of Lovat, has raised more than #250,000 at an auction sale at
Christie's in New York.
The Deer Pass is a seven-foot wide masterpiece painted in 1852 by Monarch of
the Glen artist Sir Edwin Landseer, who is renowned for his dramatic images of
the Highlands.
It was bought by a private American collector for #257,097 ($398,000), twice
its expected price.
The cash will come as a welcome boost to Lovat Estates, which put it on the
market.
It follows a series of personal tragedies over the last few years and crippling
debts of #7.4m which have forced the Lovat Fraser family to embark on a
large-scale clear-out, which included the sale of the historic castle where its
ancestors had lived since the fourteenth century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McGraw again in hospital</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORTON manager Allan McGraw was ``stable'' in hospital last night after having
suffered a heart attack on Monday. Club chairman John Wilson said that McGraw
was comfortable after being rushed to the infirmary for the second time inside
a fortnight.
McGraw was taken from the dugout at Dunfermline 10 days ago complaining of
chest pains but, although a heart attack was feared, the Cappielow manager
returned home after tests appeared to indicate that a stomach ulcer was the
problem.
Wilson said that everybody at Cappielow was hoping to see him make a quick and
full recovery. ``I had pleaded with him to take a break after the last fright
but what can you do with someone like Allan. He loves his job. He is synonymous
with Morton and I had to accept that he just can't keep away.''
News of his illness comes just as the stress and demands on current managers is
to be discussed today by the Managers and Coaches' Association chairman, Alex
Smith, and the Players' Union secretary, Tony Higgins.
``That is one of the items we want to talk about,'' said Higgins, ``and Allan's
illness further highlights the need to see if we can develop a management
course that would include ways of coping with the stress.
``More players are going straight from the dressing room into coaching and
management, and we feel that there should be a way of helping prepare them for
every aspect of the change.''
The managers' association has had a meeting with Rinus Michels, the former
Dutch coach, who is a consultant on the Review Commission led by Ernie Walker,
and plan to see him again.
Higgins and Smith also will spend time discussing the increasing involvement in
field offences of the procurator-fiscal in the Strathclyde region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Teams bag Munro cash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO hundred teams who bagged all 277 Scottish Munros, on one of the hottest
days of this year, raised #25,000 in sponsorship as part of the University of
Aberdeen's Quincentenary celebrations.
Last night, the money was donated to the Mountain Rescue Committee of Scotland
for training and equipment, and to the University Sports Development Fund for a
new fitness room and to start a sports bursary scheme.
The Munro Team Challenge was taken up by 1500 graduates - past and present -
staff, and students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nantes are now hoping to avoid a Greek tragedy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028356</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NANTES must overcome injury and suspension problems tonight to fulfil their
ambition of reaching the European Cup quarter-finals for the first time.
The French side, seeking one of the three remaining places in the last eight on
the final night of Champions' League games, have set trainer Jean-Claude
Suaudeau a selection poser, with two players banned and three injured.
Nantes are preparing for a home clash against Group A leaders Panathinaikos in
which they need a draw to guarantee a quarter-final place, and although they
will anxiously await the result of Jean-Michel Ferri's fitness test on a thigh
strain, they will look to the midfield skills of Chadian Japhet N'Doram and the
blossoming form of Reynald Pedros to see them through.
Panathinaikos have injury problems, too, with their main strike pair, Polish
internationalist Kryzstof Warzycha and George Donis, struggling with leg
injuries.
The Greek team also are without injured defender Thanasis Kolitsidakis and
suspended midfield player George Georgiadis, but their Argentine coach, Juan
Ramon Rocha, said. ``I hope their replacements will do their job. Our target is
victory because we want first position in our group.''
If Nantes lose, third-placed Porto can qualify for the last eight from Group A
by beating Aalborg in Denmark.
Porto coach and former England manager Bobby Robson will be missing defender
Jorge Costa, who is suspended.
``It's going to be a very tough task but we're going to play to win against
Aalborg,'' Robson said. ``There could be a surprise in Nantes. Panathinaikos
might win. I'm sure the Greeks want to stay top of the group to avoid Spartak
Moscow.''
Aalborg are hit by injury or suspension to seven players but trainer Sepp
Piontek hopes the energy and talent among his young replacements and the fact
Porto play in a Scandinavian winter could give his side an advantage.
With Spartak Moscow having secured a quarter-final spot from Group B, Poland's
Legia Warsaw and Norway's Rosenborg are battling for the second qualifying
place.
Second-placed Legia are at home against Spartak, while Rosenborg's task is less
daunting - a game with Blackburn Rovers, whose poor form has produced just one
point and the same amount of goals.
Rovers manager Ray Harford is facing a selection crisis, with eight first-team
men set to miss the tie. Paul Warhurst could be pressed into defensive duties,
while Kevin Gallagher, bedevilled by injuries in recent times, is also in the
frame.
``It's nice to see him getting close to fitness for the lad has had a torrid
time,'' said Harford. Gallagher has not played in the top team since the
opening day of the season.
Ajax have qualified from Group D but aim to stretch their unbeaten run in the
European Cup to 17 matches in their final game at home to Ferencvaros.
The Dutch side look certain to be joined in the last eight by Real Madrid, who
can only go out if they lose to Grasshopper in Zurich, while Ajax are beaten by
the Hungarians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato blesses peace force</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATO ministers tonight gave their blessing to a 60,000-strong force to put the
lid on Bosnia's terrible war and end what was described as ``one of the darkest
chapters of modern European history''.
As the ministers talked in Brussels, advance units moved into Bosnia to prepare
the ground.
In the first joint session of Nato foreign and defence ministers since 1979,
the Alliance gave provisional approval for the biggest operation in its history
and the first outside members' territory.
Final approval will come only after the peace deal agreed in Dayton, Ohio, last
month          is formally signed in Paris          on December 14, and the
Security Council transfers its responsibility for Bosnia to Nato.
Earlier, acting Nato Secretary-General Sergio Balanzino said the mission was
aimed at ending ``one of the darkest chapters of modern European history''.
``What has happened has happened. Our job is to make sure that it does not
happen again, that the peace which has been agreed is now implemented,'' he
said.
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told reporters he hoped the ministers'
approval of the mission would send a clear signal to the US Congress to follow
suit.
The Nato decision came as advance units were arriving in Bosnia to set up bases
for the heavily-armed troops who will start flooding in after the formal
signing of the Dayton treaty.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faith in future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #4m initiative was launched yesterday to build an international inter-faith
centre in Britain. It is hoped the centre will be built at Westminster College,
Oxford.
Woman accused
A home help yesterday denied attempting to murder an elderly cancer patient
while she was being treated in hospital. Ms Rachel Heath, 31, of Woolston
Hampshire, also pleaded not guilty to administering diamorphine to 71-year-old
Kathleen Corfield, of Wilton Road, Shirley, Southampton. Mrs Corfield
eventually died in hospital.
Bad break
A #2.2m fishery harbour at Brevig in Broad Bay in Lewis - opened only three
weeks ago by the Western Isles Islands Council - will need a #360,000
breakwater so that it can be used safely by fishing boats.
Travel trouble
TWO injured French fishermen landed in Shetland yesterday from the Dieppe
trawler Snekkar will have to stay in the islands until tomorrow because of
transport problems in France caused by strikes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man on wife murder charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975028359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Massey, 42, appeared in private at Glasgow Sheriff Court yesterday
accused of stabbing and murdering his wife, Jean, 38, at their home in Leven
Street, Pollokshields, Glasgow, on Monday.
Solicitor James Cassels made no plea or declaration on behalf of Mr Massey, who
was remanded in custody for further inquiries.
Councillor quits
INDEPENDENT Councillor Bill Kemp, 48, of Old Kilpatrick, is quitting the
Labour-controlled West Dunbartonshire Council, because he is disenchanted with
the way the shadow council is operating. The council takes over Dumbarton and
Clydebank on April 1.
Centre award
AN #8m regeneration of Kilmarnock town centre has earned it a top planning
award. The Ayrshire town is the only Scots winner in the 1995 Annual Awards for
Planning Achievements.
Youth detained
A YOUTH was detained for two-and-a-half years after he admitted at Glasgow
Sheriff Court yesterday that he attacked an insurance man with a sickle and
stole his briefcase. Mark Harrison, 17, of Gilbertfield Street, Ruchazie,
Glasgow, also admitted stealing two bikes and selling them.
Ashdown remand
A MAN was further remanded in custody by magistrates yesterday in connection
with an alleged attack on Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown. Mr Christopher
Mason, 51, of Yeovil, Somerset, was accused of possessing an offensive weapon
and with threatening violence. He was refused bail.
Masonic first
A BBC Wales camera crew has become the first to gain official access to a
Masonic Lodge. Footage of a ritual ceremony is to be included in a 40-minute
film about life in Cardiff, by award winning Polish documentary film-maker
Jacek Petrycki, on BBC Wales on 2 this Saturday during Capital Night, a special
evening of programmes celebrating the 40th anniversary of Cardiff being granted
capital city status.
Armed raid
DETECTIVES are investigating a robbery at the Spar shop in the Borders village
of Coldingham in which a young man wearing a balaclava and brandishing a knife
inflicted a hand wound on shop assistant Fran Evans before escaping with #150
from the till.
Group leader
A TEAM from the Edinburgh Telemedicine group at Edinburgh University has been
chosen to lead a #2.5m European Commission-funded study which will evaluate the
setting up of a worldwide telemedicine network.
Budget boost
ALL 29 new unitary councils, along with Strathclyde police and fire boards,
have been allocated a total of #4.155m to spend on computer systems and
accommodation needs.
Evans above!
THE Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George Carey, has agreed to a Christmas Day
quizzing from risque Radio 1 DJ Chris Evans. He tops an all-star bill including
Cher, Mick Hucknall, and Shirley Bassey.
Youth detained
A 19-year-old youth who attempted to rob a sub-post office in Berwick has been
sent to a young offenders' institution for four years. Matthew Drummond, of
Scremerston, near Berwick, admitted the offence when he appeared at Newcastle
Crown Court.
</TEXT>
