<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pantomime troubles take on farcical proportions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a farce in the best Whitehall tradition. Unfortunately, it is all
happening backstage for the Borderline Theatre Company, and threatens its plan
to lift the curtain tomorrow on its Christmas pantomime.
Three days after Borderline, one of Scotland's best-known theatre companies,
made its award-winning artistic director Jon Murtagh redundant, it has emerged
that two of the cast's leading actors have left the production of Babes in the
Wood in sympathy with Mr Murtagh.
Borderline had planned to raise the curtain at the Magnum Theatre in Irvine on
Monday, but had to reschedule the opening for tomorrow after Mr Murtagh, who
had written, was directing, and was due to star in the panto, understandably
withdrew his services after being made redundant, forcing the company into
rewriting the panto and looking for a new dame.
Yesterday, however, its backstage problems were compounded when actors Greg
Hemphill and Joey Cooper left the production in protest at Mr Murtagh's
treatment.
Mr Drew McFarlane, Scottish organiser of the actors' union, Equity, said he
would be taking Mr Murtagh's case to an industrial tribunal.
He said: ``This whole situation has been handled appallingly by the company. We
now understand Borderline is worsening the scenario by threatening legal action
against our members, but we will defend them vigorously.''
Mr McFarlane said the backstage machinations had not been without their
farcical side. All the cast had been handed little homilies in their wage
packets. ``One said `Treat yourself and others with dignity and respect.'
Another said, appropriately, `involve others in making decisions that affect
them'.''
Mr McFarlane said they were a joke. ``Did they involve Mr Murtagh? If they had,
we might not have gone down this road. Two weeks ago, Mr Murtagh was given a
new contract to sign, yet 14 days later he had been made redundant.''
Last night, Mr Murtagh said: ``In 35 years as an actor and director, I have
never missed a show, but the action by Borderline threatens that record.
``This was a show written especially for the people of Ayrshire and any
postponement or reduction in quality of it would be a travesty and, even at
this late stage, I would hope Borderline would communicate with my union
representatives in order to salvage this deeply distressing situation.''
A company spokesman said last night that the two actors had left the pantomime
after breaking their contracts. "The show will go on,'' she added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pies off the menu</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028361</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FETTES College has taken beef pies, sausages, and patties off the menu because
of concern about the threat of BSE transmission to humans.
Whole beef will continue to be served in the refectory but alternative dishes
will also be available at the #12,000-a-year school which has nearly 500 pupils.
Bursar Cameron Thaw said: ``Teachers should be aware of the policy in order to
allay parents' or pupils' fears in view of the increased media coverage of the
BSE scare.
``The policy will be reviewed once the scare is over or further guidelines are
issued by official sources.''
Schools across England and Wales have responded to requests from anxious
parents and have asked their local authority catering organisations to supply
alternatives, such as chicken and pork.
Last night, Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg stressed there was no scientific
evidence that humans were at risk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French move boosts Portillo</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels, Tuesday
DEFENCE Secretary Michael Portillo's battle to prevent the EU from taking on
the role of Europe's protector received a massive boost today with France's
decision to end a 30-year cold-shoulder of Nato's military wing.
As he issued an call to Europe to ``get its act together'', France announced it
would take up its seat on the military committee and participate in defence
ministers' meetings.
The news boosted Mr Portillo and the British Government in their battle to
retain Nato as the bedrock of European security.
The move was clear testimony that Nato was ``the only fully-effective
organisation capable of mounting large-scale military operations'', he said.
France, which pulled out of Nato's integrated military structure in 1966
because of differences over how the US-led Alliance was run, said it wanted to
play a bigger role.
Although the move stopped short of France rejoining the military structure, the
ministers welcomed it as a boost for Nato solidarity ahead of the Bosnia peace
mission.
In a speech to the 10-nation Western European Union Assembly in Paris, Mr
Portillo warned that defence could not be seen as a plaything in the game of
European construction and that words must be supported by action.
He underlined Britain's insistence that the Government would never hand over
command of British forces to Brussels.
His address, setting out a vision of European defence, followed the Tory
conference speech in which he made an attack on Brussels and a defence of
British sovereignty.
Britain, which takes over the presidency of the WEU for six months in January,
is determined to take forward the organisation as the defence arm of the EU.
Mr Portillo said today his vision was one of ``real European defence'' with a
strong Nato to guarantee ultimate security.
q.Nato Ministers today endorsed Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana as the
Alliance's ninth secretary. He replaces Belgian Willy Claes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man assaulted pregnant lover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN has been jailed for subjected his girlfriend to a sustained attack just
nine days before she gave birth to his son.
Alexander Barclay, 23, was jailed for 15 months at Edinburgh Sheriff Court
yesterday for the ``disgraceful'' incident.
Sheriff Charles Stoddart heard that Barclay battered his heavily-pregnant
live-in lover as she lay in bed just three days before last Christmas.
Barclay, of Crown Street, Edinburgh, admitted the assault. He came home from
the pub at 1am after a drinking spree and turned his anger on his girlfriend
when she told him to be quiet so that she could get some sleep.
Depute-fiscal Margaret Graham described how he grabbed his girlfriend from
behind, pulled her hair, put his hands round her neck, and punched her several
times.
He continued to hit her when she got out of bed and blows landed on her head
and arms as the attack went on from the bedroom to the living room.
The woman was hysterical, crying and screaming, but still Barclay attacked her.
A neighbour eventually called police but Barclay at first refused to let them
into the flat.
The officers got in when the woman asked for help, and they found her with a
swollen and bleeding face. She estimated her ordeal had lasted for 45 minutes.
She had also suffered a three-centimetre cut to the back of her head which was
stapled at hospital.
Fortunately there was no harm to the unborn boy who was delivered nine days
later.
Defence solicitor Brian Gilfedder said there was an argument and the woman hit
Barclay but that was no excuse.
Sheriff Stoddart pointed out that Barclay had four previous convictions for
assault and had previously been sentenced to both community service and
probation, as well as prison.
``This was a disgraceful assault,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quarry firm denies links with council</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR executive of a multinational quarry company, Mr John Leivers,
yesterday denied employing anyone who worked for Western Isles Islands Council
or who was a member of the council.
He spoke after reports of a row over the appointment of Mr Graham Edwards, a
former assistant director of administration who retired from the council a few
months ago, and who was appointed as a PR representative for Redland Aggregates
in the islands two weeks ago.
He was the official dealing with the council's case at the eight-month public
inquiry into Redland's planning application for a #70m coastal superquarry at
Lingerbay in Harris.
Yesterday, at the council's policy and resources committee, during a discussion
on the Nolan ``sleaze'' report, Councillor Roddy Murray referred to a newspaper
article which stated: ``The company admits that a number of other unnamed
people in the islands had been retained for `legal and planning advice'.''
Mr Murray asked that the chief executive, Mr Brian Stewart, should write to
Redland to find out who those unnamed people were.
Councillor George Lonie also moved that the chief executive inform the
Secretary of State of the appointment of Mr Edwards.
He agreed with Councillor Angus Graham, vice convener, that there should be a
code of conduct for officers of the council as well as members, and that that
issue too should be brought to the attention of the Secretary of State.
The vice-convener then referred to a question tabled for the full council
meeting by Councillor Alasdair Nicholson. This asked who had been paid a
retainer by Redland Aggregates from 1993 onwards while in employment or on duty
with the council and, secondly, what hospitality had been afforded by the
company either to council staff or council members.
Mr Graham said: ``There is a very serious allegation in these questions. For my
part, as someone who was closely involved with the planning application as
chairman of the development services committee, I take great exception to the
suggestion in these questions.
``Some members, I think, should put up or shut up.
``If we are putting up then it is a matter for the police.
``I find it quite scurrilous that such questions should be put. I am quite
positive that no officer or member of this council took any reward or any
hospitality from Redland.''
Before leaving Stornoway Airport after a two-day visit to the island, Mr
Leivers, director of lands and planning for Redland, said: ``It is not true
that we employ anyone involved with the council. I am not employing anyone who
works for the council or who represents the council.
``We have a right to employ legal people or surveyors on the island if we so
wish. As far as hospitality is concerned, I have been entertained by the
Western Isles Council for the past eight years.''
q.Redland yesterday published its ballast water management plan, which
maintained that one of the main environmental concerns about the proposed
superquarry had been answered.
The plan provides for ballast water exchanges to take place at sea in three
areas identified as environmentally acceptable. It specifies that the ballast
water tanks used at the port of origin should be different to those from which
water is discharged at the destination, and that ballast water shall not be
taken on board within 10 miles of land or from areas of recent algal blooms.
Mr Leivers said that the plan should allay fears of fishermen and others who
depended on a healthy marine environment for the livelihoods.
Mr Duncan MacInnes, secretary of the Western Isles Fishermen's Association,
said he had read the report and had not been persuaded. ``It is all very well
on paper but who is to say what is going to happen at sea in very bad weather
conditions. We are so dependent on shellfish in the islands and any poisoning
of the shellfish would be disastrous for us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rabin assassin charged as Israel ends 30-day period of mourning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jerusalem, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ISRAELI prosecutors today charged the man who has admitted shooting former
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin with his murder. Yigal Amir, 25, his brother, and
a friend are to be brought before Tel Aviv District Court tomorrow to hear the
charges against all three of them.
The two alleged accomplices face charges of conspiracy to murder and illegal
possession of weapons.
The formal charge sheet says that Yigal Amir decided some time after the
September 1993 Israel-PLO peace agreement to kill Rabin in a bid to prevent its
implementation.
Amir turned to his brother, Hagai, and a friend, Dror Adani, who agreed to join
the murder plot, it says.
The three initially considered blowing up Rabin's car or firing an anti-tank
rocket into his home, according to the charges.
In the end, Yigal Amir decided to kill Rabin with his 9mm Beretta pistol and
tried to approach him at three different public appearances this year,
prosecutors allege.
On January 22 Amir waited for Rabin at the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial in
Jerusalem, but the Prime Minister cancelled his planned appearance after Muslim
militants set off a suicide bomb earlier in the day.
In April and September Amir was again kept away from his planned target by
security guards.
On November 4 Amir told his brother Hagai that he would try to kill Rabin at a
peace rally in Tel Aviv, the charge sheet says.
Hagai tried to tell his brother not to do it, because heavy security around the
Prime Minister would mean his chances of getting out alive after firing the
shots would be slim.
Nevertheless Yigal went ahead with his plan. He loaded his Beretta with six
regular bullets and six hollow-point bullets that had been given to him by
Hagai, according to the court papers.
Yigal left his home in a Tel Aviv suburb, took a bus to the peace rally, and
walked to where Rabin's car was parked. He waited there for about 40 minutes
for the rally to end, the prosecution says.
As Rabin walked to his car, one of his bodyguards opened the door. Rabin was
about to get in when Amir walked up and shot him three times from close range,
according to the charges.
Meanwhile in Jerusalem Israeli leaders and Rabin's family returned to his grave
today for an emotional ceremony marking the end of the Jewish 30-day period of
mourning.
New Prime Minister Shimon Peres said: ``Yitzhak, you were murdered because you
were right. You were murdered because you won.'' He told the ceremony at
Jerusalem's Mount Herzl cemetery: ``The dawn of peace has broken. No longer can
anyone extinguish it.''
Rabin's widow Leah, his son, daughter, and granddaughter Noa stood weeping
under grey skies at the ceremony attended by politicians, senior army officers,
family, and friends.
Leah Rabin shook hands with Likud opposition leader Benjamin Netanyahu, who she
had earlier criticised as having contributed to an atmosphere of right-wing
hatred against her husband.
Other remembrance ceremonies were held in Israeli schools to honour Rabin at
the end of the Shloshim, or 30-day period, when relatives revisit the grave of
a loved one.
Rabin's grave has become a site of pilgrimage for tens of thousands of Israelis
since his murder.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Snow and cold threaten to disrupt Champions' League finale Now Rangers have the weather to beat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUB-ZERO temperatures and the threat of snowfalls could mean an extension of
Rangers' Champions' League campaign, with both of the final matches in Group C
surrounded by uncertainty. Because of high winds and snow, Juventus were unable
to land at Otopeni airport yesterday to prepare for their match against Steaua
Bucharest, and although Rangers made it safely into Dortmund, their game
against Borussia could be postponed.
A UEFA delegation will inspect the playing surface of Borussia Dortmund's
Westfalen Stadium at 10am today and the likelihood is that Rangers will be
asked to return next midweek and try again.
Juventus will attempt again to arrive in Romania this morning, if the Bucharest
airport reopens, but with a few feet of snow lying on Steaua's pitch it is
unlikely that game will be given the go-ahead tonight and UEFA could instruct
them to wait until next Wednesday.
However, with more severe weather expected this week it is difficult to
envisage an improvement even a week further on. Last night, with the
temperature of -7 and falling, and several inches of snowfall expected,
Rangers' players trained on the pitch and no-one appeared comfortable.
``The surface is taking a little stud, but if conditions worsen overnight I
wouldn't like to come back tomorrow night and risk the players,'' said manager
Walter Smith, whose fears were echoed by Borussia's coach Ottmar Hitzfeld. ``If
the pitch remains hard it will be difficult for the players,'' he said, ``but
we should not put them in any danger.''
The Westfalen does not have undersoil heating, as their domestic programme goes
into winter hibernation.
It is standard procedure for UEFA to have their Champions' League pitches
inspected before every game and the Republic of Ireland's Des Casey, who is the
UEFA delegate for this tie, and match referee Manuel Diaz Vega, of Spain, will
be charged with the responsibility of passing or rejecting the Westfalen this
morning.
Champions' League official Heinz Palme said last night: ``If it is found the
pitch is not regular, then the match will be postponed.''
The safety of players will be a priority, even though the German club have sold
most of their 34,937 tickets. Also, more than 30 buses and a couple of aircraft
are expected to have deposited a large number of Rangers supporters - 2500 is
the estimate - in Dortmund by today.
There is no doubt both sides want the game to be played but the signs were not
encouraging last night. Several Rangers players slithered on the frozen surface
as they went through training manoeuvres and the captain, Richard Gough, shook
his head when asked what he thought of the pitch. ``It's very hard, very
difficult,'' he said.
Palme also pointed out that even if the pitch could be cleared, it still might
not be possible to play the game for spectator considerations, because of
building work which is under way at the ground. One of the main stands is being
extended and has no roof over the existing seating area.
Hitzfeld had hoped to deploy Karl-Heinz Riedle up front with Heiko Herrlich,
but the latter might not be risked on a treacherous surface for his first match
for six months after knee surgery. Dortmund have Julio Cesar, Matthias Sammer,
Bodo Schmidt, and Stefan Reuter doubtful because of injury and illness, while
Jurgen Kohler and Lars Ricken are suspended.
But Hitzfeld says his team will be trying to win. ``We have to try to put on a
show, because the game will be shown all over Europe,'' he pointed out. ``We
have to impress and, besides, we have our honour to look after just the same as
Rangers.'' Honour and credibility certainly are important to the Scottish
champions.
In the end, Gough found a beginning. The Rangers captain, who had started to
relish the prospect of Champions' League football ever since the day last
season when the Ibrox club secured their seventh successive premier-division
championship, has had to wrestle with doubt and criticism about the true
strength of Rangers' capabilities.
Five Group C matches and not a single win - Rangers, in fact, have collected
only two points - but Gough has been able to come to terms with the trauma
which has been Rangers' lot in Europe this season.
He believes the experience of the current Champions' League series could have a
benefit, especially for the younger members of Rangers' squad. Gough feels all
of the players, if only to accommodate their own personal pride, should want
now to work harder to win another league title and try again to deal with the
game's elite.
Armed with greater experience the players should, therefore, be better equipped
to deal with genuine football as opposed to the bustle of the premier division.
``I have had setbacks in my career, but what you go on to achieve in football
depends a great deal on how much you learn from your experiences, whether they
be good or bad,'' he said on arrival in Germany yesterday.
``We did have a lot of problems because of injuries, but we found also that we
were not good enough this time.
``It is important for professional players to want always to measure themselves
against the very best and with the correct attitudes and enough good fortune,
which every team must have, we could do more next time.''
Gordan Petric is suspended for tonight's game, but Smith's only problem is
whether to use Craig Moore, Gary Bollan, or John Brown as cover for Petric if,
indeed, the manager wishes to persevere here with his three-man central
defensive system.
``I felt we did enough against Dortmund to have won the match at Ibrox,'' Gough
added, ``and we played reasonably well defensively against Steaua Bucharest in
Romania, even though we lost that match, but this last game should be regarded
as a learning process.''
Rangers' recent premier-division form has been impressive and Paul Gascoigne
has been looking more like the player Smith thought he was buying during the
close season. If the English internationalist, who has only threatened so far
in the Champions' League, can produced his best against Borussia, then anything
might be possible, although the belief that Rangers could end the campaign on a
high would be reinforced if Brian Laudrup treats everyone to his full
repertoire.
``He has had an awkward time because of an ankle injury, but I thought he
played his best stuff in the last half-hour of the match at Tynecastle last
Saturday, which might mean Brian is getting close to full match fitness,'' said
Smith, who added that he has no new injury problems. ``I would like to see a
similar performance to the one in the second half of the game against Borussia
at Ibrox.
``I think after the problems we have had, I am probably better placed now with
regard to team selection than at any time previously in the Champions' League.
We may have reached a point where the players are ready now to give a better
account of themselves in Europe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fees on way for Test refs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL referees in the Northern Hemisphere are on the brink of joining
their southern counterparts with match fees whenever they officiate in Test
matches, writes Derek Douglas.
South African referee Tappa Henning, who officiated at the Scotland v Western
Samoa game at Murrayfield last month, received, it is understood, a substantial
fee from the South African union. At a Five Nations' committee meeting next
week, Northern Hemisphere unions will be urged to fall into line.
Sums of #1000 a match for referees and #500 apiece for touchjudges are being
mooted in some quarters, but SRU International Board representative Alan Hosie,
who convenes the SRU referees' committee, said those figures were probably wide
of the mark.
If the new deal for officials goes through next week then the first Scottish
beneficiaries will be Jim Fleming, Ray Megson and Kenny McCartney, who were in
charge of the England match with South Africa at Twickenham last month. Any
payments sanctioned would be retrospective.
Yesterday Megson, who refereed the first of his nine major internationals in
1987, said: ``It has to happen. You can't put amateurs out on the pitch with
professionals and especially so when, nowadays, you have #20m worth of bums
sitting on seats.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder case without a body</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETECTIVES investigating a man's disappearance believe he has been murdered.
The body of Roderick Campbell has not been found but police have taken the
unusual step of reporting a 28-year-old Greenock man to the procurator-fiscal
in connection with his disappearance.
Mr Campbell, 21, of Gladsmuir Road, Hillington, Glasgow, disappeared 15 days
ago after a night out with friends.
He left them in Kelhead Drive, Penilee, telling them he was going home because
he was feeling unwell, and was not seen again.
A week later, police launched an appeal for help, saying they were ``becoming
increasingly concerned'' about Mr Campbell, who was 6ft 2in and slim. When last
seen, he was wearing a bomber jacket and jeans.
A few days ago, the search switched to the Greenock area after police at Govan
received information in connection with their search.
Last night, a Strathclyde Police spokesman said: ``We do not know the
whereabouts of Mr Campbell but, based on information we have received, we are
convinced he is dead.''
The investigation is now being headed by Greenock-based Detective Chief
Inspector John Sherry.
A spokesman for the Crown Office said: ``Although it is unusual for someone to
be reported to the fiscal in a case where there is no body, it is not
unprecedented. It has happened in the past and there have been convictions in
cases where the body has never been found.''
</TEXT>
