<HEADLINE>MPs have reservations about her ability to fulfil ambassadorial ambitions. Queen discusses role of princess with Major</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was no comment from Buckingham Palace officials last night on a meeting
between the Queen and John Major, at which the future role of the Princess of
Wales was discussed.
Senior palace aides met the princess last week for talks following her
controversial Panorama interview, in which she said she wanted to become a
roving ambassador for Britain.
The talks, held at the palace last Wednesday, were part of a continuing
dialogue which will involve consultations with other members of the royal
family and the Government.
The palace is keen to stress that the dialogue with Diana is amicable and
constructive.
However, some leading politicians have expressed growing concern about her
desire to be a roving ambassador, questioning her ambassadorial skills.
The agenda for Mr Major's ``routine'' weekly audience with the Queen last night
was confidential, but it was thought unlikely that the princess's future would
not be addressed.
The Prime Minister has come under renewed pressure from dissenting MPs,
believed to have supporters within the Cabinet, to limit the princess to a
charity role abroad.
No-one should expect a solution from a one-off meeting.
Talks with the princess will produce ideas and options which, when defined more
precisely, will have to be dove-tailed with the work of other royals and with
Government priorities in foreign policy.
But the indications are that, whatever her future commitments, the princess
will now develop her public role.
There will be those at the palace, however, eager to point out that she is not
the only royal ambassador. Indeed, it could be argued that all members of the
royal family are ambassadors for Britain.
Diana also expressed her desire on BBC1's Panorama to be a ``queen of hearts''
among ordinary people, to give affection and ``light in their dark tunnels''.
But no one member of the royal family - however aggrieved - can expect to
monopolise popularity, or the public's high esteem.
Such a claim would ignore the high standing and status of the Queen and the
Queen Mother, to name but two well-loved senior royals, who go about their
public business each day without fanfares.
q The princess's Panorama interview was the most watched television programme
this year, drawing nearly 23 million viewers, according to official figures
yesterday.
The hour-long special was also BBC TV's third-highest rated programme since
BARB ratings were introduced 14 years ago.
</TEXT>
