<HEADLINE>Blaze in former school</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 50 firefighters were early this morning still fighting a major blaze in
the old Queen's Park Secondary School in the south side of Glasgow.
Strathclyde Police said Prospecthill Road and Grange Road were closed to
traffic for several hours after the fire was reported at 6.50pm. Eight fire
engines and two other units with turntable ladders attended the blaze in the
building which is understood to be derelict.
The building ceased operating as a school in the early 1970s. Strathclyde
region used part of it as a teacher training centre until 1990. The Victoria
Infirmary, which is nearby, also used part until recently as a computer
training centre.
Strathclyde Fire Brigade said early this morning that the blaze was under
control. It is understood that one possible cause being considered is a dropped
light.
</TEXT>
