<DOCNO>GH951206-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Falkirk shops' #2.75m bill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL taxpayers could face a bill of nearly #50 a household next year to bail
out a troubled shopping centre in Falkirk.
The Callendar Square centre is still less than half full two years after
opening. Interest charges and running costs are likely to mean the equivalent
of almost #12 a household for Central region council taxpayers in the current
financial year.
Members of the region's development committee will be warned today that
attracting a major new tenant could cost more than #1.5m in ``sweeteners''.
Unless a deal is struck before April, the 57,000 householders in the area
covered by the new Falkirk unitary council could face a bill of more than
#2.75m - equivalent to #48 a household on the council tax.
Central region's problems with Callendar Square date from 1990 when the
Labour-controlled authority agreed to underwrite a #12m rescue of the
development after builders Rush and Tompkins went into receivership.
In 1993, with the centre still unfinished, the council was forced to raise its
underwriting to #13m.
In a confidential report to a meeting of the region's development and planning
committee today, development director Geoff Peart warns: ``The council will
have to consider further significant loan assistance if the letting position
doesn't improve to the extent necessary to attract bank funding.''
Councillors will be told they face a stark choice: Continue pouring large sums
into the centre or go for liquidation, which could involve coughing up the full
#13m guarantee.
Falkirk SNP leader David Alexander said last night: ``It's obvious the burden's
going to fall on Falkirk ratepayers. We're simply being handed a white
elephant.''
Mr Bill Dickson, head of corporate finance at Central region, said: ``The level
of retail space occupied can only improve if additional capital funds are made
available. It is in the interests of the regional council and the new Falkirk
Council to secure new tenancies.''
</TEXT>
