<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SRU call Sole to account as referee row escalates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS  Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAVID Sole is to provide the Scottish Rugby Union with a ``full and detailed''
written response to the charge of bringing the game into disrepute which
followed his criticism of a match referee whose performance he likened to
``tantamount to cheating''.
As the affair threatened to get out of hand with international referee Ray
Megson stating that he would not officiate at any further Edinburgh
Academicals' games until the matter had been resolved, Sole declared: ``I have
received a letter from the SRU seeking my comments and I will provide them with
a full and detailed response.''
Megson, who is acting in a personal capacity but who mirrors widespread anger
within the refereeing fraternity, has also called for the formation of a
referees' federation, divorced from the SRU, which would represent referees,
who, he believes, are grossly undervalued and mistreated.
Sole, who coaches Academicals' forwards, made his remarks after a string of
penalties awarded against his side by Kelso referee Colin Henderson led to an
injury-time defeat by Melrose and ultimate relegation.
The former Scotland captain had been summoned to Murrayfield to explain his
reported comments but was unable to attend because he was babysitting. A second
hearing had been proposed for December 14 but Sole cannot attend then either
and instead will provide a written response.
He said: ``Contrary to what many people seem to think, I am treating this
matter seriously and it probably would not be wise to comment further other
than to say that I will acquiesce with the union's request to provide them with
my account of what took place.''
Yesterday, Megson, an Edinburgh lawyer, said: ``Enough is enough. This was a
high-profile former player who basically accused a referee of cheating. Well,
this is a high-profile referee who is saying that this is unacceptable and that
the matter should have been dealt with before now.
``I'm acting here as an individual. This has nothing to do with the SRU. They
have done all they can. But if this is the stance that David Sole wants to take
and, apparently, with the backing of his club, then I am not going to referee
them in those circumstances,'' said Megson.
``You should see the absolute shit that is flung at referees these days. We are
constantly trying to recruit new referees. What do you think these kind of
comments do for that recruitment campaign?
``You can call me incompetent, you can say that Megson didn't have a
particularly good game, but you can't call me a cheat. I can tell you that if
it had been me and not Colin Henderson that was involved then we would be
talking about more than not refereeing Accies' games.''
SRU referees' convener Alan Hosie said: ``We are still awaiting David's
response to the committee so it would probably be best to say nothing. However,
I want to make it plain, too, that we will give Colin Henderson all the support
he would expect. We have told the Border Referees' Association this and they
seem happy enough with that at the moment.
``I would have hoped, though, that we would not be getting into this situation.
I'm disappointed to hear that Ray has decided to take this action and I
certainly don't want to further inflame the situation.
``Until such time as we have heard from David it would be wrong of the union to
prejudice the situation.''
Edinburgh Academicals' media spokesman Magnus Moodie, another Edinburgh laywer,
said last night: ``David still has our complete confidence and we wish that
third parties would not interfere while it is being handled by the SRU. If this
had happened to one of Ray Megson's clients then I am sure he would have been
up in arms protesting about interference with due process.''
q Brian Meek tackles Jim Telfer - Page 30
</TEXT>
