<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Celtic's stand given a pass</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC Football Club yesterday received planning permission for a temporary
stand which has already been built on the site of the former west terracing at
Celtic Park.
The planning consent, awarded by district councillors, will run until June
1997, if a safety certificate is granted today by Strathclyde region's sub
committee on safety at sports grounds.
A district council sub-committee on development control was asked to consider
``a proposal'' for the erection of temporary uncovered spectators' seated
accommodation, with a capacity of 2955.
Celtic had indicated it wished the temporary structure to be used for the
remainder of the current football season.
However, in order to accommodate any possible delays in the phased
redevelopment of Celtic Park, the club had requested that planning permission
be granted for a temporary period up to June 1997.
The sub-committee, chaired by Councillor Robert Rooney - who asked if the
application was retrospective and was told that it was - was told by an
official that, although it was retrospective, the stand was not being used.
Celtic wanted to use the stand several weeks ago to satisfy ticket demand for
the European Cup Winners' Cup tie with Paris St Germain, but were denied a
safety certificate.
On the nature of the application, Celtic public relations officer Peter McLean
said: ``Our consultants contacted the appropriate authorities and asked if it
would be acceptable for Celtic to proceed with building in advance of receiving
permisson, considering the nature of the construction.
``They were told this was quite common practice, although they could give no
guarantee that the stand would be given planning permission.''
</TEXT>
