<DOCNO>GH951206-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Army raises flag in Jaffna</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colombo, Tuesday
TAMIL Tiger rebels launched an attack on an eastern military base in Sri Lanka
today after the army raised the national flag over the rebels' former northern
stronghold of Jaffna.
The rebels tried to ram a van packed with explosives into a Special Task Force
police camp near Kalmunai in the Batticaloa district, but it blew up at the
gate killing a sentry and police commandos inflicted heavy casualties on
guerrillas.
Before the attack, Sri Lanka's armed forces raised the national flag over the
captured rebel stronghold of Jaffna, symbolically ending nearly a decade of
control over the town by the Tigers.
The Tigers, who have not admitted the fall of its citadel, said they were
continuing to fight. Their Voice of Tigers radio announced a major recruitment
drive and urged people to enlist to stop the army ``before it was too late''.
The flag-raising ceremony capped the government's seven-week offensive on
Jaffna, the army's biggest assault in 12 years of civil war.
An estimated 400 soldiers were killed in seven weeks of fighting, while the
military says its troops killed 1925 rebels and wounded more than 5000 on the
march towards the rebel citadel.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bottom-club Kilmarnock have Pittodrie mission Totten wants his side to start going up in the world</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE was once very much involved in Rangers matters, but Alex Totten will be one
of a considerable minority who will be far more concerned with the happenings
at Pittodrie tonight than the fate of the Ibrox club in Dortmund. The
Kilmarnock manager has travelled a fair distance in his career since he was
assistant to Jock Wallace, but is still regarded as one of the country's best
tacticians.
His team have had a hesitant opening period in the premier division, so
uncertain, in fact, that they are currently at the bottom, but Totten has
demonstrated on more than one occasion that he has the mettle to overcome this
kind of adversity.
``If we win, we come off the bottom,'' he said, ``and who needs any greater
incentive?''
Aberdeen might argue that securing a victory after having lost immediately
following their Coca-Cola Cup final victory is decent enough incentive for
themselves, especially as they are a long way behind in the title race. In
fact, their manager, Roy Aitken, sees this game as the first of three
opportunities to re-establish his team's position as formidable opponents at
Pittodrie.
Aitken, who has seen his side win only one of their last seven league games, is
aiming to recreate the same intimidating scenario at home as used to be the
norm in the eighties, to resurrect their championship hopes.
Said the manager, who has three home matches in succession beginning tonight:
``We are determined to become a force again at Pittodrie just like a decade ago.
``Then teams knew they would be in for a hard game here, but if they are coming
up confident then there is something wrong. The only way we will gain respect
is by doing the business on the park.
``We have played well before our own fans without getting the right results. I
am looking for my players to be more ruthless and push themselves harder to
turn performances into the wins we want.
``This is our first game at Pittodrie since winning the Coca-Cola Cup. Our
supporters will be out in their thousands to give us the lift needed going into
a vital period.''
Sweeper Gary Smith will be captain in the absence of the suspended Stewart
McKimmie. Dean Windass, the #700,000 buy from Hull City, will make his home
debut.
Stephen Glass and Eoin Jess have recovered from injuries but internationalist
Scott Booth is again ruled out with a thigh strain.
Totten recognises the threat an Aberdeen side aiming to avoid three successive
defeats will pose, but he has to take a positive approach.
``We have played well in a lot of games but not got the results we deserved,''
he said, ``and we did well against Aberdeen last season. In fact we won four
out of four but they have already beaten us this season.
``We showed for 40 minutes at Parkhead that we can be as good as anyone, but we
have to maintain our concentration all the way through.''
The Rugby Park lot will have much the same line-up as the one that took a
two-goal lead at Parkhead before being caught and passed.
q FIFA have announced that the draw for the qualifying competition of the 1998
World Cup would go ahead in Paris next week despite the wave of strikes in
France.
Football's governing body issued a statement yesterday stating the draw would
take place as scheduled at the Louvre on Tuesday amid fears the strikes could
cause a postponement.
q DUNDEE United have transferred the Brazilian, Sergio, to Kuwait Sporting Club
for an undisclosed fee. The striker was signed at the start of the year in a
#300,000 deal from Portuguese football.
q RAITH Rovers will find out next week how much they will receive for Jason
Rowbotham. The defender moved to Wycombe Wanderers under freedom of contract,
and the clubs have been unable to agree a fee.
q BERWICK were last night in signing talks with former Meadowbank keeper Jim
McQueen after he came to their rescue on Saturday. McQueen, who has just
completed a three-month deal with Clyde, stepped in for Berwick in their one
goal defeat by East Fife.
Berwick manager Tom Hendrie got in touch with McQueen after having received
news that keeper Neil Young had been involved in a car accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
