<DOCNO>GH951206-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Transformation at Triplex Lloyd</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE has been a major transformation at Triplex Lloyd over the last two years.
In the half year to September, operating profit jumped 57% to #5.92m and if a
goodwill write-off which is a non-cash item is ignored, then the uplift at the
pre-tax level was 91%.
The impetus came from the power division, where margins jumped from 5.1% to
8.5%. That reflected the elimination of #600,000 losses at Firth Vickers.
Also helping were good performances from Deritend and the Paralloy subsidiary.
Automotive benefited from high sales to Perkins.
However, the performance was partially spoilt by maintenance problems in the
summer, but chairman Colin Cooke was unable to say how much these cost. He
bought 35,000 shares yesterday.
The current half will benefit from the #5m sale of part of the Birmingham
property, which could release a #1m profit.
Full-year profit seems likely to improve from #8.3m to almost #11m. That would
leave the shares at 143p trading at 11 times possible earnings, while yielding
6.1% on the basis of a maintained 7p total dividend.
</TEXT>
