<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Howard wins a major legal victory</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028377</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOME Secretary Michael Howard won a major legal victory yesterday when the
Court of Appeal vindicated his decision to increase the minimum period a double
killer must spend in prison.
Three appeal judges overturned a landmark decision in the High Court last month
when Mr Justice Turner strongly criticised the Home Secretary and said he had
wrongly agreed to increase the term from 15 to 20 years.
John Pierson, who shot his sleeping mother and father at their remote farmhouse
near Oswestry, Shropshire, in September 1984, received a double life sentence
for the killings, described as ``horrifying and apparently motiveless''.
The trial judge and the then Lord Chief Justice, Lord Lane, recommended that
the ``tariff'' Pierson must serve for retribution and deterrence should be set
at 15 years.
However, Pierson, who protested his innocence at his trial at Chester Crown
Court in July 1985, was told in August 1993 that the Home Secretary had
increased his minimum sentence to 20 years.
Pierson successfully challenged in the High Court Mr Howard's decision in May
last year that the 20-year tariff should stand. Mr Justice Turner said the Home
Secretary had ``failed to measure up to the required standard of fairness''.
That judgment was hailed as a landmark ruling because of its apparent impact on
many other cases in which Mr Howard had increased minimum sentences for lifers.
Yesterday, Sir Thomas Bingham, the Master of the Rolls, together with Lord
Justice Neill and Lord Justice Hirst, set aside Mr Justice Turner's ruling and
said that the Home Secretary's decision to increase the sentence could not be
``stigmatised as irrational''.
The appeal judges stressed in their judgment that they were not concerned
whether Pierson should serve 15 or 20 years and they had no part to play in
making that decision.
``It is none of our business and we have no views on the subject. Nor are we in
any way called upon to consider the allocation of sentencing powers between the
executive and the judiciary. That again is none of our business.
``We are concerned, and concerned only, to rule upon the lawfulness of the
decision.''
They also made clear that the case was not a challenge to the Home Secretary
personally.
Mr Justice Turner had held that ``exceptional circumstances'' would be needed
before the Home Secretary could increase a period of imprisonment and said it
would be unfair to lengthen Pierson's term.
Yesterday's judgment said: ``The Home Secretary in 1994 did not share the view
of his predecessor in 1988 that the 15-year penal term recommended by the
judges would have been appropriate but for the aggravating features. He thought
a longer term was called for anyway.
``The existence of an earlier decision with which the Home Secretary in 1994
did not agree did not in our judgment make his later decision irrational,
whether or not that decision is open to challenge on other grounds.''
The judges said the Home Secretary had done no more than indicate that the
power to increase a penal term would be exercised only in exceptional
circumstances.
They said that there was nothing in law to stop a Home Secretary from
increasing a sentence if he believed it did not adequately meet the needs of
retribution and deterrence.
The judges also said that it was open for Pierson to make representations to
the Home Secretary and they trusted Mr Howard would give ``fair and careful
consideration'' to any pleas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Estate council hailed as a role model</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975028378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTHE community voice of Wester Hailes, on the west side of Edinburgh, was
commended yesterday as a role model in the regeneration of Britain's worst
housing estates.
In a strategy devised by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, the estate's
representative council is praised as a ``good example'' of how local people can
find an important voice in their neighbourhood - and a say in the redevelopment
of their area.
By working in partnership with other agencies, the area's representative
council has participated in the redevelopment of the sprawling housing estate,
which boasts one of the highest unemployment rates in the capital.
A foundation spokesman said the Wester Hailes group had been singled out
because residents could easily have a say in their future.
``The Wester Hailes Representative Council is a good example to other estates
all over the UK of how local people can work in partnership to improve their
community,'' a foundation spokesman said.
The estate forms part of a #1.5m research programme, focusing on 100 of the
poorest housing estates in Britain in a bid to devise a 20-year strategy for
refurbishment.
It is the only Scottish area to be featured in a video accompanying the plan,
which was launched in London yesterday.
The report's author, Ms Marilyn Taylor, of the University of Brighton, said a
national initiative was needed to counteract low income, unemployment, and
increasing demand on welfare services which have hampered previous programmes.
The call for an action plan for Britain's most deprived housing estates was
backed yesterday by the chairwoman of the Wester Hailes council. The council,
which speaks for its 11,000 residents, was set up in 1982 from a former
tenants' association.
A decade later, it was restructured to increase accountability to the people it
represented.
Chairwoman Lynne Main said it was changed to take 27 representatives from local
neighbourhood forums. Its aims and intentions were formerly stated in the
so-called Pitlochry declaration, a short time before the partnership initiative
for the area swung into action.
The council has battled for many of the changes on the estate but says much
remains to be tackled to overcome poverty and unemployment. Unemployment is
running at an average of just less than 20% - double the figure for Edinburgh
as a whole.
Ms Main, 38, who has lived in Wester Hailes for 26 years, said the group
realised at an early stage it had to get people involved in order to be
successful.
``The only real way to get people involved in any great initiative is to speak
to them face to face,'' Ms Main said. ``People tend not to take notice of
leaflets or information.
She attributes the success of the council to ``elected democracy'' and a
sophisticated consultation process.
With a #500,000 funding package from urban aid, the Scottish Office, and local
authorities, the council is also able to access vital professional training and
information, enabling it to argue its case on a par with professionals in local
authorities and the Wester Hailes Partnership.
``Each door in Wester Hailes is knocked at least once every year,'' Ms Main
said. ``Neighbourhoods are regularly surveyed to find out what they want. We
decide what the issues affecting us are and elect a spokesperson.''
Welcoming the Rowntree recommendation, she said: ``I think that all the talk
from the Government about community involvement addressing decision-making is
very encouraging reading. We've been doing that for 20 years in Wester Hailes,
where we've been trying to get more control of budgets and decision making and
get local people involved.
``You must get the community involved. It does not spring up overnight. It
takes much hard work and commitment and a lot of money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951206-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951206-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951206</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975028379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Whitbread leisure and brewing group has made a highly imaginative move with
the plan to develop the former Greater London Council building at Westminster
into a Travel Inn budget hotel with some 318 bedrooms.
That will be aimed chiefly at Eurostar passengers using the nearby Waterloo
Eurostar terminus. Also on the County Hall site, it will develop a 200 room
four-star Marriott hotel. Together they will cost some #30m.
This will be in co-operation with the Shirayama Corporation of Japan which
bought the redundant building for #60m in 1992.
